{"title_page": "Georgia Groome", "text_new": "\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Georgia Groome\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1992|02|11|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Nottingham]], [[Nottinghamshire]], [[England]]\n| occupation         = Actress\n| alma_mater         = [[Trent College]]\n| years_active       = 2001\u2013present\n| partner            = [[Rupert Grint]] (2011\u2013present)\n}}\n\n'''Georgia Groome''' is an English actress. She is best known for her roles in ''[[London to Brighton]]'' (2006) and ''[[Angus, Thongs and Perfect Snogging]]'' (2008).\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nGroome was born on 11 February 1992<ref name=\"LoveFilm\" /> in [[Nottingham]],<ref name=\"littlewhitelies.co.uk\">{{cite web | url = http://www.littlewhitelies.co.uk/interviews/georgia-groome-interview-405 | title = Georgia Groome interview | publisher = littlewhitelies.co.uk |access-date=<!--Last from live site 3 December 2011-->20 January 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120517021045/http://www.littlewhitelies.co.uk/interviews/georgia-groome-interview-405 | archive-date=17 May 2012}}</ref> the daughter of Paul Groome, a [[publican]] and [[chef]] who died in 2009, and Fiona (n\u00e9e Tulloch), a drama and vocal coach.{{cn|date=February 2020}} She resided in [[Chellaston]] near [[Shelton Lock]], [[Derbyshire]].{{cn|date=February 2020}} Groome, at the age of nine, auditioned for a role in the touring stage version of the musical ''[[Annie Get Your Gun (musical)|Annie Get Your Gun]]'' and got the part.{{cn|date=February 2020}} She trained at Nottingham Television Workshop, Derby Youth Theatre. and [[Trent College]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.thisisderbyshire.co.uk/s-year-ghosts-exams-erupting-volcanoes-Georgia/story-11587043-detail/story.html | title = It's a year of ghosts, exams and erupting volcanoes for Georgia | publisher = thisisderbyshire.co.uk | accessdate =3 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAfter her acting debut in the TV film, ''A Fish Out of Water'' in 2001, Groome appeared in an episode of the short-lived TV series, ''Dangerville'', playing an orphan.\n\nWhen Groome was just 14 years old, she landed her first feature film role in the well-received British independent film ''[[London to Brighton]]'' in 2006, playing an 11-year-old runaway.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/nottingham/content/articles/2006/11/13/alastair_clark_georgia_groome_feature.shtml | title = From Nottingham to London to Brighton |publisher=BBC | accessdate =3 December 2011}}</ref> That year she was also one of the eight young adventurers on ''[[Serious (TV series)|Serious Amazon]]'' for [[CBBC]].<ref name=\"new\">[http://www.bbc.co.uk/newtalent/under_16/success_amazon.shtml BBC New Talent \u2013 Serious Amazon], ''[[BBC]]'' (9 July 2005)</ref> In 2007, Groome had a role in Elaine Wickham's short, ''My Mother''.\n\nIn 2008, Groome had a minor role in comedy, horror ''[[The Cottage (film)|The Cottage]]''. Her breakthrough role was as 14-year-old, boyfriend-searching Georgia Nicolson alongside [[Aaron Taylor-Johnson|Aaron Johnson]] in the 2008 film ''[[Angus, Thongs and Perfect Snogging]]'', for which she won the award for Best Child Actor at the Buster International Children's Film Festival.<ref name=\"LoveFilm\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20120403022821/http://www.lovefilm.com/browse/contributor/100361/Georgia-Groome.html Georgia Groome], ''[[LoveFilm]]''</ref> She also had a minor role in horror film ''[[The Disappeared (2009 film)|The Disappeared]]''.\n\nIn 2009, she made her stage debut in ''Tusk Tusk'', a new play by [[Polly Stenham]] at the [[Royal Court Theatre]] in London.<ref name=LoveFilm /><ref>[http://www.thejc.com/arts/theatre-reviews/review-tusk-tusk \"Review: Tusk Tusk\"], ''[[The Jewish Chronicle]]''</ref> The same year, she appeared in the short ''Leaving Eva'' and an episode of ''[[The Bill]]''. In 2010, Groome appeared in an episode of [[British television]] detective drama ''[[Lewis (TV series)|Lewis]]'', as well as the short ''Silent Things''.\n\nIn 2011, Groome starred in two shorts, ''The True Meaning of Love''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dual-reality.co.uk/tmol/ |title=The True Meaning of Love |publisher=dual-reality.co.uk |accessdate=3 December 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111130180516/http://www.dual-reality.co.uk/tmol/ |archivedate=30 November 2011  }}</ref> and ''Six Degrees''. She also appeared in Susan Jacobson's ''[[The Holding]]''<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.leftlion.co.uk/articles.cfm/title/the-holding-/id/3889 | title = The Holding | publisher = leftlion.co.uk | accessdate =3 December 2011}}</ref> and had a lead role in ''[[The Great Ghost Rescue (film)|The Great Ghost Rescue]]'', a film adaptation of [[Eva Ibbotson]]'s [[The Great Ghost Rescue|book of the same name]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.empireonline.com/news/feed.asp?NID=27885 | title = New Pics Of The Great Ghost Rescue |work=Empire  | accessdate =3 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nShe appeared alongside [[Stephen Dillane]] in ''[[Papadopoulos & Sons]]'', in which she played snobby fashion victim Katie. The film was released in the UK through Cineworld on 5 April 2013.\n\n== Personal life ==\nGroome has been in a relationship with [[Rupert Grint]] since 2011.<ref>[https://www.standard.co.uk/showbiz/celebrity-news/snatch-star-rupert-grint-ill-always-be-ron-and-thats-ok-a3958716.html ''Snatch star Rupert Grint: I'll always be Ron - and that's OK''], [[Evening Standard]], 10 October 2018</ref> On 10 April 2020, it was announced that Grint and Groome were expecting their first child.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elle.com/culture/celebrities/a32111407/who-is-georgia-groome-rupert-grint-girlfriend/|title=All About Georgia Groome, Rupert Grint's Longtime Girlfriend|last=Penrose|first=Nerisha|date=2020-04-10|website=ELLE|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/lifestyle/rupert-grint-girlfriend-georgia-groome-215900616.html|title=Rupert Grint and His Girlfriend Georgia Groome Are Expecting Their First Child|website=www.yahoo.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Film\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[London to Brighton]]''\n| Joanne\n| Film debut\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''My Mother''\n| Millie\n|\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[The Cottage (film)|The Cottage]]''\n| Farmer's Daughter 1\n|\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Angus, Thongs and Perfect Snogging]]''\n| Georgia Nicolson\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[The Disappeared (2009 film)|The Disappeared]]''\n| Sophie Pryor\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''Leaving Eva''\n| Kiera\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''Silent Things''\n| Amy\n| Short film\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''The True Meaning of Love''\n| Alice\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''Six Degrees''\n| Young Girl\n| Short film\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[The Holding]]''\n| Gemma\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[The Great Ghost Rescue (film)|The Great Ghost Rescue]]''\n| Winifred\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Papadopoulos & Sons]]''\n| Katie Papadopoulos\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''Life In Orbit''\n| Laura\n| Short film\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''Double Date''\n| Lulu\n|\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''A Fish Out of Water''\n| Jenny\n| TV film\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''Dangerville''\n| Orphan Episode 1\n| Episode: \"Robots\"\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Serious (TV series)|Serious Amazon]]''\n| Herself\n|\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Loose Women]]''\n| Herself\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[The Bill]]''\n| Paige Farrelly\n| Episode: \"Powerless\"\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Lewis (TV series)|Lewis]]''\n| Briony Grahame\n| Episode: \"The Dead of Winter\"\n|-\n| 2013\u201315\n| ''[[Up the Women]]''\n| Emily\n|\n|}\n\n===Radio===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''Maidens' Trip''\n| Nanette\n| BBC Radio 4 Afternoon Play, broadcast 8 October 2010\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''The Warrah''\n| Amy\n| BBC Radio 4 [[From Fact to Fiction]], broadcast 18 February 2012\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01pzwgz The Cazalets]''\n| Clary\n| BBC Radio 4 15 Minute Drama, broadcast 1\u201311 January 2013\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''The Tunnel''\n| Chloe\n| BBC Radio 4 Drama, broadcast 12 August 2016\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Northanger Abbey]]''\n| Catherine Morland\n| BBC Radio 4 Drama, broadcast December 2016\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[The Mysteries of Udolpho]]''\n| Emily\n| BBC Radio 4 Drama, broadcast December 2016\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[The Diary of a Young Girl]]''\n| Anne Frank\n| BBC Radio 4 Book of the Week reading, broadcast May 2019\n|}\n\n===Theatre===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|2009\n|''Tusk Tusk''\n|\n|Royal Court Theatre\n|-\n|2013\n|''Tutto Bene, Mamma?''\n|Boy\n|[[The Print Room]]\n|-\n|2016\n|''Clickbait''\n|Nicola\n|[[Theatre503]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|2102872}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Groome, Georgia}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's College London]]\n[[Category:21st-century English actresses]]\n[[Category:English child actresses]]\n[[Category:English film actresses]]\n[[Category:People from Nottingham]]\n[[Category:English television actresses]]\n[[Category:English radio actresses]]\n[[Category:People educated at Trent College]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Nottinghamshire]]\n[[Category:Participants in British reality television series]]\n[[Category:People from Chellaston]]\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n", "text_old": "\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Georgia Groome\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1992|02|11|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Nottingham]], [[Nottinghamshire]], [[England]]\n| occupation         = Actress\n| alma_mater         = [[Trent College]]\n| years_active       = 2001\u2013present\n| partner            = [[Rupert Grint]] (2011\u2013present)\n}}\n\n'''Georgia Groome''' is an English actress. She is best known for her roles in ''[[London to Brighton]]'' (2006) and ''[[Angus, Thongs and Perfect Snogging]]'' (2008).\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nGroome was born on 11 February 1992<ref name=\"LoveFilm\" /> in [[Nottingham]],<ref name=\"littlewhitelies.co.uk\">{{cite web | url = http://www.littlewhitelies.co.uk/interviews/georgia-groome-interview-405 | title = Georgia Groome interview | publisher = littlewhitelies.co.uk |access-date=<!--Last from live site 3 December 2011-->20 January 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120517021045/http://www.littlewhitelies.co.uk/interviews/georgia-groome-interview-405 | archive-date=17 May 2012}}</ref> the daughter of Paul Groome, a [[publican]] and [[chef]] who died in 2009, and Fiona (n\u00e9e Tulloch), a drama and vocal coach.{{cn|date=February 2020}} She resided in [[Chellaston]] near [[Shelton Lock]], [[Derbyshire]].{{cn|date=February 2020}} Groome, at the age of nine, auditioned for a role in the touring stage version of the musical ''[[Annie Get Your Gun (musical)|Annie Get Your Gun]]'' and got the part.{{cn|date=February 2020}} She trained at Nottingham Television Workshop, Derby Youth Theatre. and [[Trent College]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.thisisderbyshire.co.uk/s-year-ghosts-exams-erupting-volcanoes-Georgia/story-11587043-detail/story.html | title = It's a year of ghosts, exams and erupting volcanoes for Georgia | publisher = thisisderbyshire.co.uk | accessdate =3 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAfter her acting debut in the TV film, ''A Fish Out of Water'' in 2001, Groome appeared in an episode of the short-lived TV series, ''Dangerville'', playing an orphan.\n\nWhen Groome was just 14 years old, she landed her first feature film role in the well-received British independent film ''[[London to Brighton]]'' in 2006, playing an 11-year-old runaway.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/nottingham/content/articles/2006/11/13/alastair_clark_georgia_groome_feature.shtml | title = From Nottingham to London to Brighton |publisher=BBC | accessdate =3 December 2011}}</ref> That year she was also one of the eight young adventurers on ''[[Serious (TV series)|Serious Amazon]]'' for [[CBBC]].<ref name=\"new\">[http://www.bbc.co.uk/newtalent/under_16/success_amazon.shtml BBC New Talent \u2013 Serious Amazon], ''[[BBC]]'' (9 July 2005)</ref> In 2007 Groome had a role in Elaine Wickham's short, ''My Mother''.\n\nIn 2008, Groome had a minor role in comedy, horror ''[[The Cottage (film)|The Cottage]]''. Her breakthrough role was as 14-year-old, boyfriend-searching Georgia Nicolson alongside [[Aaron Taylor-Johnson|Aaron Johnson]] in the 2008 film ''[[Angus, Thongs and Perfect Snogging]]'', for which she won the award for Best Child Actor at the Buster International Children's Film Festival.<ref name=\"LoveFilm\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20120403022821/http://www.lovefilm.com/browse/contributor/100361/Georgia-Groome.html Georgia Groome], ''[[LoveFilm]]''</ref> She also had a minor role in horror film ''[[The Disappeared (2009 film)|The Disappeared]]''.\n\nIn 2009, she made her stage debut in ''Tusk Tusk'', a new play by [[Polly Stenham]] at the [[Royal Court Theatre]] in London.<ref name=LoveFilm /><ref>[http://www.thejc.com/arts/theatre-reviews/review-tusk-tusk \"Review: Tusk Tusk\"], ''[[The Jewish Chronicle]]''</ref> The same year, she appeared in the short ''Leaving Eva'' and an episode of ''[[The Bill]]''. In 2010, Groome appeared in an episode of [[British television]] detective drama ''[[Lewis (TV series)|Lewis]]'', as well as the short ''Silent Things''.\n\nIn 2011, Groome starred in two shorts, ''The True Meaning of Love''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dual-reality.co.uk/tmol/ |title=The True Meaning of Love |publisher=dual-reality.co.uk |accessdate=3 December 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111130180516/http://www.dual-reality.co.uk/tmol/ |archivedate=30 November 2011  }}</ref> and ''Six Degrees''. She also appeared in Susan Jacobson's ''[[The Holding]]''<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.leftlion.co.uk/articles.cfm/title/the-holding-/id/3889 | title = The Holding | publisher = leftlion.co.uk | accessdate =3 December 2011}}</ref> and had a lead role in ''[[The Great Ghost Rescue (film)|The Great Ghost Rescue]]'', a film adaptation of [[Eva Ibbotson]]'s [[The Great Ghost Rescue|book of the same name]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.empireonline.com/news/feed.asp?NID=27885 | title = New Pics Of The Great Ghost Rescue |work=Empire  | accessdate =3 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nShe appeared alongside [[Stephen Dillane]] in ''[[Papadopoulos & Sons]]'', in which she played snobby fashion victim Katie. The film was released in the UK through Cineworld on 5 April 2013.\n\n== Personal life ==\nGroome has been in a relationship with [[Rupert Grint]] since 2011.<ref>[https://www.standard.co.uk/showbiz/celebrity-news/snatch-star-rupert-grint-ill-always-be-ron-and-thats-ok-a3958716.html ''Snatch star Rupert Grint: I'll always be Ron - and that's OK''], [[Evening Standard]], 10 October 2018</ref> On April 10, 2020, it was announced that Grint and Groome were expecting their first child.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elle.com/culture/celebrities/a32111407/who-is-georgia-groome-rupert-grint-girlfriend/|title=All About Georgia Groome, Rupert Grint's Longtime Girlfriend|last=Penrose|first=Nerisha|date=2020-04-10|website=ELLE|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/lifestyle/rupert-grint-girlfriend-georgia-groome-215900616.html|title=Rupert Grint and His Girlfriend Georgia Groome Are Expecting Their First Child|website=www.yahoo.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n