2016|accessdate=16 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161105185346/http://wtkr.com/2016/09/22/navy-sailor-dies-while-deployed-on-norfolk-based-uss-wasp/|archive-date=5 November 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|casualties2= 2,500 killed<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.libyaobserver.ly/news/al-ghasri-2500-radicals-were-killed-sirte-battle|title=Al-Ghasri: 2500 IS radicals were killed in Sirte battle|publisher=Libya Observer|date=19 December 2016|accessdate=11 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220235956/https://www.libyaobserver.ly/news/al-ghasri-2500-radicals-were-killed-sirte-battle|archive-date=20 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> and 87+ captured<ref>15 captured (12 May\u201331 Aug.),[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-idUSKCN1162RO] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190624184302/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-idUSKCN1162RO |date=2019-06-24}} 2 captured (12 Oct.),[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-sirte-idUSKCN12A11X] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170706045602/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-sirte-idUSKCN12A11X |date=2017-07-06}} 14 captured (21\u201322 Nov.),[https://www.reuters.com/article/libya-security-sirte-idINKBN13H14R] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170629024232/http://www.reuters.com/article/libya-security-sirte-idINKBN13H14R |date=2017-06-29}} 13 captured (3\u20134 Dec.),[https://www.alaraby.co.uk/english/news/2016/12/4/cornered-is-militants-try-to-swim-out-of-sirte] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161206141817/https://www.alaraby.co.uk/english/news/2016/12/4/cornered-is-militants-try-to-swim-out-of-sirte |date=2016-12-06}}[https://www.middleeastmonitor.com/20161204-libyan-forces-suspend-anti-daesh-campaign-in-sirte/] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161205130854/https://www.middleeastmonitor.com/20161204-libyan-forces-suspend-anti-daesh-campaign-in-sirte/ |date=2016-12-05}} 34 captured (5 Dec.),[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-sirte-idUSKBN13U1H4] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170723015434/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-sirte-idUSKBN13U1H4 |date=2017-07-23}} 9 captured (6 Dec.),[http://www.defense.gov/News/Article/Article/1023267/dod-update-on-counter-isil-fight-in-iraq-mosul-is-surrounded] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161208190846/http://www.defense.gov/News/Article/Article/1023267/dod-update-on-counter-isil-fight-in-iraq-mosul-is-surrounded |date=2016-12-08}} total of 87 reported captured</ref> ({{small|GNA claim}})\n|casualties3= 37 civilians killed by air-strikes<ref>[https://www.thedailybeast.com/the-last-days-of-isis-libya-stronghold?source=articles&via=rss The Last Days of ISIS\u2019 Libya Stronghold]</ref><br />35,000 people displaced<br />(as of July 2016)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sputniknews.com/world/201608041043923181-libya-un-sirte-refugees/|title=UN Monitors Refugee Situation Amid Anti-Daesh Campaign in Sirte, Libya|work=Sputnik International|access-date=2016-12-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161224164219/https://sputniknews.com/world/201608041043923181-libya-un-sirte-refugees/|archive-date=2016-12-24|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|notes= \n|campaignbox= {{Campaignbox 2014 Libyan Civil War}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Battle of Sirte (2016)''' started in the spring of 2016, in the [[Sirte District]], [[Libya]], between the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] (ISIL) and the [[Libyan Army|loyalist forces]] of the [[Government of National Accord]] (GNA) backed by [[United States of America]]. ISIL forces had captured Sirte one year earlier, during [[Battle of Sirte (2015)|the previous battle]]. The conflict for Sirte was described as ISIL's \"[[last stand]]\" in Libya.<ref name=\"last stand\"/>\n\nThe latter portion of this battle was concurrent with the [[Battle of Mosul (2016\u201317)]] in [[Iraq]], the [[Battle of al-Bab]] in northern [[Syria]], and the [[Raqqa campaign (2016\u20132017)]] by the [[Syrian Democratic Forces]], on ISIL's de facto capital in [[Syria]].\n\n== The offensive ==\n=== GNA advance on Sirte, initial gains, and stalemate ===\nThe offensive on Sirte launched on 12 May 2016,<ref name=\"freed\"/> under the name \u201cAl-Bunyan Al-Marsoos,\u201d variously translated as \"Impenetrable Wall\" or \"Solid Foundation.\"<ref name=\"GNAvsISIS\"/> Fighting took place east of Assdada, around 80&nbsp;km (50 miles) south of [[Misrata]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSKCN0Y31KS|title=Islamic State kills four Libyan security personnel near Misrata: medics|date=12 May 2016}}</ref> On 16 May, GNA military forces recaptured [[Abu Qurayn|Abu Grein]] from ISIL militants.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.libyaherald.com/2016/05/16/misratans-report-they-have-recaptured-abu-grein-from-is/|work=Libya Herald|title=Misratans report they have recaptured Abu Grain from IS|access-date=16 May 2016|date=16 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160531030305/https://www.libyaherald.com/2016/05/16/misratans-report-they-have-recaptured-abu-grein-from-is/|archive-date=31 May 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The next day, the GNA took control over the al-Wishkah district, 25&nbsp;km from Abu Grein.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.libyanexpress.com/misurata-forces-put-grip-on-al-wishkah-district-25-km-from-abu-grein/|work=Libyan Express|title=Misurata forces put grip on Al-Wishkah district, 25 km from Abu Grein|access-date=17 May 2016|date=17 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012055255/http://www.libyanexpress.com/misurata-forces-put-grip-on-al-wishkah-district-25-km-from-abu-grein/|archive-date=12 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and eventually reached nearly 50 kilometers from Sirte.<ref name=\"GNAvsISIS\">{{cite web|url=https://www.libyangazette.net/2016/05/17/libyan-troops-clash-with-isis-militants-leaving-6-dead-and-17-injured/|work=Libyan Gazette|title=Libyan Troops Clash With ISIS Militants Leaving 6 Dead and 17 Injured|access-date=17 May 2016|date=17 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160601164546/https://www.libyangazette.net/2016/05/17/libyan-troops-clash-with-isis-militants-leaving-6-dead-and-17-injured/|archive-date=2016-06-01|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 May, an ISIL suicide bomber attacked GNA forces, 90 kilometers west of Sirte, killing 30 soldiers and wounding 50.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/daesh-bombing-kills-30-soldiers-near-libya-s-sirte/574869|title=Daesh bombing kills 30 soldiers near Libya\u2019s Sirte|publisher=|accessdate=24 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160629194348/http://aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/daesh-bombing-kills-30-soldiers-near-libya-s-sirte/574869|archive-date=29 June 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> In late May, pro-GNA military forces seized many locations near the city of Sirte from ISIL, including the Sirte power station, and advanced on the town of Jarif to the south of Sirte.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.libyaherald.com/2016/05/29/misratans-say-they-have-taken-sirte-power-station/|title=Misratans say they have taken Sirte power station|website=libyaherald.com|access-date=2016-05-31|date=2016-05-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160611034820/https://www.libyaherald.com/2016/05/29/misratans-say-they-have-taken-sirte-power-station/|archive-date=2016-06-11|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.libyanexpress.com/misurata-forces-advance-to-southern-sirte/|title=Misurata forces advance to southern Sirte|website=libyaherald.com|access-date=2016-05-31|date=2016-05-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160803165508/http://www.libyanexpress.com/misurata-forces-advance-to-southern-sirte/|archive-date=2016-08-03|url-status=live}}</ref> Also in late May, the eastern front of Sirte saw action. The Petroleum Facilities Guard (PFG) captured the towns of Bin Jawad and Noufiliyah from ISIL.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-idUSKCN0YL1V0|title=Libyan security forces pushing Islamic State back from vicinity of oil terminals|website=www.reuters.com|access-date=2016-05-31|date=2016-05-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180628152951/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-idUSKCN0YL1V0|archive-date=2018-06-28|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 June, GNA forces captured the [[Ghardabiya Air Base]], 10\u201320 kilometers south of Sirte's center.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.almasdarnews.com/article/libyan-forces-liberate-key-airport-near-isis-controlled-sirte/|title=Libyan Forces liberate key airport near ISIS controlled Sirte|first=Leith|last=Fadel|date=5 June 2016|publisher=|accessdate=24 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160605123225/https://www.almasdarnews.com/article/libyan-forces-liberate-key-airport-near-isis-controlled-sirte/|archive-date=5 June 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-idUSKCN0YQ0TA|title=Libyan brigades capture air base from Islamic State south of Sirte: spokesman|date=4 June 2016|publisher=|accessdate=24 June 2016|via=Reuters|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160611185016/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-idUSKCN0YQ0TA|archive-date=11 June 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> However, ISIL recaptured the air base the following day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.almasdarnews.com/article/isis-retakes-air-base-near-sirte-clashing-libyan-troops/|title=ISIS retakes air base near Sirte after clashing with Libyan troops|first=Chris|last=Tomson|date=7 June 2016|publisher=|accessdate=24 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160614134021/https://www.almasdarnews.com/article/isis-retakes-air-base-near-sirte-clashing-libyan-troops/|archive-date=14 June 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 June, GNA fighters entered Sirte for the first time after capturing a bridge on the city's western outskirts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.almasdarnews.com/article/libyan-soldiers-enter-isis-stronghold-sirte/|title=ISIS on the verge of losing its Libyan capital after government troops storm Sirte|first=Chris|last=Tomson|date=8 June 2016|publisher=|accessdate=24 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160608220327/https://www.almasdarnews.com/article/libyan-soldiers-enter-isis-stronghold-sirte/|archive-date=8 June 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The next day, fighting was concentrated near the Ouagadougou conference hall, where ISIL held religious instruction sessions,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.almasdarnews.com/article/fierce-clashes-rage-sirte-islamic-state-clings-libyan-capital/|title=Fierce clashes rage in Sirte as the Islamic State clings on to its Libyan capital|first=News|last=Desk|date=9 June 2016|publisher=|accessdate=24 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160622200508/https://www.almasdarnews.com/article/fierce-clashes-rage-sirte-islamic-state-clings-libyan-capital/|archive-date=22 June 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> and GNA forces managed to surround the hall.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-06-10/libyan-forces-enter-sirte-as-islamic-state-resistance-weakens|title=Libyan Forces Enter Sirte as Islamic State Resistance Weakens|first=Ghaith|last=Shennib|publisher=|accessdate=24 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160616195022/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-06-10/libyan-forces-enter-sirte-as-islamic-state-resistance-weakens|archive-date=16 June 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Meanwhile, some ISIL fighters started retreating from Sirte,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/world/middle-east/isil-fighters-retreat-from-main-bastion-in-libya-shaving-beards-as-they-go|title=ISIL fighters retreat from main bastion in Libya, \u2018shaving beards\u2019 as they go - The National|publisher=|accessdate=24 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160630221602/http://www.thenational.ae/world/middle-east/isil-fighters-retreat-from-main-bastion-in-libya-shaving-beards-as-they-go|archive-date=30 June 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> while PFG forces advanced within 70 kilometers to the east of Sirte and reached the town of Harawa.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://the-japan-news.com/news/article/0003007299 |title=Libyan forces push toward ISIL stronghold of Sirte |access-date=2016-06-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160611142858/http://the-japan-news.com/news/article/0003007299 |archive-date=2016-06-11 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 June, the GNA captured two barracks, a bridge and an intersection in Sirte.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/06/libyan-forces-gains-isil-sirte-160609084405138.html|title=Libyan forces make gains against ISIL in Sirte|publisher=|accessdate=24 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160612080205/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/06/libyan-forces-gains-isil-sirte-160609084405138.html|archive-date=12 June 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> In addition, the [[Libyan Navy]] secured Sirte's coast and blocked potential escape routes for ISIL via the sea.<ref name=\"navy\">{{cite web|url=https://www.almasdarnews.com/article/libyan-navy-asserts-control-isil-controlled-sirte/|title=Libyan Navy asserts control over ISIL-controlled Sirte|first=News|last=Desk|date=10 June 2016|publisher=|accessdate=24 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160622195531/https://www.almasdarnews.com/article/libyan-navy-asserts-control-isil-controlled-sirte/|archive-date=22 June 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The following day, street fighting continued to rage in Sirte and heavy clashes took place around the Ouagadougou complex, with GNA forces hitting with artillery fire ISIL positions around the conference centre.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/libya-pro-govt-forces-enter-stronghold-sirte-spokesman-164127791.html|title=Libya unity forces in street battles with IS in Sirte|publisher=|accessdate=24 June 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> On 12 June, GNA forces secured both Sirte's port, airport<ref name=\"freed\">{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/06/libyan-forces-retake-port-isil-bastion-sirte-160611131347272.html|title=Freed Gaddafi loyalists found dead in Libya's Tripoli|publisher=|accessdate=24 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160628143150/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/06/libyan-forces-retake-port-isil-bastion-sirte-160611131347272.html|archive-date=28 June 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> and a residential area in the east of the city, while fighting was continuing two kilometers from the conference hall.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.almasdarnews.com/article/libyan-forces-retake-sirte-port-isil/|title=Libyan Forces retake Sirte Port from ISIL|first=News|last=Desk|date=12 June 2016|publisher=|accessdate=24 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160622202115/https://www.almasdarnews.com/article/libyan-forces-retake-sirte-port-isil/|archive-date=22 June 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> ISIL fighters in the city retreated into a densely built-up area, with snipers taking up positions against the advancing GNA forces.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/libyan-forces-brace-for-street-battles-against-is-in-sirte/2016/06/12/c7868b2a-3075-11e6-b9d5-3c3063f8332c_story.html|title=IS suicide bombers hit Libyan forces in Sirte, killing 1|publisher=|accessdate=24 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160613112656/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/libyan-forces-brace-for-street-battles-against-is-in-sirte/2016/06/12/c7868b2a-3075-11e6-b9d5-3c3063f8332c_story.html|archive-date=13 June 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> ISIL also started using waves of suicide-bombers to stall approaching GNA forces.<ref name=\"16libyan\"/> Three ISIL suicide car-bombers targeted a field hospital in the west of Sirte, as well as two positions of GNA fighters, including at the Abu Hadi roundabout in the southeast of the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/three-suicide-bombings-target-libya-pro-govt-forces-100950131.html|title=IS suicide bombings target Libya pro-govt forces in Sirte|publisher=|accessdate=24 June 2016|agency=AFP}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 June, the GNA advance in Sirte slowed as they reached the residential areas near the city center. ISIL fighters were holed up in the central and northern part of Sirte and a GNA counter-attack against ISIL positions at the town's main western entrance, after the suicide bombings the previous day, was repelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.middle-east-online.com/english/?id=77323|title=.:Middle East Online:::.|publisher=|accessdate=24 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160618025831/http://www.middle-east-online.com/english/?id=77323|archive-date=18 June 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> On 16 June, a suicide attack at a police station in Abu Grain, at a crossroad between Sirte and Misrata, killed 10 soldiers and wounded 7. Also, a six-man GNA scouting team in Sirte was killed and their bodies paraded by ISIL.<ref name=\"16libyan\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/10-killed-in-suicide-attack-outside-libyas-is-stronghold/2016/06/16/377721f0-33ab-11e6-ab9d-1da2b0f24f93_story.html|title=16 Libyan militiamen killed in 2 IS attacks near Sirte|publisher=|accessdate=24 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160617144410/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/10-killed-in-suicide-attack-outside-libyas-is-stronghold/2016/06/16/377721f0-33ab-11e6-ab9d-1da2b0f24f93_story.html|archive-date=17 June 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> On 21 June, GNA forces secured areas in the \"700\" neighbourhood, south of the city center, and gained ground to the west of the center of Sirte in the heavily damaged District No. 2. Other gains included: the Ben Hamal Mosque, the electricity headquarters and the radio station.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-sirte-idUSKCN0Z72H7|title=Libyan forces advance against Islamic State in Sirte: spokesman|date=21 June 2016|publisher=|accessdate=24 June 2016|via=Reuters|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625000930/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-sirte-idUSKCN0Z72H7|archive-date=25 June 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"39dead\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.libyaherald.com/2016/06/21/many-dead-in-fresh-bunyan-marsous-offensive-in-sirte-is-loses-ground/ |title=39 dead in fresh Bunyan Marsous offensive in Sirte; IS loses ground |access-date=2016-06-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160630143842/https://www.libyaherald.com/2016/06/21/many-dead-in-fresh-bunyan-marsous-offensive-in-sirte-is-loses-ground/ |archive-date=2016-06-30 |url-status=live}}</ref> During the advance, the GNA positioned themselves within a kilometer from the conference centre. Meanwhile, GNA fighters withdrew from the port, although they still controlled the port road, due to heavy ISIL sniper fire from a nearby hotel. Some 400 to 500 ISIL fighters were operating in the port area.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.middleeasteye.net/news/sirte-frontline-report-libya-726781445|title=EXCLUSIVE: Vicious fighting kills dozens as Libyan forces close in on IS-held Sirte|publisher=|accessdate=24 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160623135547/http://www.middleeasteye.net/news/sirte-frontline-report-libya-726781445|archive-date=23 June 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> During the advances, GNA fighters suffered heavy casualties with 39 being killed and another 140 wounded.<ref name=\"39dead\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/libya-clashes-blast-ammunition-depot-kill-60-40036719|title=Libya Clashes, Blast at a Depot Kill More Than 60|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=24 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160623140043/http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/libya-clashes-blast-ammunition-depot-kill-60-40036719|archive-date=23 June 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Another report put the number of GNA dead at more than 40.<ref name=\"battle\">{{cite web|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-idUKKCN0ZH5IL|title=Libyan forces battle Islamic State street-to-street in Sirte|publisher=|accessdate=13 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160702155728/http://uk.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-idUKKCN0ZH5IL|archive-date=2 July 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 June, the British SBS engaged in a 30-minute gun battle near Sirte with ISIL forces, killing 20\u201330 ISIL militants, three of whom were British.<ref name=\"SBS\">{{cite web|url=http://www.libyanexpress.com/three-british-isis-members-killed-by-sbs-soldiers-in-sirte/|title=Three British ISIS members killed by SBS soldiers in Sirte - Libyan Express|date=4 July 2016|publisher=|accessdate=13 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160711221423/http://www.libyanexpress.com/three-british-isis-members-killed-by-sbs-soldiers-in-sirte/|archive-date=11 July 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 July, ISIL fighters were driven out of the \"100\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.libyaobserver.ly/news/isis-loses-more-grounds-libyas-sirte|title=ISIS loses more grounds in Libya's Sirte - The Libya Observer|publisher=|accessdate=13 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160707095614/http://www.libyaobserver.ly/news/isis-loses-more-grounds-libyas-sirte|archive-date=7 July 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> and \"700\" neighbourhoods and GNA forces had surrounded the conference hall. ISIL fighters were also still holed up at a nearby hospital, with snipers and landmines slowing the GNA's progress.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-idUSKCN0ZI00X|title=Three killed as Libya forces close on central Sirte against Islamic State|date=2 July 2016|publisher=|accessdate=13 July 2016|via=Reuters|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160710085406/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-idUSKCN0ZI00X|archive-date=10 July 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The next day, the GNA captured the city center,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.enca.com/africa/libya-forces-control-of-strategic-locations-in-sirte|title=Libya forces control of strategic locations in Sirte|publisher=|accessdate=13 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160704044622/http://www.enca.com/africa/libya-forces-control-of-strategic-locations-in-sirte|archive-date=4 July 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> or at least part of it, as well as the harbor.<ref name=\"battle\"/> By 7 July, Mirghani Badawi al-Bashir, nicknamed \"Abu-al-Harith\", was killed by a drone strike. A leading local ISIL commander and a prominent [[Sudan]]ese peacher, Mirghani's death was regarded as heavy blow to ISIL by experts.<ref name=\"Bashir\" />\n\nOn 9 July, a mass grave was discovered by GNA forces on a farm on the southern edge of Sirte.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.libyaherald.com/2016/07/09/sirte-mass-grave-found-as-is-pressed-in-the-ouagadougou-centre/ |title=Sirte mass-grave found as IS pressed in the Ouagadougou centre |access-date=2016-07-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807032309/https://www.libyaherald.com/2016/07/09/sirte-mass-grave-found-as-is-pressed-in-the-ouagadougou-centre/ |archive-date=2016-08-07 |url-status=live}}</ref> The next day, an ISIL ammunition store was hit in the city center by ground fire, while more air-strikes hit other ISIL positions. In turn, ISIL fired Grad missiles at GNA positions in the first, second and third residential districts and the university campus.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.libyaherald.com/2016/07/10/94774/ |title=Heavy fighting continues in central Sirte as Bunyan Marsous close in IS at Ouagadougou Centre |access-date=2016-07-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807014352/https://www.libyaherald.com/2016/07/10/94774/ |archive-date=2016-08-07 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 July, heavy clashes erupted around the conference centre leaving 21 GNA soldiers dead and 139 wounded. During the fighting, three ISIL suicide car-bombers, including a Libyan and an Egyptian, hit GNA forces in an unsuccessful counter-attack. GNA fighters managed to enter the conference complex, but had not been able to capture it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/news/world/20-loyalist-troops-killed-fighting-is-in-libya-s-sirte/article/470130|title=20 loyalist troops killed fighting IS in Libya's Sirte|date=15 July 2016|publisher=|accessdate=15 July 2016|agency=AF{}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-sirte-idUSKCN0ZV2OR|title=Libyan forces battling Islamic State in Sirte suffer losses in push to advance|date=16 July 2016|publisher=|accessdate=2 August 2016|via=Reuters|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160719163114/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-sirte-idUSKCN0ZV2OR|archive-date=19 July 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.libyanexpress.com/misurata-central-hospital-21-killed-and-139-injured-in-sirte-clashes-against-isis/|title=Misurata Central Hospital: 21 killed and 139 injured in Sirte clashes against ISIS - Libyan Express|date=16 July 2016|publisher=|accessdate=2 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160809153908/http://www.libyanexpress.com/misurata-central-hospital-21-killed-and-139-injured-in-sirte-clashes-against-isis/|archive-date=9 August 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Some 10 days later, the GNA captured the largest ISIL bomb factory in Sirte,<ref name=\"factory\">{{cite web|url=http://www.france24.com/en/20160724-libya-loyalists-take-bomb-factory-sirte|title=Libya loyalists take IS bomb factory in Sirte|date=24 July 2016|accessdate=2 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160725144925/http://www.france24.com/en/20160724-libya-loyalists-take-bomb-factory-sirte|archive-date=2016-07-25|url-status=dead}}</ref> a hotel in the eastern part of the city, part of the \u201cDollar\u201d neighbourhood,<ref name=\"shell\">{{cite web|url=http://africa.tvcnews.tv/2016/07/25/libyan-troops-shell-i-s-positions-sirte/|title=Libyan troops shell I.S. positions in Sirte|publisher=TVC News|date=25 July 2016|accessdate=2 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160728063722/http://africa.tvcnews.tv/2016/07/25/libyan-troops-shell-i-s-positions-sirte/|archive-date=28 July 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> and the security headquarters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/libyan-forces-advance-in-islamic-state-held-city-1469462978|title=Libyan Forces Advance in Islamic State-Held City|first1=Tamer El-Ghobashy in|last1=Cairo|first2=Hassan Morajea in|last2=Nice|first3=|last3=France|date=25 July 2016|publisher=|accessdate=2 August 2016|via=Wall Street Journal|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160728135912/http://www.wsj.com/articles/libyan-forces-advance-in-islamic-state-held-city-1469462978|archive-date=28 July 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Operation Odyssey Lightning ==\nOn 1 August, at the request of the GNA, the [[United States Air Force]] and [[United States Marine Corps]] Harriers and helicopters launched from USS Wasp LHD-1 and USS San Antonio, began to bomb Sirte, targeting ISIL tanks and vehicles in support of the GNA forces. The attacks put further pressure on the estimated 1,000 ISIL fighters who remained in the city center.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.faz.net/aktuell/politik/ausland/afrika/libyen-amerikanische-luftwaffe-bombardiert-is-stellungen-14367579.html|title=Amerikanische Luftwaffe bombardiert IS-Stellungen|newspaper=[[Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung]]|date=1 August 2016|accessdate=2 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160802144551/http://www.faz.net/aktuell/politik/ausland/afrika/libyen-amerikanische-luftwaffe-bombardiert-is-stellungen-14367579.html|archive-date=2 August 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The strikes hit two T-72 tanks, a fighting position and two construction vehicles. The next day, an ISIL rocket launcher and a heavy equipment excavator were also hit.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.voanews.com/content/libyans-advance-sirte-with-more-united-states-airstrikes/3446276.html|title=Libyans Advance on Sirte With More US Airstrikes|publisher=Carla Babb|date=2 August 2016|accessdate=2 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160803201738/http://www.voanews.com/content/libyans-advance-sirte-with-more-united-states-airstrikes/3446276.html|archive-date=3 August 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> During these airstrikes, another Sudanese ISIL commander, Qusai al-Jaili, was reportedly killed, though other sources said he had died of illness or wounds. Al-Jaili had achieved prominence by masterminding the escape of four assassins of U.S. diplomat [[John Granville (diplomat)|John Granville]] from the Kober prison, [[Khartoum]], in 2009.<ref name=\"qusai\" /> By 4 August, \u201cDollar\u201d was secured.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-sirte-idUSKCN10E2LA|title=U.S. strikes easing advance against Islamic State in Sirte, says commander|date=4 August 2016|publisher=|accessdate=3 October 2016|via=Reuters|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160915213908/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-sirte-idUSKCN10E2LA|archive-date=15 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> On 7 August, GNA troops showed a small former ISIL training camp with an assault course, along with fox holes, that was taken by GNA forces.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.africanews.com/2016/08/06/libyan-army-show-territory-they-captured-from-isil-in-sirte/|title=Libyan army show territory they captured from ISIL in Sirte|first=|last=AfricaNews|date=3 October 2016|publisher=|accessdate=3 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817192142/http://www.africanews.com/2016/08/06/libyan-army-show-territory-they-captured-from-isil-in-sirte/|archive-date=17 August 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 August, the GNA seized an area of guest houses close to the Ouagadougou conference centre.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/08/libya-gains-isil-sirte-fighting-160808152702720.html|title=Libya makes gains against ISIL in Sirte fighting|publisher=al-Jazeera|date=10 August 2016|accessdate=10 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160810071941/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/08/libya-gains-isil-sirte-fighting-160808152702720.html|archive-date=10 August 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Two days later, GNA forces took control of the Ouagadougou centre, Sirte's Ibn Sina hospital and the university campus. During the fighting, a GNA fighter jet was shot down over Sirte with both pilots missing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-37037544|title=Libyans 'oust' so-called IS from Sirte headquarters|first=B. B. C.|last=News|publisher=|accessdate=3 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160814063059/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-37037544|archive-date=14 August 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> By 11 August, 70 percent of Sirte was under GNA control.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/mena/libya/70-per-cent-of-libya-s-sirte-liberated-from-daesh-1.1877392|title=70 per cent of Libya\u2019s Sirte liberated from Daesh|first=By Rob Norland, New York Times News|last=Service|date=11 August 2016|publisher=|accessdate=3 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161015052840/http://gulfnews.com/news/mena/libya/70-per-cent-of-libya-s-sirte-liberated-from-daesh-1.1877392|archive-date=15 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> At this point, the GNA started launching incursions into neighbourhoods 1 and 3, two of the districts that were still IS-held.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-idUSKCN10M1EE|title=Libyan forces in fresh clashes with Islamic State in Sirte|date=11 August 2016|publisher=|accessdate=3 October 2016|via=Reuters|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161008084317/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-idUSKCN10M1EE|archive-date=8 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The following day, bombardment commenced of neighbourhoods 1 and 2.<ref name=\"Macmadas\">{{cite web|url=http://www.libyanexpress.com/libyan-forces-announce-finals-battle-dubbed-macmadas-to-eradicate-is-from-sirte/|title=Libyan forces announce final battle dubbed \"Macmadas\" to eradicate IS from Sirte - Libyan Express|date=13 August 2016|publisher=|accessdate=3 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161026023347/http://www.libyanexpress.com/libyan-forces-announce-finals-battle-dubbed-macmadas-to-eradicate-is-from-sirte/|archive-date=26 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Meanwhile, it was confirmed the GNA also took control of the Amina Hotel,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.defense.gov/News/Article/Article/913814/dod-officials-local-forces-in-libya-syria-gain-ground-against-isil|title=DoD Officials: Local Forces in Libya, Syria Gain Ground Against ISIL|publisher=|accessdate=3 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160914171258/http://www.defense.gov/News/Article/Article/913814/dod-officials-local-forces-in-libya-syria-gain-ground-against-isil|archive-date=14 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> the police academy building and the Al-Giza military zone.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.libyanexpress.com/libyan-forces-close-in-on-is-last-two-hideouts-in-sirte-kill-senior-leader/|title=Libyan forces close in on IS last two hideouts in Sirte, kill senior leader - Libyan Express|date=12 August 2016|publisher=|accessdate=3 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161026023441/http://www.libyanexpress.com/libyan-forces-close-in-on-is-last-two-hideouts-in-sirte-kill-senior-leader/|archive-date=26 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== \"Macmadas\" ===\nOn 12 August, the GNA announced the beginning of the final battle, dubbed ''Macmadas'', to completely capture Sirte.<ref name=\"Macmadas\"/> On the next day, the city's radio station<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.libyaherald.com/2016/08/13/sirte-radio-station-retaken-from-is/|title=Sirte radio station retaken from IS|date=13 August 2016|access-date=14 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160815072201/https://www.libyaherald.com/2016/08/13/sirte-radio-station-retaken-from-is/|archive-date=15 August 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-idUSKCN10P0MG|title=Libyans fighting Islamic State in Sirte report advances along coast|date=14 August 2016|access-date=30 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171018031204/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-idUSKCN10P0MG|archive-date=18 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and the \"Indian\" buildings were captured by the GNA as they advanced into neighbourhood 2. During the fighting, there was an attempted ISIL suicide bomb attack against the advancing forces.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.libyaobserver.ly/news/al-bunyan-al-marsoos-widens-grip-sirte-downtown-areas|title=Al-Bunyan Al-Marsoos widens grip on Sirte downtown areas|date=14 August 2016|access-date=15 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160815162018/http://www.libyaobserver.ly/news/al-bunyan-al-marsoos-widens-grip-sirte-downtown-areas|archive-date=15 August 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Three days later, pro-GNA militias captured the neighbourhood 2 district and started advancing into neighbourhood 1.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-idUSKCN10R1EU|title=Libyan forces claim capture of district in Sirte from Islamic State|date=16 August 2016|access-date=30 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170706045608/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-idUSKCN10R1EU|archive-date=6 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/08/libyan-forces-seize-central-district-isil-held-sirte-160817034516906.html|title=Libyan forces retake central Sirte district from ISIL|publisher=|accessdate=3 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160924022633/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/08/libyan-forces-seize-central-district-isil-held-sirte-160817034516906.html|archive-date=24 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> During the fighting for neighbourhood 2, ISIL fighters launched nine suicide bombings that killed 9 GNA fighters and wounded 82.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2016/08/18/world/islamic-state-holdouts-wage-wave-suicide-blasts-sirte-pockets-fall|title=Islamic State holdouts wage wave of suicide blasts as Sirte pockets fall|work=Japan Times|date=18 August 2016|access-date=18 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160818135416/http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2016/08/18/world/islamic-state-holdouts-wage-wave-suicide-blasts-sirte-pockets-fall/|archive-date=18 August 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Following the capture of this area, only neighbourhoods 1 and 3 remained IS-held.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/08/17/africa/libya-sirte-isis/index.html|title=Libya: ISIS all but defeated in key city|author1=Paul Armstrong |author2=Ghazi Balkiz|publisher=CNN|accessdate=3 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161006134051/http://www.cnn.com/2016/08/17/africa/libya-sirte-isis/index.html|archive-date=6 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 August, ISIL fighters from outside the city attacked GNA fighters at a rallying area and a checkpoint, killing at least 10 GNA fighters and wounding 20.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/suicide-bombers-hit-libyan-troops-sirte-kill-41481401|title=Suicide Bombers Hit Libyan Troops in Sirte, Kill at Least 10|work=ABC News|date=18 August 2016|access-date=18 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160819055954/http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/suicide-bombers-hit-libyan-troops-sirte-kill-41481401|archive-date=19 August 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Another attack by three IS suicide-bombers was prevented and the attackers killed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.libyanexpress.com/libyan-forces-kill-three-is-suicide-bombers-after-two-car-bomb-blasts-in-sirte/|title=Libyan forces kill three IS suicide bombers after two car bomb blasts in Sirte|work=Libyan Express|date=18 August 2016|access-date=21 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160821170231/http://www.libyanexpress.com/libyan-forces-kill-three-is-suicide-bombers-after-two-car-bomb-blasts-in-sirte/|archive-date=21 August 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Between 21 and 22 August, pro-GNA militias captured the Ribat mosque, the city's biggest and main mosque,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-idUSKCN10W0XQ|title=Libyan forces say they capture mosque, prison from Islamic State in Sirte|work=REUTERS|date=21 August 2016|access-date=30 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170706045619/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-idUSKCN10W0XQ|archive-date=6 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> as well as the internal security building that was used as an IS prison, a courthouse, the Al-Naga district and Dubai Street.<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/anti-forces-seize-more-ground-libyas-sirte-095031746.html Anti-IS forces seize more ground in Libya's Sirte] (AFP)</ref>\n\nDuring their advances, the GNA discovered a major horde of gold, money and weapons inside the IS security headquarters. In one room, there were boxes of gold, jewelry, wads of Tunisian currency, rifles and shotguns, computers, radios and cartons of telephone cards.<ref>[https://www.libyaherald.com/2016/08/22/is-abandons-treasure-hoard-in-sirte/ IS abandons treasure hoard in Sirte] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160825184224/https://www.libyaherald.com/2016/08/22/is-abandons-treasure-hoard-in-sirte/ |date=2016-08-25}} Libya Herald (22 August 2016)</ref> On 25 August, GNA's spokesman for the operation Mohamed al-Ghasry stated that ISIL had withdrawn from most of the neighbourhood 3 into a small part of the neighbourhood as well as the northern half of neighbourhood 1.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/us-carries-out-anti-daesh-airstrikes-in-sirte-libya/635522|title=US carries out anti-Daesh airstrikes in Sirte, Libya|work=Andalou Agency|date=25 August 2016|access-date=25 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826200927/http://aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/us-carries-out-anti-daesh-airstrikes-in-sirte-libya/635522|archive-date=26 August 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 August, the GNA suffered heavy casualties in fighting while advancing into neighbourhood 1 and 3. Five car bombs were deployed by the militants in the battle though at least one was destroyed before it could reach its target. Hospitals in Sirte reported that 35<ref name=Reuters1/> GNA fighters died and 150 more were wounded. U.S. and Libyan warplanes bombarded ISIL-held neighbourhoods in Sirte overnight.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-37210552|title=Heavy casualties as Libyan forces advance on IS in Sirte - BBC News|language=en-GB|access-date=2016-08-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160829120849/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-37210552|archive-date=2016-08-29|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/08/libyan-forces-final-push-retake-sirte-isil-160828134612134.html|title=Libyan forces make final push to retake Sirte from ISIL|publisher=Al Jazeera|date=2016-08-29|access-date=2016-08-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160828162030/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/08/libyan-forces-final-push-retake-sirte-isil-160828134612134.html|archive-date=2016-08-28|url-status=live}}</ref> The Cordoba mosque which ISIL had renamed to [[Abu Musab Zarqawi]] mosque was captured on the same day along with other areas of neighbourhood 3.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.libyaobserver.ly/news/main-isis-mosque-libyas-sirte-recaptured|title=Main ISIS mosque in Libya's Sirte recaptured|publisher=Libya Observer|date=2016-08-29|access-date=2016-08-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160830171603/http://www.libyaobserver.ly/news/main-isis-mosque-libyas-sirte-recaptured|archive-date=2016-08-30|url-status=live}}</ref> GNA militias announced the next day that they had completely captured neighbourhood 1 with ISIL still controlling half of neighbourhood 3. 10 GNA fighters were killed during the clashes while 12 were wounded.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/libyan-forces-corner-fighters-sirte-005445796.html|title=Libyan forces tighten noose on IS in Sirte|author=Mahmud Turkia|publisher=Yahoo! News|date=2016-08-30|access-date=2016-08-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160829182310/https://www.yahoo.com/news/libyan-forces-corner-fighters-sirte-005445796.html|archive-date=2016-08-29|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 September, pro-GNA militias launched an offensive on the last-ISIL held areas of Sirte and stated they had captured several buildings including two banks and a hotel. An attempted suicide bombing by ISIL was also thwarted by the militias. 7\u201310 pro-GNA fighters were reported to be killed, while 30\u201360 were wounded in the clashes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.middleeasteye.net/news/libya-pro-government-forces-attack-last-islamic-state-diehards-sirte-1649700589|title=Libya pro-government forces attack last Islamic State diehards in Sirte|publisher=Middle East Eye|date=2016-08-03|access-date=2016-08-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160904161936/http://www.middleeasteye.net/news/libya-pro-government-forces-attack-last-islamic-state-diehards-sirte-1649700589|archive-date=2016-09-04|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-idUSKCN1190U3|title=Libyan forces report further progress against Islamic State holdouts in Sirte|work=Reuters|date=2016-08-04|access-date=2016-08-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160903195910/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-idUSKCN1190U3|archive-date=2016-09-03|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/09/libyan-forces-attack-isil-positions-sirte-160903201929388.html|title=Libyan forces attack 'last ISIL positions' in Sirte|publisher=Al Jazeera|date=2016-08-03|access-date=2016-08-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160904025931/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/09/libyan-forces-attack-isil-positions-sirte-160903201929388.html|archive-date=2016-09-04|url-status=live}}</ref> On 5 September, the media wing of Al-Bunyan Al-Marsous reported that it had captured ISIL pockets in the Jizah neighbourhood including a Wihda Bank branch.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.libyanexpress.com/libyan-forces-capture-seaside-jizah-neighbourhood-in-sirte-battle/|title=Libyan forces capture seaside Jizah neighbourhood in Sirte battle|date=2016-09-06|access-date=2016-09-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160908164931/http://www.libyanexpress.com/libyan-forces-capture-seaside-jizah-neighbourhood-in-sirte-battle/|archive-date=2016-09-08|url-status=live}}</ref> On 6 September, the pro-GNA forces captured the buildings of the civil court and the savings bank in neighbourhood 3 in addition to an ammunition stockpile belonging to the militants containing mines, explosives and warheads.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.libyanexpress.com/libyan-forces-seize-key-poisons-from-is-in-neighbourhood-3-sirte/|title=Libyan forces seize key positions from IS in neighbourhood (3) Sirte|date=2016-09-06|access-date=2016-09-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160908195602/http://www.libyanexpress.com/libyan-forces-seize-key-poisons-from-is-in-neighbourhood-3-sirte/|archive-date=2016-09-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== New stalemate ===\nOn 8 September, pro-GNA forces stated that ISIL was using civilians as human shields which was delaying the advancement of pro-GNA fighters.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://english.aawsat.com/2016/09/article55358011/libya-isis-use-families-human-shields-delayed-liberation-sirte|title=Libya: ISIS\u2019 Use of Families as Human Shields Delayed Liberation of Sirte|author=Khalid Mahmoud|publisher=Asharq al-Awsat|date=2016-09-08|access-date=2016-09-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160909151504/http://english.aawsat.com/2016/09/article55358011/libya-isis-use-families-human-shields-delayed-liberation-sirte|archive-date=2016-09-09|url-status=live}}</ref> Some days later, they also pointed out that the slipping away of some militants as pro-GNA militias advanced was behind the delay. There were concerns that all of them hadn't been cleared behind the lines as some militants had carried out attacks on pro-GNA troops behind them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.libyaherald.com/2016/09/11/sirte-battle-pauses-as-is-feared-in-rear-areas/|title=Sirte battle pauses as IS feared in rear areas|publisher=Libya Herald|date=2016-09-11|access-date=2016-09-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160914155331/https://www.libyaherald.com/2016/09/11/sirte-battle-pauses-as-is-feared-in-rear-areas/|archive-date=2016-09-14|url-status=live}}</ref> On 14 September, four foreigners and two Libyans were freed from ISIL's prisons in Sirte. The foreigners included two [[North Korea]]ns and two [[Indian people|Indians]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.libyaobserver.ly/news/foreigners-freed-isis-prisons-sirte|title=Foreigners freed from ISIS prisons in Sirte|publisher=Libya Observer|date=2016-09-14|access-date=2016-09-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160915172038/http://www.libyaobserver.ly/news/foreigners-freed-isis-prisons-sirte|archive-date=2016-09-15|url-status=live}}</ref> Meanwhile, [[AFRICOM]] carried out airstrikes against ISIL, hitting six positions of the group and a car bomb.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.libyaherald.com/2016/09/16/indian-academics-held-in-sirte-freed-us-air-strikes-against-is-continue/|title=Indian academics held in Sirte freed; US air strikes against IS continue|publisher=Libya Herald|date=2016-09-16|access-date=2016-09-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160918164154/https://www.libyaherald.com/2016/09/16/indian-academics-held-in-sirte-freed-us-air-strikes-against-is-continue/|archive-date=2016-09-18|url-status=live}}</ref> By 16 September, 15 people including nine Libyans, three Koreans, two Indians and a Palestinian had been freed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laht.com/article.asp?CategoryId=12395&ArticleId=2421147|title=15 People Kidnapped by IS in Libya Freed|publisher=Latin American Herald Tribune|date=2016-09-16|access-date=2016-09-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160918140204/http://www.laht.com/article.asp?ArticleId=2421147&CategoryId=12395|archive-date=2016-09-18|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 September, al-Bunyan al-Marsous launched an offensive against the last ISIL holdouts in [[Sirte]]. During the clashes, two car bombs were destroyed, before they could reach pro-GNA fighters. Pro-GNA militias stated they had captured the Social Security headquarters, an ISIL field hospital, Fateh School, Grand Mosque and a workshop for manufacturing explosives. Three pro-GNA fighters were killed, while two ISIL commanders, Hassan al-Karami and Walid Al-Furjan, were confirmed to have been killed in the clashes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.libyaobserver.ly/news/clashes-against-isis-libyas-sirte-renewed|title=Clashes against ISIS in Libya's Sirte renewed|publisher=Libya Observer|date=2016-09-18|access-date=2016-09-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160919074258/http://www.libyaobserver.ly/news/clashes-against-isis-libyas-sirte-renewed|archive-date=2016-09-19|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.middleeasteye.net/news/libya-forces-resume-assault-islamic-state-after-lull-1734443169|title=Libya forces resume assault on Islamic State after lull|publisher=Middle East Eye|date=2016-09-18|access-date=2016-09-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160919131348/http://www.middleeasteye.net/news/libya-forces-resume-assault-islamic-state-after-lull-1734443169|archive-date=2016-09-19|url-status=live}}</ref> Clashes renewed on 22 September, with 10 militants and 9 pro-GNA fighters being killed. Three car bombs were destroyed before reaching their targets, while the spokesman for Misratan militias stated that the militants had been cut off from each other and surrounded in two different areas.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSKCN11S28E|title=Libyan forces say foil Islamic State car bombings in Sirte|work=Reuters|date=2016-09-22|access-date=2016-09-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.france24.com/en/20160922-19-dead-clashes-with-libyas-sirte|title='19 dead' in clashes with IS in Libya's Sirte|publisher=France24|date=2016-09-22|access-date=2016-09-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160923113810/http://www.france24.com/en/20160922-19-dead-clashes-with-libyas-sirte|archive-date=2016-09-23|url-status=dead}}</ref> Misrata's Central Hospital reported on 23 September that 10 pro-GNA fighters had been killed while 65 were injured during clashes from 22\u201323 September.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.libyanexpress.com/10-fighters-killed-as-libyan-forces-step-up-fight-in-last-is-hideouts-in-sirte/|title=10 fighters killed as Libyan forces step up fight in last IS hideouts in Sirte|publisher=Libyan Express|date=2016-09-24|access-date=2016-09-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160925134048/http://www.libyanexpress.com/10-fighters-killed-as-libyan-forces-step-up-fight-in-last-is-hideouts-in-sirte/|archive-date=2016-09-25|url-status=live}}</ref> As the situation for the besieged ISIL forces became increasingly dire, media reports started to emerge that ISIL began to employ female fighters as snipers in an extremely unusual move for the militant group.<ref name=\"female\" />\n\nBetween 25 and 26 September, AFRICOM carried out airstrikes on an ISIL supply point<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.libyaherald.com/2016/09/26/drop-in-us-airstrikes-on-sirte/|title=Drop in US airstrikes on Sirte|publisher=Libyan Herald|date=2016-09-26|access-date=2016-09-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161001154920/https://www.libyaherald.com/2016/09/26/drop-in-us-airstrikes-on-sirte/|archive-date=2016-10-01|url-status=live}}</ref> and other positions around the \"600 Buildings\" neighbourhood.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.libyanexpress.com/us-airstrikes-on-sirte-killed-6-is-militants-libyan-forces-announce/|title=US airstrikes on Sirte killed 6 IS militants, Libyan forces announce|publisher=Libyan Express|date=2016-09-27|access-date=2016-09-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160928155832/http://www.libyanexpress.com/us-airstrikes-on-sirte-killed-6-is-militants-libyan-forces-announce/|archive-date=2016-09-28|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 October 2016, a group of ISIL militants, who attempted to escape the city, were killed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Middle-East/2016/Oct-02/374790-libyan-forces-kill-10-isis-fighters-fleeing-sirte.ashx|title=Libyan forces kill 10 ISIS fighters fleeing Sirte|date=2 October 2016|publisher=|accessdate=3 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161003054255/http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Middle-East/2016/Oct-02/374790-libyan-forces-kill-10-isis-fighters-fleeing-sirte.ashx|archive-date=3 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The same day, an attack by ISIL militants on a GNA checkpoint from outside [[Sirte]], near [[Ghardabiya Air Base]], in a possible attempt to lift the siege of the city, was repelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.libyaobserver.ly/news/isis-convoy-exterminated-south-sirte|title=ISIS convoy exterminated in south Sirte - The Libya Observer|publisher=|accessdate=3 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161003171951/http://www.libyaobserver.ly/news/isis-convoy-exterminated-south-sirte|archive-date=3 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.libyaherald.com/2016/10/08/bunyan-marsous-forces-in-sirte-split-last-is-enclave/ |title=Bunyan Marsous forces in Sirte split last IS enclave |access-date=2016-10-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161010213409/https://www.libyaherald.com/2016/10/08/bunyan-marsous-forces-in-sirte-split-last-is-enclave/ |archive-date=2016-10-10 |url-status=live}}</ref> Overall, 80 ISIL and 8 GNA fighters were reported killed during the clashes, while another 57 GNA fighters were wounded.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeslive.co.za/africa/2016/10/03/Libya-govt-forces-say-80-jihadists-killed-in-Sirte|title=Libya govt forces say 80 jihadists killed in Sirte|first=|last=AFP|publisher=|accessdate=3 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161004064845/http://www.timeslive.co.za/africa/2016/10/03/Libya-govt-forces-say-80-jihadists-killed-in-Sirte|archive-date=4 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> A Dutch photojournalist, [[Jeroen Oerlemans]], who was covering the government-backed offensive against ISIL, also died due to ISIL sniper fire.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.middleeasteye.net/news/libya-battle-sirte-leaves-19-dead-including-dutch-journalist-2020609980|title=Libya, IS battle in Sirte leaves 19 dead, including Dutch journalist|publisher=Middle East Eye|date=2016-10-02|access-date=2016-10-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161003164828/http://www.middleeasteye.net/news/libya-battle-sirte-leaves-19-dead-including-dutch-journalist-2020609980|archive-date=2016-10-03|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== ISIL pocket split ===\nOn 7 October 2016, GNA forces managed to separate the last ISIL-controlled areas in Sirte, after taking control of the dividing line between the \"600\" neighbourhood and the sea-view Jizah apartment buildings. The control of the dividing line also cut ISIL aid routes. During their advances, the GNA discovered secret tunnels connecting the besieged areas in the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.libyaobserver.ly/news/al-bunyan-al-marsoos-forces-uncover-underground-tunnels-disconnect-isis-controlled-areas-sirte|title=Al-Bunyan Al-Marsoos forces uncover underground tunnels; disconnect ISIS-controlled areas in Sirte|publisher=The Libyan Observer|access-date=2016-10-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161009170328/http://www.libyaobserver.ly/news/al-bunyan-al-marsoos-forces-uncover-underground-tunnels-disconnect-isis-controlled-areas-sirte|archive-date=2016-10-09|url-status=live}}</ref> During the day's fighting, the senior ISIL leader Abu al-Baraa al-Masri was killed on the frontline in Jizah neighbourhood, along with two ISIL snipers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.libyanexpress.com/top-is-leader-killed-in-sirte-clashes-sources-say/|title=Top IS leader killed in Sirte clashes, sources say|publisher=Libyan Express|access-date=2016-10-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161009142151/http://www.libyanexpress.com/top-is-leader-killed-in-sirte-clashes-sources-say/|archive-date=2016-10-09|url-status=live}}</ref> On 9 October, GNA forces advanced across two streets in the \"600\" neighbourhood. The media officer of the Misratan militias stated that they had completely encircled the neighbourhood. Two female militants reportedly surrendered along with their children, in fear of being used as suicide bombers.<ref name=\"pushinto\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-sirte-idUSKCN12A11X|title=Libyan forces push into last Islamic State area in Sirte|work=Reuters|access-date=2016-10-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161010230103/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-sirte-idUSKCN12A11X|archive-date=2016-10-10|url-status=live}}</ref> Another media official reported that pro-GNA fighters had also advanced into the al-Manara neighbourhood.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.libyanexpress.com/libyan-forces-make-big-ground-gains-in-sirte-say-liberation-is-in-sight/|title=Libyan forces make big ground gains in Sirte, say liberation is in sight|publisher=Libyan Express|access-date=2016-10-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161011055806/http://www.libyanexpress.com/libyan-forces-make-big-ground-gains-in-sirte-say-liberation-is-in-sight/|archive-date=2016-10-11|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAs of 12 October, the GNA air force and artillery were intermittently bombarding ISIL positions in the \"600\" neighbourhood.<ref name=\"fiveIS\">{{cite web|url=http://libyaprospect.com/index.php/2016/10/12/al-bunyan-al-marsous-kills-five-is-elements-in-sirte/|title=Al-Bunyan Al-Marsous kills five IS elements in Sirte|publisher=LIBYAPROSPECT|access-date=2016-10-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161013132723/http://libyaprospect.com/index.php/2016/10/12/al-bunyan-al-marsous-kills-five-is-elements-in-sirte/|archive-date=2016-10-13|url-status=live}}</ref> U.S. airstrikes were also being conducted.<ref name=\"14dead\">{{cite web|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/1199172/14-dead-pro-govt-fighters-squeeze-libyas-sirte/|title=14 dead as pro-govt fighters squeeze IS in Libya's Sirte - The Express Tribune|date=15 October 2016|publisher=|accessdate=16 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018212828/http://tribune.com.pk/story/1199172/14-dead-pro-govt-fighters-squeeze-libyas-sirte/|archive-date=18 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Overall between 9 and 15 October, at least 22 pro-GNA fighters were killed in clashes,<ref name=\"14dead\"/><ref name=\"pushinto\"/> while more than half a dozen militants also died.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://libyaprospect.com/index.php/2016/10/15/two-is-leaders-killed-in-sirte/|title=Two IS leaders killed in Sirte|publisher=LIBYAPROSPECT|access-date=2016-10-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018211547/http://libyaprospect.com/index.php/2016/10/15/two-is-leaders-killed-in-sirte/|archive-date=2016-10-18|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"fiveIS\"/> On 14 October, street-to-street fighting, involving tanks and armoured vehicles, took place in the Jizah neighbourhood.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-libya-security-sirte-idUKKBN12F033|title=Libyan forces advance in Sirte, 14 troops killed, officials say|first=Reuters|last=Editorial|publisher=|accessdate=16 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161020041151/http://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-libya-security-sirte-idUKKBN12F033|archive-date=20 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> On 16 October, the GNA captured the Cambo (al-Manara) neighbourhood, including tunnels and a field hospital,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-sirte-idUSKBN12H1U9|title=U.S. air strikes pound Libya's Sirte to oust Islamic State militants|date=17 October 2016|publisher=|accessdate=16 November 2016|via=Reuters|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161020154923/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-sirte-idUSKBN12H1U9|archive-date=20 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.libyanexpress.com/libyan-forces-capture-key-sirtes-campo-neighbourhood-from-is-grip/|title=Libyan forces capture key Sirte's Campo neighbourhood from IS grip - Libyan Express|date=16 October 2016|publisher=|accessdate=16 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018211107/http://www.libyanexpress.com/libyan-forces-capture-key-sirtes-campo-neighbourhood-from-is-grip/|archive-date=18 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> and advanced several hundred metres into Jizah neighbourhood.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/10/16/libyan-government-forces-near-victory-in-sirte/|title=Libyan government forces near victory in Sirte|publisher=|accessdate=16 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161022164124/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/10/16/libyan-government-forces-near-victory-in-sirte/|archive-date=22 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 October, pro-GNA militias announced they had captured the \"600\" neighbourhood, leaving only the Jizah area under ISIL control,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-idUSKCN12M0EE|title=Libya forces free 13 foreign captives from militants in Sirte battle|date=22 October 2016|publisher=|accessdate=16 November 2016|via=Reuters|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161115101739/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-idUSKCN12M0EE|archive-date=15 November 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> although the last apartment blocks in the \"600\" neighbourhood were not cleared until the next day.<ref name=\"600apartment\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.libyaherald.com/2016/10/23/bm-forces-win-fight-for-sirtes-600-apartment-complex/ |title=BM forces win fight for Sirte\u2019s 600 apartment complex |access-date=2016-10-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161024214131/https://www.libyaherald.com/2016/10/23/bm-forces-win-fight-for-sirtes-600-apartment-complex/ |archive-date=2016-10-24 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Attack on the last ISIL-held district ===\nOn 26 October, GNA militias launched an attack on the Jizah neighbourhood by shelling it with heavy artillery,<ref name=\"HeavyArtillery\"/> managing to take control of several residential blocks by the following day.<ref name=\"Gainground\">{{cite web|url=http://www.libyaobserver.ly/news/revolutionary-forces-gain-ground-last-isis-held-area-sirte|title=Revolutionary forces gain ground in last ISIS-held area in Sirte - The Libya Observer|publisher=|accessdate=16 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161031215322/http://www.libyaobserver.ly/news/revolutionary-forces-gain-ground-last-isis-held-area-sirte|archive-date=31 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> In the fighting between 19 and 26 October, 22 GNA fighters and more than 22 ISIL militants were killed, while 24 foreign hostages were freed by the GNA. Additionally, 24 civilians crossed the frontline into GNA territory, while seven unidentified and burned bodies were found.<ref name=\"600apartment\"/><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.libyaherald.com/2016/10/20/more-bm-dead-and-wounded-as-the-sirte-terrorist-battle-goes-on/ |title=More BM dead and wounded as the Sirte terrorist battle goes on |access-date=2016-10-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161021131311/https://www.libyaherald.com/2016/10/20/more-bm-dead-and-wounded-as-the-sirte-terrorist-battle-goes-on/ |archive-date=2016-10-21 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.libyanexpress.com/libyan-forces-seize-the-entire-600-buildings-residential-area-in-sirte/|title=Libyan forces seize the entire 600 buildings residential area in Sirte - Libyan Express|date=22 October 2016|publisher=|accessdate=16 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161023185619/http://www.libyanexpress.com/libyan-forces-seize-the-entire-600-buildings-residential-area-in-sirte/|archive-date=23 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"HeavyArtillery\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ansamed.info/ansamed/en/news/sections/generalnews/2016/10/26/libya-media-6-foreigners-abducted-by-isis-in-sirte-freed_71d33a0d-d99e-470c-9b89-5a29dd3aa1d2.html|title=Libya: media, 6 foreigners abducted by ISIS in Sirte freed - General news - ANSAMed.it|publisher=|accessdate=16 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161027123700/http://www.ansamed.info/ansamed/en/news/sections/generalnews/2016/10/26/libya-media-6-foreigners-abducted-by-isis-in-sirte-freed_71d33a0d-d99e-470c-9b89-5a29dd3aa1d2.html|archive-date=27 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> On 31 October, the GNA launched a new attack on the Jizah neighbourhood from the seaside.<ref name=\"Spearhead\">{{cite web|url=http://www.libyaobserver.ly/news/al-bunyan-al-marsoos-forces-spearhead-frontal-attacks-sirte|title=Al-Bunyan Al-Marsoos forces spearhead frontal attacks on IS in Sirte - The Libya Observer|publisher=|accessdate=16 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161104064455/http://www.libyaobserver.ly/news/al-bunyan-al-marsoos-forces-spearhead-frontal-attacks-sirte|archive-date=4 November 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBy this point, about 100 ISIL militants were reportedly left, holding out in the city.<ref name=\"About100\">{{cite web|url=http://www.voanews.com/a/libya-kerry-haftar-saraj/3573427.html|title=Libya's Chaos Prompts New US Calls for Action|first=Luis|last=Ramirez|publisher=|accessdate=16 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161104053149/http://www.voanews.com/a/libya-kerry-haftar-saraj/3573427.html|archive-date=4 November 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The United States also ended its bombing campaign on ISIL in Sirte, after carrying out a total of 367 airstrikes.<ref>{{cite web|title=US air attacks on ISIS in Sirte Libya appear to have ended|url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/news/world/us-air-attacks-on-isis-in-sirte-libya-appear-to-have-ended/article/479033|author=Ken Hanly|publisher=Digital Journal|date=7 November 2016|accessdate=8 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161107215944/http://www.digitaljournal.com/news/world/us-air-attacks-on-isis-in-sirte-libya-appear-to-have-ended/article/479033|archive-date=7 November 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Is US quietly ending the Libyan bombing campaign against ISIS?|url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2016/11/04/us-quietly-ends-libya-bombing-campaign-against-isis.html|author=Lucas Tomlinson|publisher=Fox News|date=4 November 2016|accessdate=8 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161108015256/http://www.foxnews.com/us/2016/11/04/us-quietly-ends-libya-bombing-campaign-against-isis.html|archive-date=8 November 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[United States Department of Defense]] stated, that airstrikes would be resumed, if they were needed.<ref>{{cite web|title=U.S. ready to resume air strikes in Libya if needed: Pentagon|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSKBN1322M1|date=7 November 2016|accessdate=8 November 2016}}</ref> On 2 November, GNA forces gained a new foothold in the last ISIL-controlled area of the city<ref name=\"Trap\">{{cite web|title=Libyan forces lose more fighters in Sirte as they continue to trap IS radicals in 1km area|url=http://www.libyanexpress.com/libyan-forces-lose-more-fighters-in-sirte-as-they-continue-to-trap-is-radicals-in-1km-area/|accessdate=2 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161103141137/http://www.libyanexpress.com/libyan-forces-lose-more-fighters-in-sirte-as-they-continue-to-trap-is-radicals-in-1km-area/|archive-date=3 November 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> and advanced further on 6 November.<ref name=\"New Nooks\">{{cite web|title=Libyan forces advance deeper into last IS hideout in Sirte|url=http://www.libyanexpress.com/libyan-forces-advance-deeper-into-last-is-hideout-in-sirte/|accessdate=8 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161107153650/http://www.libyanexpress.com/libyan-forces-advance-deeper-into-last-is-hideout-in-sirte/|archive-date=7 November 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> During the fighting, the GNA freed 14 civilians,<ref>{{cite web|title=Libyan forces report 14 civilians freed from Islamic State in Sirte|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-idUSKBN13111G|accessdate=7 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161107160914/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-idUSKBN13111G|archive-date=7 November 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> while a senior GNA commander was killed.<ref name=\"al-Maadani\">{{cite web|url=http://www.libyanexpress.com/libyan-forces-lose-more-fighters-in-sirte-as-they-continue-to-trap-is-radicals-in-1km-area/|title=Libyan forces lose more fighters in Sirte as they continue to trap IS radicals in 1km area - Libyan Express|date=2 November 2016|publisher=|accessdate=16 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161106060636/http://www.libyanexpress.com/libyan-forces-lose-more-fighters-in-sirte-as-they-continue-to-trap-is-radicals-in-1km-area/|archive-date=6 November 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 November, after more advances by the GNA, only a few ISIL snipers were estimated to be left in the area, still under their control.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.africanews.com/2016/11/10/libya-fighters-free-more-areas-in-sirte/|title=Libya fighters free more areas in Sirte|publisher=Africanews|access-date=2016-11-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161111163337/http://www.africanews.com/2016/11/10/libya-fighters-free-more-areas-in-sirte/|archive-date=2016-11-11|url-status=live}}</ref> On 12 November, the GNA stated that it was delaying the final assault because it would result in intense street-to-street fighting. They also stated that they were taking a step-by-step approach to limit casualties among their ranks, as well as the civilians held as human shields by ISIL.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.aawsat.com/2016/11/article55361999/war-attrition-sirte-delays-final-assault-isis|title=War of Attrition in Sirte Delays Final Assault on ISIS|publisher=Asharq Al-Awsat|date=12 November 2016|accessdate=17 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161118043420/http://english.aawsat.com/2016/11/article55361999/war-attrition-sirte-delays-final-assault-isis|archive-date=18 November 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> On 16 November, GNA advanced to control the \"20\" street.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://libyaprospect.com/index.php/2016/11/17/civilians-call-al-bunyan-al-marsous-to-stop-advancing/|title=Civilians call Al-Bunyan Al-Marsous to stop advancing|publisher=LIBYAPROSPECT|date=16 November 2016|accessdate=17 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161118100937/http://libyaprospect.com/index.php/2016/11/17/civilians-call-al-bunyan-al-marsous-to-stop-advancing/|archive-date=18 November 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The next day, they tightened the siege on the group and found bodies of 11 militants, likely killed in recent clashes. They also destroyed a car bomb and freed three women along with a number of children.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.libyaobserver.ly/news/three-women-children-freed-misrata-led-forces-continue-crimp-isis-diehards-sirte|title=Three women, children freed as Misrata-led forces continue to crimp ISIS diehards in Sirte|publisher=Asharq Al-Awsat|date=17 November 2016|accessdate=17 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161118144657/http://www.libyaobserver.ly/news/three-women-children-freed-misrata-led-forces-continue-crimp-isis-diehards-sirte|archive-date=18 November 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBy this point, ISIL territory in the city had been reduced to just one square kilometer. About 400 ISIL militants, who had managed to escape [[Sirte]] since the beginning of the offensive, were conducting guerrilla attacks behind the frontline.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-idUSKBN13D222 |title=Far from Mosul, Islamic State close to defeat in Libya's Sirte |access-date=2017-06-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170723024115/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-idUSKBN13D222 |archive-date=2017-07-23 |url-status=live}}</ref> The GNA advanced further on 21 November, capturing a fortified school.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/north-africa/2016/11/22/Libya-unity-forces-closing-on-Sirte-militants-.html|title=Libya unity forces closing on Sirte militants|publisher=Al Arabiya|date=22 November 2016|accessdate=22 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161123054326/http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/north-africa/2016/11/22/Libya-unity-forces-closing-on-Sirte-militants-.html|archive-date=23 November 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> They seized a number of barricaded houses on the next day. The United States also resumed its airstrikes on ISIL at this point. Advancing GNA fighters were delayed by booby traps and mines. Some GNA units had to be pulled back from the narrow frontline and were reserved for relieving other fighters.<ref name=14arrest>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idINKBN13H14R|title=Libyan forces press forward against Islamic State in Sirte, urge civilians to leave|work=Reuters|date=22 November 2016|accessdate=22 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"37perish\">{{cite web|url=https://www.libyaherald.com/2016/11/22/surrender-calls-as-37-terrorists-perish-in-shrinking-sirte-enclave/|title=Surrender calls as 37 terrorists perish in shrinking Sirte enclave|publisher=Libya Herald|date=22 November 2016|accessdate=24 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161124091547/https://www.libyaherald.com/2016/11/22/surrender-calls-as-37-terrorists-perish-in-shrinking-sirte-enclave/|archive-date=24 November 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBy 22 November, only 50 militants were remaining in a few dozen properties, still controlled by ISIL.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/daesh-terrorists-surrender-in-libya-s-sirte-source/691631|title=Daesh terrorists surrender in Libya\u2019s Sirte: source|author=Seif Eddine Trabelsi|publisher=Anadolu Agency|date=22 November 2016|accessdate=24 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161124092230/http://aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/daesh-terrorists-surrender-in-libya-s-sirte-source/691631|archive-date=24 November 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"37perish\"/> Between 22 and 24 November, the US conducted more than a dozen airstrikes, hitting 61 ISIL positions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sputniknews.com/africa/201611251047839021-us-airstrikes-daesh-libya/|title=US Airstrikes Hit 34 Daesh Fighting Positions Near Libya\u2019s Sirte|publisher=Sputnik International|date=25 November 2016|accessdate=25 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161126133036/https://sputniknews.com/africa/201611251047839021-us-airstrikes-daesh-libya/|archive-date=26 November 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> GNA captured 25 houses in addition to a stash of arms on 24 November.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-idUSKBN13J1FG|title=Libyan forces edge forward against Islamic State holdouts in Sirte|author1=Aidan Lewis|author2=Ahmed Elumami|work=Reuters|date=24 November 2016|accessdate=25 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161125002955/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-idUSKBN13J1FG|archive-date=25 November 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> On 26 November, GNA managed to take control of around 30 buildings, facing heavy resistance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.libyaobserver.ly/news/misrata-led-forces-advance-jiza-isis-deploy-suicide-bombers|title=Misrata-led forces advance into Jiza, ISIS deploy suicide bombers|publisher=Libyan Observer|date=26 November 2016|accessdate=27 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161127134937/http://www.libyaobserver.ly/news/misrata-led-forces-advance-jiza-isis-deploy-suicide-bombers|archive-date=27 November 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> During the clashes, two suicide bombers targeted them, while a woman, whom they were trying to provide a safe passage, started firing on them instead, before being killed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSKBN13L0MM|title=Libyan forces face deadly Islamic State defense in Sirte holdout|author=Aidan Lewis|work=Reuters|date=26 November 2016|accessdate=27 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nBy 1 December, the territory under ISIL control was reduced to around 50 buildings in the area of two city blocks.<ref name=\"last stand\">{{cite web|url=http://www.middleeasteye.net/news/making-last-stand-libyan-city-pentagon-623438379|title=IS making 'last stand' in Libya's Sirte: Pentagon|publisher=Middle East Eye|date=1 December 2016|accessdate=1 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161202115537/http://www.middleeasteye.net/news/making-last-stand-libyan-city-pentagon-623438379|archive-date=2 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> By this point, the GNA also closed off all pathways for the militants to escape. Only families, women and children were allowed to exit the area.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://libyaprospect.com/index.php/2016/12/01/no-pathways-for-daesh-fighters-in-sirte/|title=No pathways for Daesh fighters in Sirte|publisher=LIBYAPROSPECT|date=1 December 2016|accessdate=1 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161202101437/http://libyaprospect.com/index.php/2016/12/01/no-pathways-for-daesh-fighters-in-sirte/|archive-date=2 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> On 2 December, several women, who pretended to surrender, blew themselves up, killing four GNA fighters and wounding 38 others. ISIL had also recaptured a few buildings.<ref>{{cite web|title=Women bombers emerge from Islamic State redoubt to attack Libyan forces|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-sirte-idUSKBN13R2EM|accessdate=2 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161206000745/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-sirte-idUSKBN13R2EM|archive-date=6 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The campaign was temporarily halted to preserve the lives of civilians, while a senior militant was arrested and 4 others surrendered.<ref name=\"Suspended\">{{cite web|title=Libyan forces suspend anti-Daesh campaign in Sirte|url=https://www.middleeastmonitor.com/20161204-libyan-forces-suspend-anti-daesh-campaign-in-sirte/|accessdate=5 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161205130854/https://www.middleeastmonitor.com/20161204-libyan-forces-suspend-anti-daesh-campaign-in-sirte/|archive-date=5 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> 42 women and children were rescued on the next day,<ref>{{cite web|title=Libyan forces bust 6 IS militants before they escape Sirte|url=http://www.libyanexpress.com/libyan-forces-bust-6-is-militants-before-they-escape-sirte/|accessdate=5 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161205125142/http://www.libyanexpress.com/libyan-forces-bust-6-is-militants-before-they-escape-sirte/|archive-date=5 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> while six militants, who tried to escape, were arrested.<ref name=\"Swim\">{{cite web|title=Cornered IS militants try to swim out of Sirte|url=https://www.alaraby.co.uk/english/news/2016/12/4/cornered-is-militants-try-to-swim-out-of-sirte|accessdate=5 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161206141817/https://www.alaraby.co.uk/english/news/2016/12/4/cornered-is-militants-try-to-swim-out-of-sirte|archive-date=6 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The GNA captured nine buildings on 4 December, with 10 women and children leaving ISIL-held area,<ref>{{cite web|title=Women, children leave Islamic State holdout in Sirte: Libyan forces|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-sirte-idUSKBN13T0VK|accessdate=5 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161205023642/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-sirte-idUSKBN13T0VK|archive-date=5 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> while 2 militants, who tried to escape, were arrested.<ref name=\"Swim\"/>\n\nOn 5 December, GNA spokesman Ridda Issa claimed that the GNA was in control of Jizah neighbourhood, while another spokesman, Mohamed al-Gasri, stated that they were besieging the remaining militants.<ref name=\"Close\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-sirte-idUSKBN13U1H4|title=Libyan forces close to securing last Islamic State holdouts in Sirte: officials|work=Reuters|accessdate=5 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161205225105/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-security-sirte-idUSKBN13U1H4|archive-date=5 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> There were premature reports that Sirte had been fully captured by GNA. GNA fighters later confirmed that they still hadn't fully captured Jizah neighbourhood, with ISIL still controlling around 10 buildings.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sirte is not fully liberated, victory over ISIS is imminent - Sources|url=http://www.libyaobserver.ly/news/sirte-not-fully-liberated-victory-over-isis-imminent-sources|publisher=The Libya Observer|accessdate=5 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161206171040/http://www.libyaobserver.ly/news/sirte-not-fully-liberated-victory-over-isis-imminent-sources|archive-date=6 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBy 6 December, ISIL was in control of less than 10 houses, with the GNA trying to neutralize a small number of militants still present in the area and rescuing a group of women and children.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/last-jihadists-being-hunted-down-libyas-sirte-162907985.html|title=Last jihadists being hunted down in Libya's Sirte|work=Yahoo! Sports|accessdate=6 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161207153124/http://sports.yahoo.com/news/last-jihadists-being-hunted-down-libyas-sirte-162907985.html|archive-date=7 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Sirte was completely captured by pro-GNA militias later in the day. The last holdouts were defeated after heavy clashes earlier in the day and a combing operation on the last 3 ISIL-held buildings where they were barricaded. The last nine militants surrendered to GNA during the night, along with 10 women and children. By the end of the offensive, the United States had carried out 495 airstrikes against the group in Sirte. 21 women and 31 children were released from ISIL-held territory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.libyaobserver.ly/news/misrata-led-forces-declare-liberation-sirte|title=Misrata-led forces declare liberation of Sirte from IS|publisher=The Libya Observer|accessdate=6 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161207144627/http://www.libyaobserver.ly/news/misrata-led-forces-declare-liberation-sirte|archive-date=7 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Lastholdout\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSKBN13V15R|title=Libyan forces clear last Islamic State hold-out in Sirte|work=Reuters|accessdate=6 December 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Finalnine\">{{cite web|url=http://www.defense.gov/News/Article/Article/1023267/dod-update-on-counter-isil-fight-in-iraq-mosul-is-surrounded|title=DoD Update on Counter-ISIL Fight in Iraq: Mosul is Surrounded|author=Cheryl Pellerin|publisher=United States Department of Defence|accessdate=9 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161208190846/http://www.defense.gov/News/Article/Article/1023267/dod-update-on-counter-isil-fight-in-iraq-mosul-is-surrounded|archive-date=8 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> A total of 12 fighters were killed in the clashes on the last day.<ref name=\"Lastpositons\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dailysabah.com/africa/2016/12/06/libyan-forces-seize-last-daesh-positions-in-sirte|title=Libyan forces seize last Daesh positions in Sirte|newspaper=Daily Sabah|date=6 December 2016|accessdate=6 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161207153137/http://www.dailysabah.com/africa/2016/12/06/libyan-forces-seize-last-daesh-positions-in-sirte|archive-date=7 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== U.S. involvement ==\nOn 1 August 2016, the Pentagon announced the U.S. military effort to support the Libyan government against ISIL would be code-named Operation Odyssey Lightning.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://insidedefense.com/insider/libya-effort-named-operation-odyssey-lightning|title=Libya effort named 'Operation Odyssey Lightning'|access-date=2017-01-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202043044/https://insidedefense.com/insider/libya-effort-named-operation-odyssey-lightning|archive-date=2017-02-02|url-status=live}}</ref> Members of the US Armed Forces consisted of the 22nd Marine Expeditionary Unit ([[HMLA-467]], [[1st Battalion, 6th Marines|BLT 1/6]], and [[Combat Logistics Battalion 22|CLB 22]]) aboard the USS Wasp and USS San Antonio. Between August and December 2016, US forces launched 495 precision strikes in and around Sirte.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2017/01/us-bombs-two-islamic-state-camps-south-of-sirte-libya.php|title=US bombs 2 Islamic State camps south of Sirte, Libya|website=Long War Journal|date=19 January 2017|access-date=28 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170128002309/http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2017/01/us-bombs-two-islamic-state-camps-south-of-sirte-libya.php|archive-date=28 January 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> On 20 December, AFRICOM formally announced the end of its military operations to help GNA capture Sirte.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.libyanexpress.com/us-africom-ends-military-operation-against-is-radicals-in-libya/|title=US AFRICOM ends military operation against IS radicals in Libya|publisher=Libyan Express|date=21 December 2016|accessdate=30 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170101002727/http://www.libyanexpress.com/us-africom-ends-military-operation-against-is-radicals-in-libya/|archive-date=1 January 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, the US Africa Command announced that 495 precision airstrikes were carried out and 800 to 900 ISIL fighters were killed during the operation in Sirte between 1 August and 19 December 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2017/09/us-resumes-strikes-against-islamic-state-in-libya.php|title=US resumes strikes against Islamic State in Libya|publisher=FDD's LONG WAR JOURNAL|date=30 September 2017|accessdate=5 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171006021327/https://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2017/09/us-resumes-strikes-against-islamic-state-in-libya.php|archive-date=6 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Aftermath ==\n[[Image:Libya.sire.2017.jpg|thumb|upright|Destroyed buildings (2017).]]\nGNA spokesman Ridda Issa stated after capturing Sirte that they would continue their military operations to secure the area around the city, as Libyan officials and those of other countries were concerned that a number of militants who had escaped before the battle or during it may mount an insurgent campaign from outside the city. [[Jean-Yves Le Drian]], [[Minister of Defence (France)|Defence Minister]] of [[France]], meanwhile praised the pro-GNA militias for defeating ISIL.<ref name=\"Lastholdout\"/> Celebrations erupted among the pro-GNA militias after capture of the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/celebrations-in-sirte-as-islamic-state-is-cleared-out-707393|title=Celebrations in Sirte as Islamic State is cleared out|website=International Business Times|accessdate=7 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161208130831/http://www.ibtimes.co.in/celebrations-in-sirte-as-islamic-state-is-cleared-out-707393|archive-date=8 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Another spokesman Ahmes Hadiya stated that while it was the last major battle, it wasn't the end of military operations or a declaration of liberation.<ref name=\"Lastpositons\"/> After the defeat of ISIL, the Central Committee for Municipal Council Elections (CCMCE) scheduled mayoral elections for the city on 12 December 2016 at the Local Government Ministry in [[Tripoli]], with CCMCE's head Otman Gajiji supervising it.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.libyaherald.com/2016/12/06/mayoral-election-set-for-sirte-and-municipal-elections-for-central-zawia-and-bani-walid/|title=Mayoral election set for Sirte and municipal elections for central Zawia and Bani Walid|publisher=The Libya Herald|accessdate=6 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161208151554/https://www.libyaherald.com/2016/12/06/mayoral-election-set-for-sirte-and-municipal-elections-for-central-zawia-and-bani-walid/|archive-date=8 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The Military Intelligence Chief, Ismaeil Al-Shukri later in a televised statement denied that diehard militants had escaped the city. He also accused regional countries as well as countries that have political and economic interests in Libya, of sponsoring ISIL inside the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.libyaobserver.ly/news/terrorists-have-gone-nowhere-outside-sirte-military-intelligence-says|title=IS terrorists have gone nowhere outside Sirte, military intelligence says|publisher=The Libya Observer|accessdate=7 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161207130944/http://libyaobserver.ly/news/terrorists-have-gone-nowhere-outside-sirte-military-intelligence-says|archive-date=7 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Grand Mufti]] of Libya, [[Sadiq Al-Ghariani]], praised victory over ISIL, while criticizing and accusing the [[United Nations Support Mission in Libya]] (UNSMIL) of neglecting the victory. He called for UNSMIL to be replaced.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.libyaobserver.ly/news/grand-mufti-calls-unsmil-replacement-praises-victory-over-isis|title=Grand Mufti calls for UNSMIL replacement; praises victory over ISIS|publisher=The Libya Observer|accessdate=8 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161208151131/http://www.libyaobserver.ly/news/grand-mufti-calls-unsmil-replacement-praises-victory-over-isis|archive-date=8 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMost of the city was destroyed in the battle, with unexploded explosives strewn across the streets, with key services and vital infrastructure also destroyed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://reliefweb.int/report/libya/libyans-twice-uprooted-war-call-urgent-help|title=Libyans twice uprooted by war call for urgent help|publisher=ReliefWeb|accessdate=7 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161208124339/http://reliefweb.int/report/libya/libyans-twice-uprooted-war-call-urgent-help|archive-date=8 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[International Red Cross and Red Crescent Movement|Red Crescent]] found 230 bodies confirmed to be of ISIL militants, as well as 36 other bodies in former positions of the group. Bunyan Marsous operations room stated, on the other hand, that 483 bodies were recovered.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.libyaherald.com/2016/12/08/after-victory-the-clear-up-in-sirte/|title=After victory, the clear-up in Sirte|publisher=Libya Herald|accessdate=9 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220112207/https://www.libyaherald.com/2016/12/08/after-victory-the-clear-up-in-sirte/|archive-date=20 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Mukhtar Al-Madani was elected as the mayor on 12 December.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.libyaherald.com/2016/12/12/sirte-finally-gets-a-mayor/|title=Sirte finally gets a mayor|publisher=Libya Herald|accessdate=18 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220180915/https://www.libyaherald.com/2016/12/12/sirte-finally-gets-a-mayor/|archive-date=20 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Ahmed Abu Shahma was appointed as the [[military governor]] by Bunyan Marsous on 14 December.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.libyaherald.com/2016/12/14/sirte-military-governor-named-48-hours-after-mayor-chosen/|title=Sirte military governor named 48 hours after mayor chosen|publisher=Libya Herald|accessdate=18 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220180419/https://www.libyaherald.com/2016/12/14/sirte-military-governor-named-48-hours-after-mayor-chosen/|archive-date=20 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> GNA's [[List of heads of government of Libya|Prime Minister]] [[Fayez al-Sarraj]] officially announced the end of military operations and \"liberation of Sirte\" on 18 December. UN's envoy to Libya [[Martin Kobler]] termed the ISIL defeat as a major step towards ending terrorism in the country and called for national reconciliation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.albawaba.com/news/libyan-forces-announce-\u201cliberation\u2019-sirte-daesh-916192|title=Libyan forces announce \"liberation\u2019 of Sirte from Daesh|website=Al Bawaba|accessdate=18 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171009214735/https://www.albawaba.com/news/libyan-forces-announce-%E2%80%9Cliberation%E2%80%99-sirte-daesh-916192|archive-date=9 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 January 2017, US [[Northrop Grumman B-2 Spirit|B-2 bombers]] bombed 2 ISIL camps to the south of Sirte, killing 90 ISIL militants.<ref name=\"kill nearly 100\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2017/01/19/b-2-bombers-strike-isis-in-libya.html |title=B-2 bombers kill nearly 100 ISIS terrorists in Libya |access-date=2017-02-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170216112815/http://www.foxnews.com/world/2017/01/19/b-2-bombers-strike-isis-in-libya.html |archive-date=2017-02-16 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"90 bodies\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.newsweek.com/libya-isis-isis-libya-militants-air-strike-us-air-strike-548794 |title=90 BODIES FOUND AT SITE OF U.S. AIR STRIKE IN LIBYA |access-date=2017-02-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170215210427/http://www.newsweek.com/libya-isis-isis-libya-militants-air-strike-us-air-strike-548794 |archive-date=2017-02-15 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Libya}}\n* [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant in Libya]]\n* [[Derna campaign (2014\u201316)|ISIL occupation of Derna]]\n* [[Battle of Benghazi (2014\u20132017)]]\n* [[Battle of Derna (2018)]]\n* [[Battle of Baghuz Fawqani]]\n* [[List of wars and battles involving ISIL]]\n* [[Timeline of ISIL-related events]]\n* [[Timeline of the Libyan Civil War (2014\u2013present)]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant}}\n{{Military intervention against ISIL}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Battle of Sirte (2016)}}\n[[Category:Conflicts in 2016]]\n[[Category:Military operations of the Second Libyan Civil War in 2016]]\n[[Category:Military operations of the Second Libyan Civil War involving the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]]\n[[Category:Sirte]]\n", "name_user": "Operation 0", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Sirte_(2016)"}
{"title_page": "Rhythm Heaven Megamix", "text_new": "{{Infobox video game\n| title = Rhythm Heaven Megamix\n| image = Rhythm_Paradise_Megamix_PAL_Box.png<!-- Please do NOT put the US Logo on here. Wikipedia guidelines dictate that a box art must be used unless there is consensus. -->\n| caption = European promotional art featuring Tibby, and several playable and non-playable characters\n| developer = [[Nintendo SPD]]\n| publisher = [[Nintendo]]\n| director = Masami Yone\n| producer = [[Tsunku|Tsunku\u2642]]\n| programmer = Takafumi Masaoka\n| artist = Ko Takeuchi\n| composer = [[Tsunku]]<br/>Shinji Ushiroda<br/>Asuka Ito<br/>Yumi Takahashi<br/>Megumi Inoue\n| engine = \n| released = {{vgrelease|JP|June 11, 2015|NA|June 15, 2016|EU|October 21, 2016|AUS|October 22, 2016|KOR|December 1, 2016}}\n| genre = [[Rhythm game]]\n| modes = [[Single player]], [[Multiplayer]]\n| platforms = [[Nintendo 3DS]]\n}}\n\n'''''Rhythm Heaven Megamix''''', known in Europe as '''''Rhythm Paradise Megamix''''', and in Japan as {{nihongo|'''''Rhythm Tengoku: The Best Plus'''''|\u30ea\u30ba\u30e0\u5929\u56fd \u30b6\u30fb\u30d9\u30b9\u30c8\uff0b|Rizumu Tengoku: Za Besuto Purasu}}, is a [[rhythm game]] developed and published by [[Nintendo]] for the [[Nintendo 3DS]]. It is the fourth game in [[Nintendo]]'s ''Rhythm Heaven'' series and compiles stages from the series' previous entries; ''[[Rhythm Tengoku]]'', ''[[Rhythm Heaven]]'', and ''[[Rhythm Heaven Fever]]'', as well as adding new ones. The game was released in Japan in June 2015<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2015/1/14/7546175/new-rhythm-heaven-coming-to-nintendo-3ds-in-2015|title=New Rhythm Heaven coming to Nintendo 3DS in 2015|author=Michael McWhertor |work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=January 14, 2015|accessdate=April 3, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=3DS\u300c\u30ea\u30ba\u30e0\u5929\u56fd \u30b6\u30fb\u30d9\u30b9\u30c8\uff0b\u300d\u304c6\u670811\u65e5\u306b\u767a\u58f2\u3002\u65b0\u65e7\u5408\u308f\u305b\u3066100\u7a2e\u985e\u4ee5\u4e0a\u306e\u30ea\u30ba\u30e0\u30b2\u30fc\u30e0\u304c\u697d\u3057\u3081\u308b|url=http://www.4gamer.net/games/287/G028796/20150402011/|website=4Gamer|accessdate=2 April 2015}}</ref> and in The United States, Europe, Oceania and South Korea throughout 2016.\n\n==Gameplay==\n{{see also|Rhythm Tengoku#Gameplay|l1=Gameplay of the Rhythm Heaven series}}\n\nLike the previous three entries in the series, ''Rhythm Heaven Megamix'' is composed of several Rhythm Games, requiring players to play in time with the music in order to clear each one. The game uses the traditional control scheme featured in the original ''Rhythm Tengoku'', which uses the A, B, and directional buttons on the Nintendo 3DS. The game can be optionally played with the stylus, though controls are more simplified compared to ''Rhythm Heaven''. The game features over 100 Rhythm Games, including 70 taken from previous titles (including the GBA release, which was never released in the west) and 30 brand new ones, as well as new Remix stages based on the game's Rainbow Towers which combine the previous rhythm games in the tower (or more rhythm games) into one song. Tower-themed elements are incorporated into the remix while every character in the present rhythm games get to wear special tower-themed alternate costumes (except for the Left-Hand, Right-Hand and Final Remixes). Ratings for the Rhythm Games are now awarded based on a score meter indicating how well the player performed. Each Rhythm Game also features a special Skill Star point, which awards bonuses for hitting a certain part of the game with precise timing. Playing through Rhythm Games earns Medals that can be used to unlock bonuses such as additional rhythm games.<ref name=4GamerReview>{{cite web|title=\u300c\u30ea\u30ba\u30e0\u5929\u56fd \u30b6\u30fb\u30d9\u30b9\u30c8\uff0b\u300d\u306f\uff0c\u300c\u30d9\u30b9\u30c8\uff0b\u300d\u306e\u540d\u306b\u6065\u3058\u306a\u3044\u30dc\u30ea\u30e5\u30fc\u30e0\uff06\u30af\u30aa\u30ea\u30c6\u30a3\u3067\uff0c\u3044\u3064\u3067\u3082\u3069\u3053\u3067\u3082\u6301\u3061\u6b69\u304d\u305f\u3044\u4e00\u672c\u3060|url=http://www.4gamer.net/games/287/G028796/20150703076/|website=4Gamer|accessdate=12 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=\u300e\u30ea\u30ba\u30e0\u5929\u56fd \u30b6\u30fb\u30d9\u30b9\u30c8\uff0b\u300f\u30dc\u30bf\u30f3\u64cd\u4f5c\u304c\u57fa\u672c\u3001\u904e\u53bb\u4f5c\u306e\u30ea\u30ba\u30e0\u30b2\u30fc\u30e0\u3067\u3082\u65b0\u66f2\u304c\u7528\u610f\u3055\u308c\u308b\u3053\u3068\u304c\u660e\u3089\u304b\u306b|url=http://www.famitsu.com/news/201504/02075728.html|website=\u30d5\u30a1\u30df\u901a.com|accessdate=15 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n''Megamix'' features a Story Mode in which players try to help a character named Tibby reach Heaven World, his home. The mode has players play through stages in a linear format, which is broken up by challenge games, before allowing players to tackle various towers in any order they choose. Some older Rhythm Games that returned in ''Megamix'' (such as ''Karate Man'', ''Glee Club'' and ''Air Rally''), received a prequel version, An easier version with new graphics and an alternated music (to match the music style of the new rhythm games featured in ''Megamix''), while the original Rhythm Games have been labeled as sequels.\n\nSome of the returning games from ''Tengoku'' and ''Heaven (DS)'' have been added new music and redesigned graphics. Outside of the Story Mode, players can attempt Perfect Campaigns, which require players to clear selected stages without making any mistakes, or take on challenges on the Challenge Train, which can be played with up to four players via [[Nintendo DS#Download Play|Download Play]]. The Challenge Mode in the game also has two ''[[WarioWare]]'' crossover challenges named as \"[[Wario]]... Where?\", which replaces some of the rhythm games' main characters with characters from the ''WarioWare'' series (This is due to both the ''WarioWare'' and ''Rhythm Heaven'' franchises being made by the same developers). The game also features bonus rhythm games (all from previous titles) and a ''Figure Fighter Duel'' challenge that uses the 3DS' [[StreetPass]] functionality.<ref name=4GamerReview />\n\n==Development==\nMasami Yone, the director of ''Rhythm Heaven Fever'', assumed the same role for ''Megamix''. He was assisted by Takumi Hatakeyama, who previously worked as a programmer and designer for ''[[WarioWare D.I.Y.]]'' and ''Rhythm Heaven Fever''. Ko Takeuchi returns as the art director, and Yoshio Sakamoto as the general producer. \n\nThe game's music is done by Tsunku\u2642 (who also serves as the game's producer), as well as Shinji Ushiroda, Asuka Ito, Yumi Takahashi, and Megumi Inoue. While some music pieces from the original ''Rhythm Tengoku'' and ''Rhythm Heaven (DS)'' were re-used, ''Rhythm Heaven Megamix'' re-uses several music themes from the previous game, ''Rhythm Heaven Fever''. For the prequel versions of older rhythm games from previous titles and for the new rhythm games and remixes in the game, most of the music that Tsunku\u2642 had composed for them was given a techno-themed motif. This is different from the music styles used in the previous three ''Rhythm Heaven'' titles, which in ''Rhythm Tengoku'', ''Rhythm Heaven (DS)'' and ''Rhythm Heaven Fever'', the music for those titles was a mix of catchy tunes and vocal songs. The new vocal songs for ''Megamix'' are \"Story Of True Love\" (used for the Lush Remix), \"I'm a lady now/Hotzmic\" (used for the Honeybee Remix) and \"In the Big Grain Of Tears\" (used for the Machine Remix). ''Megamix'' was the final game developed by Nintendo SPD1 before it was merged into Nintendo Entertainment Planning and Development.\n\nIn 2016, Nintendo announced that the game would launch in North America, Europe, Australia and Korea \"later\" that year.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rhythm Heaven Megamix Announced For 3DS|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/rhythm-heaven-megamix-announced-for-3ds/1100-6435349/|website=Gamespot|accessdate=14 March 2016}}</ref> The game was released as a [[Nintendo eShop]] exclusive in North America on June 15, 2016 during Nintendo's Treehouse Livestream presentation at [[Electronic Entertainment Expo 2016|E3 2016]]. The game received a physical retail release in Europe on October 21, 2016.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=NintendoUK|author=Nintendo UK|number=743382854311215104|date=16 June 2016|title=Rhythm Paradise Megamix comes to stores and Nintendo #eShop for #3DS on 21/10. #NintendoE3}}</ref> Like the European release of ''[[Rhythm Heaven Fever|Beat the Beat: Rhythm Paradise]]'', the English versions of the game feature both English and Japanese audio.<ref>http://www.polygon.com/e3/2016/6/15/11950726/rhythm-heaven-megamix-release-date</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n''Rhythm Heaven Megamix'' received favourable reviews from Famitsu reviewers, scoring 34/40 (8/8/8/10) in Famitsu Score, and praised for various aspects including its great variety in gameplay despite the simple controls, and supportive feedback from input timing effects.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rhythm Heaven: The Best Plus gets first review in Famitsu|url=http://nintendoeverything.com/rhythm-heaven-the-best-plus-gets-first-review-in-famitsu/|website=Nintendo Everything|accessdate=22 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe game debuted at No. 1 in Japanese charts maintained by [[Media Create]], recording 158,000 copies sold in its first week of release.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u3010\u9031\u9593\u58f2\u4e0a\u30e9\u30f3\u30ad\u30f3\u30b0\u3011\u9996\u4f4d\u300e\u30ea\u30ba\u30e0\u5929\u56fd \u30b6\u30fb\u30d9\u30b9\u30c8\uff0b\u300f15.8\u4e07\u672c\u3001\u300e\u30c9\u30e9\u30b4\u30f3\u30dc\u30fc\u30ebZ \u8d85\u7a76\u6975\u6b66\u95d8\u4f1d\u300f7.4\u4e07\u672c\u30672\u4f4d(6/8\uff5e6/14)|url=http://www.inside-games.jp/article/2015/06/18/88620.html|website=\u30a4\u30f3\u30b5\u30a4\u30c9|accessdate=30 June 2015}}</ref> As of 26 February 2016, total Japanese sales reached 650,000 copies.\n\n==Trivia==\n* Tibby appears as a plush in [[WarioWare Gold]] during Mona's intro video.\n* Many of the games from [[Rhythm Heaven]] that were transferred into this game either received minor graphical upgrades (ex. Fillbots and Dog Ninja) or were completely redesigned and upgraded from their original iterations (ex. The Dazzles and Shoot-Em-Up). However, almost all of the returning games feature the same music and theme that was present in the original versions, with a few having new remixes.\n* In the Japanese version of the game, the themes for the second staff credits, and the Lush and Machine Remixes have vocals. In the international versions, these three themes use instrumental versions instead.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{officialwebsite|http://www.nintendo.com/games/detail/rhythm-heaven-megamix-3ds}}\n\n{{Rhythm Heaven}}\n\n[[Category:2015 video games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo 3DS eShop games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo 3DS games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo 3DS-only games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Network games]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer and single-player video games]]\n[[Category:Rhythm Heaven]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Japan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox video game\n| title = Rhythm Heaven Megamix\n| image = Rhythm_Paradise_Megamix_PAL_Box.png<!-- Please do NOT put the US Logo on here. Wikipedia guidelines dictate that a box art must be used unless there is consensus. -->\n| caption = European promotional art featuring Tibby, and several playable and non-playable characters\n| developer = [[Nintendo SPD]]\n| publisher = [[Nintendo]]\n| director = Masami Yone\n| producer = [[Tsunku|Tsunku\u2642]]\n| programmer = Takafumi Masaoka\n| artist = Ko Takeuchi\n| composer = [[Tsunku]]<br/>Shinji Ushiroda<br/>Asuka Ito<br/>Yumi Takahashi<br/>Megumi Inoue\n| engine = \n| released = {{vgrelease|JP|June 11, 2015|NA|June 15, 2016|EU|October 21, 2016|AUS|October 22, 2016|KOR|December 1, 2016}}\n| genre = [[Rhythm game]]\n| modes = [[Single player]], [[Multiplayer]]\n| platforms = [[Nintendo 3DS]]\n}}\n\n'''''Rhythm Heaven Megamix''''', known in Europe as '''''Rhythm Paradise Megamix''''', and in Japan as {{nihongo|'''''Rhythm Tengoku: The Best Plus'''''|\u30ea\u30ba\u30e0\u5929\u56fd \u30b6\u30fb\u30d9\u30b9\u30c8\uff0b|Rizumu Tengoku: Za Besuto Purasu}}, is a [[rhythm game]] developed and published by [[Nintendo]] for the [[Nintendo 3DS]]. It is the fourth game in [[Nintendo]]'s ''Rhythm Heaven'' series and compiles stages from the series' previous entries; ''[[Rhythm Tengoku]]'', ''[[Rhythm Heaven]]'', and ''[[Rhythm Heaven Fever]]'', as well as adding new ones. The game was released in Japan in June 2015<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2015/1/14/7546175/new-rhythm-heaven-coming-to-nintendo-3ds-in-2015|title=New Rhythm Heaven coming to Nintendo 3DS in 2015|author=Michael McWhertor |work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=January 14, 2015|accessdate=April 3, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=3DS\u300c\u30ea\u30ba\u30e0\u5929\u56fd \u30b6\u30fb\u30d9\u30b9\u30c8\uff0b\u300d\u304c6\u670811\u65e5\u306b\u767a\u58f2\u3002\u65b0\u65e7\u5408\u308f\u305b\u3066100\u7a2e\u985e\u4ee5\u4e0a\u306e\u30ea\u30ba\u30e0\u30b2\u30fc\u30e0\u304c\u697d\u3057\u3081\u308b|url=http://www.4gamer.net/games/287/G028796/20150402011/|website=4Gamer|accessdate=2 April 2015}}</ref> and in The United States, Europe, Oceania and South Korea throughout 2016.\n\n==Gameplay==\n{{see also|Rhythm Tengoku#Gameplay|l1=Gameplay of the Rhythm Heaven series}}\n\nLike the previous three entries in the series, ''Rhythm Heaven Megamix'' is composed of several Rhythm Games, requiring players to play in time with the music in order to clear each one. The game uses the traditional control scheme featured in the original ''Rhythm Tengoku'', which uses the A, B, and directional buttons on the Nintendo 3DS. The game can be optionally played with the stylus, though controls are more simplified compared to ''Rhythm Heaven''. The game features over 100 Rhythm Games, including 70 taken from previous titles (including the GBA release, which was never released in the west) and 30 brand new ones, as well as new Remix stages based on the game's Rainbow Towers which combine the previous rhythm games in the tower (or more rhythm games) into one song. Tower-themed elements are incorporated into the remix while every character in the present rhythm games get to wear special tower-themed alternate costumes (except for the Left-Hand, Right-Hand and Final Remixes). Ratings for the Rhythm Games are now awarded based on a score meter indicating how well the player performed. Each Rhythm Game also features a special Skill Star point, which awards bonuses for hitting a certain part of the game with precise timing. Playing through Rhythm Games earns Medals that can be used to unlock bonuses such as additional rhythm games.<ref name=4GamerReview>{{cite web|title=\u300c\u30ea\u30ba\u30e0\u5929\u56fd \u30b6\u30fb\u30d9\u30b9\u30c8\uff0b\u300d\u306f\uff0c\u300c\u30d9\u30b9\u30c8\uff0b\u300d\u306e\u540d\u306b\u6065\u3058\u306a\u3044\u30dc\u30ea\u30e5\u30fc\u30e0\uff06\u30af\u30aa\u30ea\u30c6\u30a3\u3067\uff0c\u3044\u3064\u3067\u3082\u3069\u3053\u3067\u3082\u6301\u3061\u6b69\u304d\u305f\u3044\u4e00\u672c\u3060|url=http://www.4gamer.net/games/287/G028796/20150703076/|website=4Gamer|accessdate=12 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=\u300e\u30ea\u30ba\u30e0\u5929\u56fd \u30b6\u30fb\u30d9\u30b9\u30c8\uff0b\u300f\u30dc\u30bf\u30f3\u64cd\u4f5c\u304c\u57fa\u672c\u3001\u904e\u53bb\u4f5c\u306e\u30ea\u30ba\u30e0\u30b2\u30fc\u30e0\u3067\u3082\u65b0\u66f2\u304c\u7528\u610f\u3055\u308c\u308b\u3053\u3068\u304c\u660e\u3089\u304b\u306b|url=http://www.famitsu.com/news/201504/02075728.html|website=\u30d5\u30a1\u30df\u901a.com|accessdate=15 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n''Megamix'' features a Story Mode in which players try to help a character named Tibby reach Heaven World, his home. The mode has players play through stages in a linear format, which is broken up by challenge games, before allowing players to tackle various towers in any order they choose. Some older Rhythm Games that returned in ''Megamix'' (such as ''Karate Man'', ''Glee Club'' and ''Air Rally''), received a prequel version, An easier version with new graphics and an alternated music (to match the music style of the new rhythm games featured in ''Megamix''), while the original Rhythm Games have been labeled as sequels.\n\nSome of the returning games from ''Tengoku'' and ''Heaven (DS)'' have been added new music and redesigned graphics. Outside of the Story Mode, players can attempt Perfect Campaigns, which require players to clear selected stages without making any mistakes, or take on challenges on the Challenge Train, which can be played with up to four players via [[Nintendo DS#Download Play|Download Play]]. The Challenge Mode in the game also has two ''[[WarioWare]]'' crossover challenges named as \"[[Wario]]... Where?\", which replaces some of the rhythm games' main characters with characters from the ''WarioWare'' series (This is due to both the ''WarioWare'' and ''Rhythm Heaven'' franchises being made by the same developers). The game also features bonus rhythm games (all from previous titles) and a ''Figure Fighter Duel'' challenge that uses the 3DS' [[StreetPass]] functionality.<ref name=4GamerReview />\n\n==Development==\nMasami Yone, the director of ''Rhythm Heaven Fever'', assumed the same role for ''Megamix''. He was assisted by Takumi Hatakeyama, who previously worked as a programmer and designer for ''[[WarioWare D.I.Y.]]'' and ''Rhythm Heaven Fever''. Ko Takeuchi returns as the art director, and Yoshio Sakamoto as the general producer. \n\nThe game's music is done by Tsunku\u2642 (who also serves as the game's producer), as well as Shinji Ushiroda, Asuka Ito, Yumi Takahashi, and Megumi Inoue. While some music pieces from the original ''Rhythm Tengoku'' and ''Rhythm Heaven (DS)'' were re-used, ''Rhythm Heaven Megamix'' re-uses several music themes from the previous game, ''Rhythm Heaven Fever''. For the prequel versions of older rhythm games from previous titles and for the new rhythm games and remixes in the game, most of the music that Tsunku\u2642 had composed for them was given a techno-themed motif. This is different from the music styles used in the previous three ''Rhythm Heaven'' titles, which in ''Rhythm Tengoku'', ''Rhythm Heaven (DS)'' and ''Rhythm Heaven Fever'', the music for those titles was a mix of catchy tunes and vocal songs. The new vocal songs for ''Megamix'' are \"Story Of True Love\" (used for the Lush Remix), \"I'm a lady now/Hotzmic\" (used for the Honeybee Remix) and \"In the Big Grain Of Tears\" (used for the Machine Remix). ''Megamix'' was the final game developed by Nintendo SPD1 before it was merged into Nintendo Entertainment Planning and Development.\n\nIn 2016, Nintendo announced that the game would launch in North America, Europe, Australia and Korea \"later\" that year.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rhythm Heaven Megamix Announced For 3DS|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/rhythm-heaven-megamix-announced-for-3ds/1100-6435349/|website=Gamespot|accessdate=14 March 2016}}</ref> The game was released as a [[Nintendo eShop]] exclusive in North America on June 15, 2016 during Nintendo's Treehouse Livestream presentation at [[Electronic Entertainment Expo 2016|E3 2016]]. The game received a physical retail release in Europe on October 21, 2016.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=NintendoUK|author=Nintendo UK|number=743382854311215104|date=16 June 2016|title=Rhythm Paradise Megamix comes to stores and Nintendo #eShop for #3DS on 21/10. #NintendoE3}}</ref> Like the European release of ''[[Rhythm Heaven Fever|Beat the Beat: Rhythm Paradise]]'', the English versions of the game feature both English and Japanese audio.<ref>http://www.polygon.com/e3/2016/6/15/11950726/rhythm-heaven-megamix-release-date</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n''Rhythm Heaven Megamix'' received favourable reviews from Famitsu reviewers, scoring 34/40 (8/8/8/10) in Famitsu Score, and praised for various aspects including its great variety in gameplay despite the simple controls, and supportive feedback from input timing effects.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rhythm Heaven: The Best Plus gets first review in Famitsu|url=http://nintendoeverything.com/rhythm-heaven-the-best-plus-gets-first-review-in-famitsu/|website=Nintendo Everything|accessdate=22 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe game debuted at No. 1 in Japanese charts maintained by [[Media Create]], recording 158,000 copies sold in its first week of release.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u3010\u9031\u9593\u58f2\u4e0a\u30e9\u30f3\u30ad\u30f3\u30b0\u3011\u9996\u4f4d\u300e\u30ea\u30ba\u30e0\u5929\u56fd \u30b6\u30fb\u30d9\u30b9\u30c8\uff0b\u300f15.8\u4e07\u672c\u3001\u300e\u30c9\u30e9\u30b4\u30f3\u30dc\u30fc\u30ebZ \u8d85\u7a76\u6975\u6b66\u95d8\u4f1d\u300f7.4\u4e07\u672c\u30672\u4f4d(6/8\uff5e6/14)|url=http://www.inside-games.jp/article/2015/06/18/88620.html|website=\u30a4\u30f3\u30b5\u30a4\u30c9|accessdate=30 June 2015}}</ref> As of 26 February 2016, total Japanese sales reached 650,000 copies.\n\n==Trivia==\n* Tibby appears as a plush in [[WarioWare Gold]] during Mona's intro video.\n* Many of the games from [[Rhythm Heaven]] that were transferred into this game either received minor graphical upgrades (ex. Fillbots and Dog Ninja) or were completely redesigned and upgraded from their original iterations (ex. The Dazzles and Shoot-Em-Up). However, almost all of the returning games feature the same music and theme that was present in the original versions, with a few having new remixes.\n* In the Japanese version of the game, the themes for the second staff credits, and the Lush and Machine Remixes have vocals. In the international versions, these three themes use instumental versions instead.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{officialwebsite|http://www.nintendo.com/games/detail/rhythm-heaven-megamix-3ds}}\n\n{{Rhythm Heaven}}\n\n[[Category:2015 video games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo 3DS eShop games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo 3DS games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo 3DS-only games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Network games]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer and single-player video games]]\n[[Category:Rhythm Heaven]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Japan]]\n", "name_user": "Bellowhead678", "label": "safe", "comment": "instumental->instrumental -Fix a typo in one click", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rhythm_Heaven_Megamix"}
{"title_page": "2019\u201320 North American winter", "text_new": "{{Infobox winter\n| image = File:Satellite imagery on February 27, 2020 of Great Lakes blizzard.jpg\n| caption = Strong extratropical cyclone brings strong winds and feet of snow to Great Lakes February 27, 2020\n| astro = December&nbsp;21&nbsp;\u2013 March&nbsp;19\n| meteo = December&nbsp;1&nbsp;\u2013 February&nbsp;29\n| year = 2019\n| notable event = [[November 26 - December 3, 2019 North American blizzard]]\n| maxsnow = 114 inches at [[Homewood, California]]\n| event duration = November 26 - December 3, 2019\n}}\n\nThe '''2019\u201320 North American winter''' refers to winter in [[North America]] as it is occurring across the continent from late 2019 through early 2020. While there is no well-agreed-upon date used to indicate the start of winter in the Northern Hemisphere, there are two definitions of winter which may be used. Based on the astronomical definition, winter begins at the [[winter solstice]], which in 2019 occurred on December&nbsp;21, and ends at the March equinox, which in 2020 occurred on March&nbsp;20.<ref name=\"USNO Seasons\">{{cite web|title=Earth's Seasons: Equinoxes, Solstices, Perihelion, and Aphelion, 2000-2025 |url=http://aa.usno.navy.mil/data/docs/EarthSeasons.php |publisher=[[United States Naval Observatory]] |date=March 27, 2015 |accessdate=August 15, 2015 |location=[[Washington, D.C.]] |format=PHP |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6anEZkLaj?url=http://aa.usno.navy.mil/data/docs/EarthSeasons.php |archive-date=August 15, 2015 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref> Based on the meteorological definition, the first day of winter is December 1 and the last day February 29.<ref name=\"NOAA/NWS-Seasons\">{{cite web|title=Meteorological vs. Astronomical Seasons|url=https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/news/meteorological-versus-astronomical-summer%E2%80%94what%E2%80%99s-difference|publisher=NOAA National Centers for Environmental Information|date=June 21, 2013|accessdate=July 3, 2015}}</ref> Both definitions involve a period of approximately three months, with some variability. Winter is often defined by meteorologists to be the three calendar months with the lowest average temperatures. Since both definitions span the [[calendar year]], it is possible to have a winter storm in two different years.\n\nSeasonal forecasts indicated a milder than normal winter across most of the United States and even parts of Canada. These forecasts were verified after the United States experienced their 6th warmest winter on record<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mobile.twitter.com/NOAANCEIclimate/status/1235961898476036097?s=19|title=Twitter|website=mobile.twitter.com|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> and many cities in the Northeast Megalopolis received <1\" of snow all winter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.accuweather.com/en/winter-weather/could-a-big-storm-end-this-winters-snow-drought-in-the-northeast/693375|title=Could a big storm end snow drought in the Northeast this winter?|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Fewer significant events than normal occurred during the season and much of them occured later in the season or in early spring; they include a bomb cyclone/early-season winter storm in the country's norther tier, a series of brief cold waves in the Northwest and Midwest Late January through Early February, a historic blizzard in Atlantic Canada Late January, a significant lake effect snow event on the Great Lakes late February, a bomb cyclone Nor'easter in March that provided a yet another near-miss to New England, and a late-season blizzard that impacted the High Plains and Rocky Mountains.\n\n==Seasonal forecasts==\n{{multiple image\n | width = 200\n | image1 = US temp outlook winter 2019\u201320 NOAA.png\n | caption1 = Temperature outlook\n | image2 = US precip outlook winter 2019\u201320 NOAA.png\n | caption2 = Precipitation outlook\n | caption_align = center\n}}\nOn October&nbsp;17, 2019, the [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]]'s [[Climate Prediction Center]] released its U.S. Winter Outlook. The [[El Ni\u00f1o\u2013Southern Oscillation]] was in its neutral phase and was thus not expected to be a key predictor for the season. As a result, other oscillations such as the Madden\u2013Julian Oscillation and the Arctic Oscillation were anticipated to be more significant drivers of the seasonal weather, particularly in the form of large temperature and precipitation swings. From the outlook, the greatest likelihoods for above-normal temperatures were for Alaska and Hawaii, with lower but still above-normal odds of above-average temperatures for most of the lower 48 states. The exception was for the Northern Plains, Upper Mississippi Valley, and western Great Lakes regions, which were ascribed equal changes for above-, near-, or below-average temperatures. No area in the United States was favored to have below-average temperatures. In terms of precipitation, wetter-than-average conditions were most likely in Alaska, Hawaii, part of the Northern Plains, Upper Mississippi Valley, Great Lakes, and parts of the Mid-Atlantic and Northeastern U.S. Drier-than-average conditions were favored for Louisiana and parts of Texas, Mississippi, Arkansas, and Oklahoma, as well as parts of central and northern California, with the rest of the U.S. having equal changes of above-, near-, or below-average precipitation. The drought outlook highlighted the presence of abnormally dry conditions across much of the Southern U.S, with improvement expected in part of the Southeast and Mid-Atlantic regions, Alaska, and Hawaii. Drought was expected to persist in central Texas and the Southwestern U.S, with further development anticipated in parts of central California.<ref>{{cite news|title=Winter Outlook: Warmer than average for many, wetter in the North: Drought improvement expected in the Southeast|url=https://www.noaa.gov/media-release/winter-outlook-warmer-than-average-for-many-wetter-in-north|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|date=October 17, 2019|accessdate=October 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Events ==\n=== Early November winter storm ===\nRecord breaking temperatures and snowfall caused disruption throughout the Midwestern United States in early November. Approximately 1000 flights were grounded at Chicago's [[O'Hare International Airport]] as 3.7 inches of snow fell on November 11, breaking the previous record of 1.9 inches on November 11, 1995.<ref name=\"WGN911NOV\">{{cite news |title=Nearly 1,000 flights canceled as record-breaking snow blankets Chicago |url=https://wgntv.com/2019/11/11/winter-weather-advisory-for-3-to-6-inches-of-snow-across-the-chicago-area-monday-lakeshore-flood-warning-for-the-illinois-and-nw-indiana-lake-michigan-shoreline-into-tuesday/ |agency=Nextstar Broadcasting, inc. |publisher=WGN9 |date=11 November 2019}}</ref> In Canada, Southern Ontario and Southern Quebec had their first major winter storm of the season on November 11 and 12 respectively, which was followed by record January-like cold.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theweathernetwork.com/ca/news/article/significant-november-snow-storm-hits-southern-ontario-quebec-with-record-january-like-cold|title=After strong storm, traffic chaos, where to expect Tuesday's snow|last=Inc|first=Pelmorex Weather Networks|website=theweathernetwork.com|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref> 10\u201320&nbsp;cm of snow fell across much of the region crippling large cities such as Montreal and Toronto. In Montreal, local officials announced the city's earliest ever snow removal operation in the aftermath of the storm. Over 10 school boards province-wide closed the day after the storm.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theweathernetwork.com/ca/news/article/major-snow-storm-coming-to-quebec-early-week|title=Quebec digs out from its first major snowstorm of the season|last=Inc|first=Pelmorex Weather Networks|website=theweathernetwork.com|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n=== Late November - Early December bomb cyclone & blizzard ===\n\n{{Main|November 26 - December 3, 2019 North American blizzard}}\n\n[[File:Two Large Winter Storms to Wallop Parts of the U.S.jpg|thumb|Satellite imagery of winter storms crossing the US November 27, 2019]]\n\nMoving ashore November 26\u201327 near the Oregon/California border as an over-achieving bomb cyclone, it produced wind gusts in excess of 100&nbsp;mph near its point of landfall. The storm produced a record low pressure reading of 973.4 millibars in Crescent City, California. From November 27\u201330, the low merged with the subtropical jet as it tracked slowly eastward across the Rockies, plains & Midwest. The combination of cold air, moisture and high winds produced a wide swath of blizzard conditions from Colorado through western South Dakota, including the Denver Metro. In Rapid City, 14.5 inches of snow fell on the 30th, breaking the one-day snowfall record for November. In Duluth, where 21.7 inches of snow accumulated, it was the city's heaviest snowstorm in 10 years. As the first major winter storm of the season in the northeast, it dumped 22.6 inches of snow in Albany, where it was the heaviest snowfall since the 1993 Superstorm. Widespread totals in excess of 20 inches occurred in the Albany Metro, Southern New Hampshire & Northwestern Massachusetts with a regional peak of 36 inches of snow in New Ipswich, New Hampshire. The low finally moved out to sea December 3.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://weather.com/storms/winter/news/2019-12-01-northeast-great-lakes-snowstorm-forecast-ezekiel|title=Cross-Country Winter Storm Brought Snow, Ice and Wind Thanksgiving Week Into Early December (RECAP)|website=The Weather Channel|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n=== Late December Great Plains and Midwest blizzard ===\n\nThe winter storm had the largest impact on the Midwestern states, as it affected Nebraska, the Dakotas, and Minnesota. In [[Fargo, North Dakota]], there were many closings of schools, businesses, and roadways, from December 28 to December 30. Freezing rain lead to over 470 reported traffic accidents in Minneapolis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.inforum.com/news/weather/4843620-It-could-take-weeks-for-Fargo-plows-to-completely-dig-out-of-once-in-a-10-year-blizzard|title=It could take weeks for Fargo plows to completely dig out of 'once-in-a-10-year' blizzard|first1=April|last1=Baumgarten|first2=C. S. |last2=Hagen |website=INFORUM|accessdate=Jan 7, 2020}}</ref><ref>https://www.fox9.com/news/slippery-road-conditions-lead-to-470-crashes-across-Minnesota</ref>\n\n[[File:Great Lakes Region Slammed By Severe Winter Storm (49305407947).jpg|thumb|Plains being impacted by blizzard, as seen from space]]\n\n=== Early January storm complex ===\nA large complex of low pressure systems began developing January 9 over Central North America. A large trough dug into the jet stream over the Southwestern United States, providing arctic air that had been settled over Canada to move southwards and clash with warm, moist air moving northward from the Gulf of Mexico.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://weather.com/news/news/2020-01-10-winter-storm-oklahoma-kansas-missouri-iowa-illinois|title=Winter Storm Closes Schools, Airlines Prepare for Delays|website=The Weather Channel|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-11}}</ref> In the warm sector, severe thunderstorms and tornadoes broke out in the south central United States on the morning of January 10. Tornado warnings were issued for more than 1.7 million in the Dallas-Fort Worth Metroplex, at 7:52 pm CST a PDS tornado warning was issued for Scranton, Arkansas and surrounding communities and more than 111,000 customers were left without power in Texas alone. Severe weather continued in the deep south into following day, with Alabama being affected particularly severely.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.accuweather.com/en/weather-news/live-tornado-watches-issued-in-oklahoma-texas-as-severe-weather-outbreak-begins-in-southern-us/659511|title=LIVE: Storms leave behind trail of damage as severe weather outbreak advances east|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> North of the boundary, a mix of heavy snow and freezing rain caused travel woes across the Midwest. Along the Great Lakes, winds were forecast to whip up 23 foot waves as lakeshore flooding had already begun in Chicago.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://weather.com/news/news/2020-01-11-winter-storm-impacts-flights-canceled-power-outages-rough-driving|title=Waves More Than 20 Feet High Could Hit Chicago Lakeshore as Winter Storm Pounds Plains, Upper Midwest|website=The Weather Channel|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-11}}</ref> Central Michigan through Eastern Ontario received a swath of crippling ice accretion. Several January rainfall records fell in Southern Ontario, as event rainfall totals over 50&nbsp;mm were widespread, which is highly unusual for that time of year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theweathernetwork.com/ca/news/article/ontario-ice-storm-with-prolonged-freezing-rain-record-january-rainfall-flood-threat|title=Ontario: Largest temperature drop in almost two years, freezing rain ramps up|last=Inc|first=Pelmorex Weather Networks|website=theweathernetwork.com|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-01-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theweathernetwork.com/ca/news/article/in-photos-ontario-extreme-rainfall-and-freezing-rain-event|title=PHOTOS: Cleanup underway after record rainfall floods streets, ice topples trees|last=Inc|first=Pelmorex Weather Networks|website=theweathernetwork.com|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-01-12}}</ref>\n\n=== Mid January snowstorm ===\nBeginning on the west coast January 15, much of southern British Columbia, including the Lower Mainland and Vancouver Island, received an unusually heavy snowstorm. Combined with high wind, some localities were put under blizzard warning, which is rare in British Columbia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theweathernetwork.com/ca/news/article/photos-b-c-digs-out-after-winter-storm-dumps-heavy-snow-causes-power-outages|title=PHOTOS: B.C. digs out after winter storm dumps heavy snow, causes power outages|last=Inc|first=Pelmorex Weather Networks|website=theweathernetwork.com|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> 15&nbsp;cm of snow fell in Vancouver<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://climate.weather.gc.ca/climate_data/daily_data_e.html?StationID=51442|title=Daily Data Report for January 2020 - Climate - Environment and Climate Change Canada|last=Canada|first=Environment and Climate Change|date=2011-10-31|website=climate.weather.gc.ca|language=en|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> and 20&nbsp;cm fell in Victoria,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://climate.weather.gc.ca/climate_data/daily_data_e.html?StationID=51337|title=Daily Data Report for January 2020 - Climate - Environment and Climate Change Canada|last=Canada|first=Environment and Climate Change|date=2011-10-31|website=climate.weather.gc.ca|language=en|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> closing schools, disrupting transportation and cutting power to 23,000. Across the Plains and Midwest, the snow also caused problems for travelers, closing a 175-mile stretch of I-29, a 63-mile stretch of I-90 as well as all of I-85 within the state of Idaho. A plane slipped off the runway at Kansas City International Airport and the Quad Cities region declared a snow emergency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://weather.com/news/news/2020-01-17-winter-storm-impacts-plane-slides-off-runway-kansas-nebraska|title=Interstates Shut Down, Plane Slides Off Runway as Winter Storm Brings Ice and Snow to Plains, Midwest|website=The Weather Channel|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> In Southern Ontario, up to 20&nbsp;cm (8 inches) of snow fell breaking a few daily snowfall records for January 18, including at Ottawa International Airport where 19&nbsp;cm of snow fell (14.3&nbsp;cm of which fell on the 18th), and Pearson International Airport, which received 17.2&nbsp;cm of snow. The heavy snowfall was severely disruptive to transportation, particularly in the GTA, where 250 collisions occurred.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theweathernetwork.com/ca/news/article/in-photos-snowstorm-hits-southern-ontario|title=IN PHOTOS: Southern Ontario sees first significant snowfall in 2020, records set|last=Inc|first=Pelmorex Weather Networks|website=theweathernetwork.com|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-01-19}}</ref>\n\n=== North Atlantic bomb cyclone ===\n\nA low pressure system brought moderate snow to the  Great Lakes region it crossed the Northeast before emerging over the North Atlantic. While south of Nova Scotia, the storm became a weather bomb and the following day, January 17, it moved just to the south of Newfoundland Avalon Peninsula,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.accuweather.com/en/winter-weather/storm-to-explode-into-bomb-cyclone-offshore-of-new-england-before-eyeing-canada/663218|title=Bomb cyclone to hammer Newfoundland with blizzard conditions|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> bringing with it 2 to 3 feet of snow and hurricane-force winds that produced a large swath of blizzard condition in the Southeast Corner of the island. 76.2&nbsp;cm of snow accumulated, becoming St. John's heaviest 1-day snowfall since records began, with winds gusting to 100&nbsp;km/h for 14 consecutive hours, the city was paralyzed. Several locations were evacuated due to a significant avalanche risk.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theweathernetwork.com/ca/news/article/newfoundland-attempting-to-dig-out-after-blizzard-dumps-record-setting-snowfall-st-johns-strong-winds-power-outages|title=Newfoundland attempting to dig out after blizzard dumps record-setting snowfall|last=Inc|first=Pelmorex Weather Networks|website=theweathernetwork.com|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> At high tide, a storm surge of 60 \u2013 80&nbsp;cm occurred, with 9 to 12 m waves on top. Several communities in the region declared a state of emergency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theweathernetwork.com/ca/news/article/atlantic-canada-major-winter-storm-significant-snow-blizzard-conditions-for-newfoundland|title=Newfoundland: States of emergency amid 130+ km/h winds, 70+ cm snow|last=Inc|first=Pelmorex Weather Networks|website=theweathernetwork.com|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref>\n\n=== January\u2013February cold waves ===\n\nA major arctic outbreak affected western Canada and the Pacific Northwest from January 12\u201319. Extreme cold warnings were issued across all of Alberta, the Yukon, the Northwest Territories, most of BC, most of Saskatchewan and part of Manitoba during this period, as a cross-polar flow caused arctic to settle in the region. Much of Central Alberta dipped below -40&nbsp;\u00b0C, colder than it was in Siberia at the time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theweathernetwork.com/ca/news/article/prairies-record-breaking-cold-possible-as-dangerous-arctic-air-locks-in|title=Prairies: Temperatures will be among lowest on Earth with intense deep freeze|last=Inc|first=Pelmorex Weather Networks|website=theweathernetwork.com|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-01-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.accuweather.com/en/winter-weather/canadian-prairies-locked-in-icy-grip-of-winter-too-cold-for-penguins/659160|title=Canadian Prairies locked in icy grip of winter too cold for penguins|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the storm that would go on to become the North Atlantic bomb cyclone, the Ohio River Valley area and parts of the Midwest suffered brutally cold temperatures on January 19.\n\nOn February 14, the Ohio River Valley region suffered brutally cold temperatures again this winter with temperatures plummeting to a low of -2&nbsp;\u00b0F at Chicago O'Hare Airport, regionally the coldest temperatures recorded in the 2019\u20132020 season. Considering the windchill factor, temperatures ranged from -10&nbsp;\u00b0F - -20&nbsp;\u00b0F; dangerously cold for anyone outdoors. It was Chicago's coldest Valentine's Day in 77 years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wgntv.com/2020/02/14/wind-chill-advisory-for-northeast-illinois-remains-in-effect-until-10am-cst-this-friday-morning/|title=Friday is Chicago's coldest Valentine's Day in 77 years|date=2020-02-14|website=WGN-TV|language=en|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref> Temperatures in Minnesota were also record breaking; an overnight low of -35&nbsp;\u00b0F was reported at Preston. New Hampton, Iowa broke a near-century old record when they fell to -18&nbsp;\u00b0F.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.accuweather.com/en/winter-weather/deep-freeze-brings-accuweather-realfeel-temps-as-low-as-minus-46-f/681571|title=Deep freeze brings AccuWeather RealFeel Temps as low as minus 46 F|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> North of the International border, temperatures fell into the -20&nbsp;\u00b0C range as far south as Toronto, where several frostquakes occurred.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theweathernetwork.com/ca/news/article/frost-quakes-reported-in-southern-ontario-frigid-winter-conditions|title=Did you hear it? Frost quakes rumble through southern Ontario|last=Inc|first=Pelmorex Weather Networks|website=theweathernetwork.com|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref>\n\n=== Early February storm complex ===\n\n[[File:Winter storm over Eastern US February 6, 2020.jpg|thumb|Large storm complex over Eastern North America February 6]]\n\nFebruary 4 and 5, snow fell in the deep south, primarily in Texas and Oklahoma, where several highways were closed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.keyc.com/2020/02/05/snowfall-blankets-texas-oklahoma-deep-south-see-storms/|title=Snowfall blankets Texas, Oklahoma; Deep South to see storms|website=https://www.keyc.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-05}}</ref> Snow fell as far south as Austin, 14 inches of snow fell in Jayton, Texas, and thundersnow occurred in Big Spring. I-70 in central Missouri was temporarily shut down as road crews cleaned debris in the aftermath of a collision. Schools closed in portions of Texas, Oklahoma and Missouri. 9,000 were left without power in the Oklahoma city metro. The following day, severe thunderstorms produced flash flooding and tornadoes in the Southeastern United States. In Simpson County, Mississippi, a possible-tornado destroyed several mobile homes. A PDS-tornado warning was issued for Charlotte, where those at the airport were relocated to the building's interior.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.accuweather.com/en/severe-weather/sleepless-night-in-southeast-after-deadly-severe-outbreak-rocks-the-area-with-tornado-reports/675726|title='Particularly dangerous situation' tornado warnings prompted by severe storms marching across Southeast|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://weather.com/news/news/2020-02-05-winter-storm-impacts-oklahoma-kansas-missouri-texas|title=Portion of Interstate 70 Shut Down in Missouri as Winter Storm Marches East|website=The Weather Channel|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-05}}</ref> Severe thunderstorms and tornado warnings occurred as far North as Maryland and Delaware.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NWStornado/status/1225791217662746630?s=19|title=NWS Tornado twitter|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Winter weather advisories were issued from Tennessee to Maine, with warnings concentrated over North-central Pennsylvania, Western New York, Northern portions of Vermont, New Hampshire and Maine. With a precipitation shield of 2500&nbsp;km, the storm impacted 16 million across 6 provinces in Canada.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theweathernetwork.com/ca/news/article/nearly-half-the-population-of-canada-riding-out-this-next-storm-heavy-snow-ice-ontario-quebec-nova-scotia-pei-new-brunswick-newfoundland|title=Nearly HALF the population of Canada is riding out this big storm|last=Inc|first=Pelmorex Weather Networks|website=theweathernetwork.com|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref> The storm was dubbed \"Winter Storm Kade\" by The Weather Channel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://weather.com/storms/winter/news/2020-02-02-winter-storm-west-rockies-plains-midwest-northeast-early-february|title=Winter Storm to Intensify With Heavy Snow, Some Ice In Northeast, But Will Leave New York, Philly, Washington All Wet|website=The Weather Channel|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref>\n\n=== Mid February Southeast U.S snowstorm ===\nA broad area of low pressure brought snow to parts of the Southeast beginning on February 19, when snow began to fall in the mountains of Tennessee. 4.2 and 4 inches of snow accumulated in Waynesville and Mount LeConte respectively. Similar but slightly lesser amounts occurred in surrounding areas of Eastern Tennessee and Western North Carolina. Another swath of snow occurred in Eastern North Carolina and Southeastern Virginia on February 20\u201321, ending a 400+ day snow-free streak in the region.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.accuweather.com/en/winter-weather/north-carolina-prepares-for-wintry-blast-as-437-day-snow-drought-ends/685691|title=North Carolina feels wintry blast as 437-day snow drought ends|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In preparation for the storm, most school boards closed or had delayed openings, hundreds of flights were cancelled and all of North Carolina was put under a Winter weather advisory.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://weather.com/news/news/2020-02-20-winter-storm-impacts-north-carolina-virginia-snow|title=Winter Storm Closes Schools, Cancels Flights in North Carolina, Virginia; Officials Warn of Hazardous Road Conditions|website=The Weather Channel|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref>\n\n=== Late February Great Lakes winter storm ===\n\nOn February 25, heavy snowfall and winds caused travel disruption in South Dakota and Wyoming, where portions of Interstates 80 and 25 were closed. 31 inches of snow fell in South Dakota's Black hills.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://weather.com/safety/winter/news/2020-02-22-more-rain-south-snow-west-midwest-northeast-forecast|title=Snowstorm to Track From Plains to Midwest and Interior Northeast Through Midweek|website=The Weather Channel|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-26}}</ref> The following day, the storm impacted the Midwest, with accumulations peaking at 8.7 inches in Salem Center, Indiana. Major cities in the Midwest, such as Chicago or Indianapolis, avoided the heaviest snow as they received fewer than 3 inches of it. However, strong winds caused minor lakeshore flooding and delayed 900 flights in the former. 1 fatality was reported in Missouri as the result of a car crash.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://weather.com/safety/winter/news/2020-02-22-more-rain-south-snow-west-midwest-northeast-forecast|title=Winter Storm Odell Blankets West, Plains, Midwest With Snow|website=The Weather Channel|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.accuweather.com/en/weather-news/two-winter-storms-joined-forces-sending-deadly-blow-to-midwest/690583|title=2 winter storms joined forces sending deadly blow to Midwest|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The entire 401 corridor from Windsor through Southern Quebec was impacted by heavy snow, high winds and/or freezing rain. The inclement weather resulted in 250 collision in the Greater Toronto area alone. 19.6&nbsp;cm of snow fell in Ottawa,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://climate.weather.gc.ca/climate_data/daily_data_e.html?StationID=49568|title=Daily Data Report for February 2020 - Climate - Environment and Climate Change Canada|last=Canada|first=Environment and Climate Change|date=2011-10-31|website=climate.weather.gc.ca|language=en|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref> however, the storm may have produced over a foot of snow in nearby, sparsely populated Cottage country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theweathernetwork.com/ca/news/article/ontario-dangerous-winter-driving-amid-heavy-blowing-snow-intense-squalls-with-reduced-visibility|title=Ontario: Slick Thursday commute, blizzard conditions with intense squalls next|last=Inc|first=Pelmorex Weather Networks|website=theweathernetwork.com|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref> Due to the Great Lakes being relatively ice free and warmer than normal, unusually heavy lake-effect snow squalls followed along their leeward shores, prompting Blizzard warnings in some localities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.accuweather.com/en/winter-weather/blizzard-warnings-in-upstate-new-york-as-60-inches-of-snow-possible/690025|title=Blizzard warnings in effect as parts of upstate NY brace for as much as 60 inches of snow|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (As of 11 PM February 28) 48 inches of snow fell in Carthage, New York, downwind of Lake Ontario. The heaviest snowfall downwind of Lake Erie was 25 inches at Springville, New York. 33.8 inches of snow fell at Watertown.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NWSBUFFALO/status/1233600953066172419?s=19|title=Check out some of the preliminary snowfall amounts that have been reported so far! Expect some of these totals to climb even higher as lake snow continues downwind of Lakes Erie and Ontario through Saturday morning across some areas.pic.twitter.com/oXmGd7d7tb|last=Buffalo|first=N. W. S.|date=2020-02-28|website=@NWSBUFFALO|language=en|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref>\n\n=== March nor'easters ===\n\n[[File:GOES-16 satellite image of March 6\u2014 2020 nor'easter.jpg|thumb|Bomb cyclone Nor'easter at peak intensity March 7, 2020]]\n\n==== 1st nor'easter (March 6\u20138) ====\n\nAn area of low pressure off the US East Coast began intensifying when it merged with a weaker area of low pressure over the Great Lakes. Between the morning of March 6 and the morning of March 7, the storm's central pressure dropped 40 mb, qualifying for the 24 mb drop in 24 hours to classify a bomb cyclone. Due to the sharp pressure gradient, very strong winds were reported on the islands off Massachusetts' coast, with a peak gust of 66&nbsp;mph reported on Nantucket, where 2.4 - 2.5 inches of snow was recorded.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/WX1BOX/status/1236262306029461504?s=19|title=700 AM: Nantucket, MA: basement window blown out of a home on siasconset - W1AWB-Andrew's residence. He also report 2.5\" of snow on the island. #mawx|last=Skywarn|first=NWS Boston/Norton|date=2020-03-07|website=@WX1BOX|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://weather.com/safety/winter/news/2020-03-05-potential-bomb-cyclone-east-coast-new-england-high-winds-snow|title=Bomb Cyclone Is Scraping Southeastern New England With High Winds, Snow, Coastal Flooding|website=The Weather Channel|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref> A 62&nbsp;mph wind gust was reported on Cape Cod while nearby coastlines of Connecticut, Rhode Island and New Hampshire were affected by winds in the 30 - 45&nbsp;mph range. Light snow fell in Southeastern Massachusetts, peaking at 2.6 inches in Dighton.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NWSBoston/status/1236325833922379776?s=19|title=Here's the latest map of observed snowfall (note due to smoothing many places show 0.1\" that didn't receive any). Overall accumulating snow was confined to SE MA, incl Cape Cod & Islands. \"Jackpot\" was 2.6\" in Dighton! Complete list: https://nwschat.weather.gov/p.php?pid=202003071426-KBOX-NOUS41-PNSBOX\u00a0\u2026pic.twitter.com/sM41B1vht7|last=Boston|first=N. W. S.|date=2020-03-07|website=@NWSBoston|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> The storm achieved a peak intensity of 965 mb early on March 7, as it was pulling away from New England.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NWSBoston/status/1236234206713274368?s=19|title=[5 am] latest weather map shows #BombCyclone well southeast of #Nantucket & continuing to generate strong to damaging winds with gusts up to 60 mph across Cape Cod & Nantucket. Latest radar indicates accumulating #snow continuing as well here with a band of heavier snow (green)pic.twitter.com/SXGEGf3m33|last=Boston|first=N. W. S.|date=2020-03-07|website=@NWSBoston|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref>\n\n==== 2nd nor'easter (March 22\u201325) ====\nAn area of low pressure moved offshore of the Mid-Atlantic and began organizing and stregnthening slightly. Remaining offshore, enough cold air was in place for it to deliver moderate, locally heavy snow to the interior northeast. Syracuse received their 2nd heaviest seasonal snowfall with 6.8 inches. The Albany metro area also saw >6 inches of snow. Higher elevation locales received much heftier totals; 9 inches of snow accumulated at Lake Desolate and 8.8 inches in Savoy, Massachusetts, for example. The most snowfall accumulated for this storm in the United States was 11 inches and occurred in 3 different locations; Mildford, New Hampshire, Quechee, Vermont and Norridgewock, Maine. Beforehand, light snowfall was experienced over a swath of the Midwest and 2 inches of snow accumulated at Chicago O'Hare International Airport.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://weather.com/storms/winter/news/2020-03-21-spring-snow-northeast-coastal-lows|title=Coastal Low Brought Snow and Rain to the Northeast as First Full Week of Spring Began|website=The Weather Channel|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Atlantic Canada also experienced impacts from the storm. In the Maritimes, wet snow fell ahead of moderate rainfall and mixed precipitation lessened snowfall totals. However, the island of Newfoundland experienced much heavier snow and stronger winds, producing near-blizzard conditions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theweathernetwork.com/ca/news/article/atlantic-maritimes-will-see-heavy-rain-blizzard-like-conditions-and-heavy-snow-for-newfoundland|title=Atlantic: Spring storm brings 20-40 cm of snow, blizzard-like conditions|last=Inc|first=Pelmorex Weather Networks|website=theweathernetwork.com|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> At Stanfield International Airport, 27.1&nbsp;cm of snow fell on March 24.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://climate.weather.gc.ca/climate_data/daily_data_e.html?StationID=50620|title=Daily Data Report for March 2020 - Climate - Environment and Climate Change Canada|last=Canada|first=Environment and Climate Change|date=2011-10-31|website=climate.weather.gc.ca|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> St. John's, Newfoundland saw 18.4&nbsp;cm of snow March 24\u201325 and winds there gusted to 91&nbsp;km/h.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://climate.weather.gc.ca/climate_data/daily_data_e.html?StationID=50089|title=Daily Data Report for March 2020 - Climate - Environment and Climate Change Canada|last=Canada|first=Environment and Climate Change|date=2011-10-31|website=climate.weather.gc.ca|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n=== Mid March High Plains blizzard ===\n\n[[File:Satellite image of water vapor over Northern rockies March 19, 2020.jpg|thumb|GOES 16 water vapor image of the Northern Rockies as the late season blizzard moves over.]]\n\nAn area of low pressure incoming from the Pacific drifted down the California coastline the week of March 16, bringing scattered thunderstorms with hail to Southern California.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NWSLosAngeles/status/1240028664340701184?s=19|title=Convective showers observed moving through LA County this afternoon. Have had reports of hail in some areas, including Woodland Hills. #SoCal #LArain #LAweatherpic.twitter.com/3DpBE1ipOH|last=Angeles|first=NWS Los|date=2020-03-17|website=@NWSLosAngeles|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> Continuous flow of moisture into California's mountains produced extreme snowfall totals during an otherwise unipressive winter there. 114 inches of snow fell at Homewood, 92\" at Sierra-at-Tahoe and 77\" at Kingvale, for example.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Brittany_Boyer/status/1240046206430183425?s=19|title=Incredible snow totals coming in from the multi-day event in California. They definitely needed it after the lack of snow prior to this #cawxpic.twitter.com/Jekzw2cn7L|last=Boyer|first=Brittany|date=2020-03-17|website=@Brittany_Boyer|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> Several rounds of severe thunderstorms occurred in Texas during this time period with the Dallas Metro being especially hit hard. Following >4 inches of rain, street flooding was reported.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/StormOfCorn/status/1240387696197074944?s=19|title=Twitter|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/BillWadell/status/1240282044300738561?s=19|title=Twitter|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The responsible low pressure area was observed to finally move ashore mid-day on the 18,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NWSSanDiego/status/1240346154853732352?s=19|title=Twitter NWS San Diego|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and the Colorado low began forming shortly afterward. In the Rocky Mountains and Great Plains, blizzard warnings were issued March 17 in anticipation of a very heavy snowfall to be accompanied by strong winds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://weather.com/storms/winter/news/2020-03-14-snow-wind-west-plains-upper-midwest-strong-system|title=Blizzard Warnings Issued in Wyoming and Nebraska as a Winter Storm Will Blast the Rockies, Plains|website=The Weather Channel|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> Snowfall totals in NWS Boulder's forecast region peak at 23 inches 4 miles NE of Nederland.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NWSBoulder/status/1240948876108062720?s=19|title=Snowfall totals from 8\"-18\" in the mountains and foothills with local amounts over 20\" in a few spots.  Along the I-25 Corridor 5\" to 10\" around Denver with up to 12\" over the Palmer Divide.  #cowxpic.twitter.com/XeKDuN7Ler|last=Boulder|first=N. W. S.|date=2020-03-20|website=@NWSBoulder|language=en|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> Combined with winds gusting >62&nbsp;mph,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NWSBoulder/status/1240777533832007680?s=19|title=List of peak wind reports: Akron airport checks in w/the strongest gust of 62 mph . Snow combined w/snow has created widespread blizzard conditions. Numerous locations across the northeast plains have been reporting whiteout or near whiteout conditions. #COwxpic.twitter.com/nMm74ud1jH|last=Boulder|first=N. W. S.|date=2020-03-19|website=@NWSBoulder|language=en|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> widespread blizzard conditions occurred.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NWSBoulder/status/1240776985011519489?s=19|title=Blizzard conditions exist over a large chunk of northeast Colorado (east of I-25 and over the Palmer Divide). More technical discussion attached in this tweet.  #COwxhttps://twitter.com/NWSSPC/status/1240771590301736960\u00a0\u2026|last=Boulder|first=N. W. S.|date=2020-03-19|website=@NWSBoulder|language=en|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> At Denver's airport over 1,000 flights or ~80% of air traffic that day, were cancelled.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://weather.com/storms/winter/news/2020-03-14-snow-wind-west-plains-upper-midwest-strong-system|title=Winter Storm Takes Aim on the Plains, Upper Midwest with Snow and Gusty Winds|website=The Weather Channel|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Include-NOAA}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.wpc.ncep.noaa.gov/storm_summaries/storm_summaries.shtml 2019 Storm Summaries] from the Weather Prediction Center\n\n{{portal|Weather}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{Succession box|before=[[2018\u201319 North American winter|2018\u201319]]|title=North American winters|years=2019\u201320|after=2020\u201321}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{United States winter storms}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2019-20 North American winter}}\n[[Category:2019 meteorology]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 North American winter| ]]\n[[Category:North American winters]]\n[[Category:2019 in North America|Winter]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox winter\n| image = File:Satellite imagery on February 27, 2020 of Great Lakes blizzard.jpg\n| caption = Strong extratropical cyclone brings strong winds and feet of snow to Great Lakes February 27, 2020\n| astro = December&nbsp;21&nbsp;\u2013 March&nbsp;19\n| meteo = December&nbsp;1&nbsp;\u2013 February&nbsp;29\n| year = 2019\n| notable event = [[November 26 - December 3, 2019 North American blizzard]]\n| maxsnow = 114 inches at [[Homewood, California]]\n| event duration = November 26 - December 3, 2019\n}}\n\nThe '''2019\u201320 North American winter''' refers to winter in [[North America]] as it is occurring across the continent from late 2019 through early 2020. While there is no well-agreed-upon date used to indicate the start of winter in the Northern Hemisphere, there are two definitions of winter which may be used. Based on the astronomical definition, winter begins at the [[winter solstice]], which in 2019 occurred on December&nbsp;21, and ends at the March equinox, which in 2020 occurred on March&nbsp;20.<ref name=\"USNO Seasons\">{{cite web|title=Earth's Seasons: Equinoxes, Solstices, Perihelion, and Aphelion, 2000-2025 |url=http://aa.usno.navy.mil/data/docs/EarthSeasons.php |publisher=[[United States Naval Observatory]] |date=March 27, 2015 |accessdate=August 15, 2015 |location=[[Washington, D.C.]] |format=PHP |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6anEZkLaj?url=http://aa.usno.navy.mil/data/docs/EarthSeasons.php |archive-date=August 15, 2015 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref> Based on the meteorological definition, the first day of winter is December 1 and the last day February 29.<ref name=\"NOAA/NWS-Seasons\">{{cite web|title=Meteorological vs. Astronomical Seasons|url=https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/news/meteorological-versus-astronomical-summer%E2%80%94what%E2%80%99s-difference|publisher=NOAA National Centers for Environmental Information|date=June 21, 2013|accessdate=July 3, 2015}}</ref> Both definitions involve a period of approximately three months, with some variability. Winter is often defined by meteorologists to be the three calendar months with the lowest average temperatures. Since both definitions span the [[calendar year]], it is possible to have a winter storm in two different years.\n\nSeasonal forecasts indicated a milder than normal winter across most of the United States and even parts of Canada. These forecasts were verified after the United States experienced their 6th warmest winter on record<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mobile.twitter.com/NOAANCEIclimate/status/1235961898476036097?s=19|title=Twitter|website=mobile.twitter.com|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> and many cities in the Northeast Megalopolis received <1\" of snow all winter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.accuweather.com/en/winter-weather/could-a-big-storm-end-this-winters-snow-drought-in-the-northeast/693375|title=Could a big storm end snow drought in the Northeast this winter?|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Fewer significant events than normal occurred during the season and many of them occurred later in the season or in early spring; they include a bomb cyclone/early-season winter storm in the country's norther tier, a series of brief cold waves in the Northwest and Midwest Late January through Early February, a historic blizzard in Atlantic Canada Late January, a significant lake effect snow event on the Great Lakes late February, a bomb cyclone Nor'easter in March that provided a yet another near-miss to New England, and a late-season blizzard that impacted the High Plains and Rocky Mountains.\n\n==Seasonal forecasts==\n{{multiple image\n | width = 200\n | image1 = US temp outlook winter 2019\u201320 NOAA.png\n | caption1 = Temperature outlook\n | image2 = US precip outlook winter 2019\u201320 NOAA.png\n | caption2 = Precipitation outlook\n | caption_align = center\n}}\nOn October&nbsp;17, 2019, the [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]]'s [[Climate Prediction Center]] released its U.S. Winter Outlook. The [[El Ni\u00f1o\u2013Southern Oscillation]] was in its neutral phase and was thus not expected to be a key predictor for the season. As a result, other oscillations such as the Madden\u2013Julian Oscillation and the Arctic Oscillation were anticipated to be more significant drivers of the seasonal weather, particularly in the form of large temperature and precipitation swings. From the outlook, the greatest likelihoods for above-normal temperatures were for Alaska and Hawaii, with lower but still above-normal odds of above-average temperatures for most of the lower 48 states. The exception was for the Northern Plains, Upper Mississippi Valley, and western Great Lakes regions, which were ascribed equal changes for above-, near-, or below-average temperatures. No area in the United States was favored to have below-average temperatures. In terms of precipitation, wetter-than-average conditions were most likely in Alaska, Hawaii, part of the Northern Plains, Upper Mississippi Valley, Great Lakes, and parts of the Mid-Atlantic and Northeastern U.S. Drier-than-average conditions were favored for Louisiana and parts of Texas, Mississippi, Arkansas, and Oklahoma, as well as parts of central and northern California, with the rest of the U.S. having equal changes of above-, near-, or below-average precipitation. The drought outlook highlighted the presence of abnormally dry conditions across much of the Southern U.S, with improvement expected in part of the Southeast and Mid-Atlantic regions, Alaska, and Hawaii. Drought was expected to persist in central Texas and the Southwestern U.S, with further development anticipated in parts of central California.<ref>{{cite news|title=Winter Outlook: Warmer than average for many, wetter in the North: Drought improvement expected in the Southeast|url=https://www.noaa.gov/media-release/winter-outlook-warmer-than-average-for-many-wetter-in-north|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|date=October 17, 2019|accessdate=October 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Events ==\n=== Early November winter storm ===\nRecord breaking temperatures and snowfall caused disruption throughout the Midwestern United States in early November. Approximately 1000 flights were grounded at Chicago's [[O'Hare International Airport]] as 3.7 inches of snow fell on November 11, breaking the previous record of 1.9 inches on November 11, 1995.<ref name=\"WGN911NOV\">{{cite news |title=Nearly 1,000 flights canceled as record-breaking snow blankets Chicago |url=https://wgntv.com/2019/11/11/winter-weather-advisory-for-3-to-6-inches-of-snow-across-the-chicago-area-monday-lakeshore-flood-warning-for-the-illinois-and-nw-indiana-lake-michigan-shoreline-into-tuesday/ |agency=Nextstar Broadcasting, inc. |publisher=WGN9 |date=11 November 2019}}</ref> In Canada, Southern Ontario and Southern Quebec had their first major winter storm of the season on November 11 and 12 respectively, which was followed by record January-like cold.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theweathernetwork.com/ca/news/article/significant-november-snow-storm-hits-southern-ontario-quebec-with-record-january-like-cold|title=After strong storm, traffic chaos, where to expect Tuesday's snow|last=Inc|first=Pelmorex Weather Networks|website=theweathernetwork.com|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref> 10\u201320&nbsp;cm of snow fell across much of the region crippling large cities such as Montreal and Toronto. In Montreal, local officials announced the city's earliest ever snow removal operation in the aftermath of the storm. Over 10 school boards province-wide closed the day after the storm.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theweathernetwork.com/ca/news/article/major-snow-storm-coming-to-quebec-early-week|title=Quebec digs out from its first major snowstorm of the season|last=Inc|first=Pelmorex Weather Networks|website=theweathernetwork.com|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n=== Late November - Early December bomb cyclone & blizzard ===\n\n{{Main|November 26 - December 3, 2019 North American blizzard}}\n\n[[File:Two Large Winter Storms to Wallop Parts of the U.S.jpg|thumb|Satellite imagery of winter storms crossing the US November 27, 2019]]\n\nMoving ashore November 26\u201327 near the Oregon/California border as an over-achieving bomb cyclone, it produced wind gusts in excess of 100&nbsp;mph near its point of landfall. The storm produced a record low pressure reading of 973.4 millibars in Crescent City, California. From November 27\u201330, the low merged with the subtropical jet as it tracked slowly eastward across the Rockies, plains & Midwest. The combination of cold air, moisture and high winds produced a wide swath of blizzard conditions from Colorado through western South Dakota, including the Denver Metro. In Rapid City, 14.5 inches of snow fell on the 30th, breaking the one-day snowfall record for November. In Duluth, where 21.7 inches of snow accumulated, it was the city's heaviest snowstorm in 10 years. As the first major winter storm of the season in the northeast, it dumped 22.6 inches of snow in Albany, where it was the heaviest snowfall since the 1993 Superstorm. Widespread totals in excess of 20 inches occurred in the Albany Metro, Southern New Hampshire & Northwestern Massachusetts with a regional peak of 36 inches of snow in New Ipswich, New Hampshire. The low finally moved out to sea December 3.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://weather.com/storms/winter/news/2019-12-01-northeast-great-lakes-snowstorm-forecast-ezekiel|title=Cross-Country Winter Storm Brought Snow, Ice and Wind Thanksgiving Week Into Early December (RECAP)|website=The Weather Channel|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n=== Late December Great Plains and Midwest blizzard ===\n\nThe winter storm had the largest impact on the Midwestern states, as it affected Nebraska, the Dakotas, and Minnesota. In [[Fargo, North Dakota]], there were many closings of schools, businesses, and roadways, from December 28 to December 30. Freezing rain lead to over 470 reported traffic accidents in Minneapolis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.inforum.com/news/weather/4843620-It-could-take-weeks-for-Fargo-plows-to-completely-dig-out-of-once-in-a-10-year-blizzard|title=It could take weeks for Fargo plows to completely dig out of 'once-in-a-10-year' blizzard|first1=April|last1=Baumgarten|first2=C. S. |last2=Hagen |website=INFORUM|accessdate=Jan 7, 2020}}</ref><ref>https://www.fox9.com/news/slippery-road-conditions-lead-to-470-crashes-across-Minnesota</ref>\n\n[[File:Great Lakes Region Slammed By Severe Winter Storm (49305407947).jpg|thumb|Plains being impacted by blizzard, as seen from space]]\n\n=== Early January storm complex ===\nA large complex of low pressure systems began developing January 9 over Central North America. A large trough dug into the jet stream over the Southwestern United States, providing arctic air that had been settled over Canada to move southwards and clash with warm, moist air moving northward from the Gulf of Mexico.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://weather.com/news/news/2020-01-10-winter-storm-oklahoma-kansas-missouri-iowa-illinois|title=Winter Storm Closes Schools, Airlines Prepare for Delays|website=The Weather Channel|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-11}}</ref> In the warm sector, severe thunderstorms and tornadoes broke out in the south central United States on the morning of January 10. Tornado warnings were issued for more than 1.7 million in the Dallas-Fort Worth Metroplex, at 7:52 pm CST a PDS tornado warning was issued for Scranton, Arkansas and surrounding communities and more than 111,000 customers were left without power in Texas alone. Severe weather continued in the deep south into following day, with Alabama being affected particularly severely.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.accuweather.com/en/weather-news/live-tornado-watches-issued-in-oklahoma-texas-as-severe-weather-outbreak-begins-in-southern-us/659511|title=LIVE: Storms leave behind trail of damage as severe weather outbreak advances east|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> North of the boundary, a mix of heavy snow and freezing rain caused travel woes across the Midwest. Along the Great Lakes, winds were forecast to whip up 23 foot waves as lakeshore flooding had already begun in Chicago.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://weather.com/news/news/2020-01-11-winter-storm-impacts-flights-canceled-power-outages-rough-driving|title=Waves More Than 20 Feet High Could Hit Chicago Lakeshore as Winter Storm Pounds Plains, Upper Midwest|website=The Weather Channel|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-11}}</ref> Central Michigan through Eastern Ontario received a swath of crippling ice accretion. Several January rainfall records fell in Southern Ontario, as event rainfall totals over 50&nbsp;mm were widespread, which is highly unusual for that time of year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theweathernetwork.com/ca/news/article/ontario-ice-storm-with-prolonged-freezing-rain-record-january-rainfall-flood-threat|title=Ontario: Largest temperature drop in almost two years, freezing rain ramps up|last=Inc|first=Pelmorex Weather Networks|website=theweathernetwork.com|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-01-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theweathernetwork.com/ca/news/article/in-photos-ontario-extreme-rainfall-and-freezing-rain-event|title=PHOTOS: Cleanup underway after record rainfall floods streets, ice topples trees|last=Inc|first=Pelmorex Weather Networks|website=theweathernetwork.com|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-01-12}}</ref>\n\n=== Mid January snowstorm ===\nBeginning on the west coast January 15, much of southern British Columbia, including the Lower Mainland and Vancouver Island, received an unusually heavy snowstorm. Combined with high wind, some localities were put under blizzard warning, which is rare in British Columbia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theweathernetwork.com/ca/news/article/photos-b-c-digs-out-after-winter-storm-dumps-heavy-snow-causes-power-outages|title=PHOTOS: B.C. digs out after winter storm dumps heavy snow, causes power outages|last=Inc|first=Pelmorex Weather Networks|website=theweathernetwork.com|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> 15&nbsp;cm of snow fell in Vancouver<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://climate.weather.gc.ca/climate_data/daily_data_e.html?StationID=51442|title=Daily Data Report for January 2020 - Climate - Environment and Climate Change Canada|last=Canada|first=Environment and Climate Change|date=2011-10-31|website=climate.weather.gc.ca|language=en|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> and 20&nbsp;cm fell in Victoria,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://climate.weather.gc.ca/climate_data/daily_data_e.html?StationID=51337|title=Daily Data Report for January 2020 - Climate - Environment and Climate Change Canada|last=Canada|first=Environment and Climate Change|date=2011-10-31|website=climate.weather.gc.ca|language=en|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> closing schools, disrupting transportation and cutting power to 23,000. Across the Plains and Midwest, the snow also caused problems for travelers, closing a 175-mile stretch of I-29, a 63-mile stretch of I-90 as well as all of I-85 within the state of Idaho. A plane slipped off the runway at Kansas City International Airport and the Quad Cities region declared a snow emergency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://weather.com/news/news/2020-01-17-winter-storm-impacts-plane-slides-off-runway-kansas-nebraska|title=Interstates Shut Down, Plane Slides Off Runway as Winter Storm Brings Ice and Snow to Plains, Midwest|website=The Weather Channel|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> In Southern Ontario, up to 20&nbsp;cm (8 inches) of snow fell breaking a few daily snowfall records for January 18, including at Ottawa International Airport where 19&nbsp;cm of snow fell (14.3&nbsp;cm of which fell on the 18th), and Pearson International Airport, which received 17.2&nbsp;cm of snow. The heavy snowfall was severely disruptive to transportation, particularly in the GTA, where 250 collisions occurred.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theweathernetwork.com/ca/news/article/in-photos-snowstorm-hits-southern-ontario|title=IN PHOTOS: Southern Ontario sees first significant snowfall in 2020, records set|last=Inc|first=Pelmorex Weather Networks|website=theweathernetwork.com|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-01-19}}</ref>\n\n=== North Atlantic bomb cyclone ===\n\nA low pressure system brought moderate snow to the  Great Lakes region it crossed the Northeast before emerging over the North Atlantic. While south of Nova Scotia, the storm became a weather bomb and the following day, January 17, it moved just to the south of Newfoundland Avalon Peninsula,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.accuweather.com/en/winter-weather/storm-to-explode-into-bomb-cyclone-offshore-of-new-england-before-eyeing-canada/663218|title=Bomb cyclone to hammer Newfoundland with blizzard conditions|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> bringing with it 2 to 3 feet of snow and hurricane-force winds that produced a large swath of blizzard condition in the Southeast Corner of the island. 76.2&nbsp;cm of snow accumulated, becoming St. John's heaviest 1-day snowfall since records began, with winds gusting to 100&nbsp;km/h for 14 consecutive hours, the city was paralyzed. Several locations were evacuated due to a significant avalanche risk.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theweathernetwork.com/ca/news/article/newfoundland-attempting-to-dig-out-after-blizzard-dumps-record-setting-snowfall-st-johns-strong-winds-power-outages|title=Newfoundland attempting to dig out after blizzard dumps record-setting snowfall|last=Inc|first=Pelmorex Weather Networks|website=theweathernetwork.com|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> At high tide, a storm surge of 60 \u2013 80&nbsp;cm occurred, with 9 to 12 m waves on top. Several communities in the region declared a state of emergency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theweathernetwork.com/ca/news/article/atlantic-canada-major-winter-storm-significant-snow-blizzard-conditions-for-newfoundland|title=Newfoundland: States of emergency amid 130+ km/h winds, 70+ cm snow|last=Inc|first=Pelmorex Weather Networks|website=theweathernetwork.com|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref>\n\n=== January\u2013February cold waves ===\n\nA major arctic outbreak affected western Canada and the Pacific Northwest from January 12\u201319. Extreme cold warnings were issued across all of Alberta, the Yukon, the Northwest Territories, most of BC, most of Saskatchewan and part of Manitoba during this period, as a cross-polar flow caused arctic to settle in the region. Much of Central Alberta dipped below -40&nbsp;\u00b0C, colder than it was in Siberia at the time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theweathernetwork.com/ca/news/article/prairies-record-breaking-cold-possible-as-dangerous-arctic-air-locks-in|title=Prairies: Temperatures will be among lowest on Earth with intense deep freeze|last=Inc|first=Pelmorex Weather Networks|website=theweathernetwork.com|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-01-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.accuweather.com/en/winter-weather/canadian-prairies-locked-in-icy-grip-of-winter-too-cold-for-penguins/659160|title=Canadian Prairies locked in icy grip of winter too cold for penguins|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the storm that would go on to become the North Atlantic bomb cyclone, the Ohio River Valley area and parts of the Midwest suffered brutally cold temperatures on January 19.\n\nOn February 14, the Ohio River Valley region suffered brutally cold temperatures again this winter with temperatures plummeting to a low of -2&nbsp;\u00b0F at Chicago O'Hare Airport, regionally the coldest temperatures recorded in the 2019\u20132020 season. Considering the windchill factor, temperatures ranged from -10&nbsp;\u00b0F - -20&nbsp;\u00b0F; dangerously cold for anyone outdoors. It was Chicago's coldest Valentine's Day in 77 years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wgntv.com/2020/02/14/wind-chill-advisory-for-northeast-illinois-remains-in-effect-until-10am-cst-this-friday-morning/|title=Friday is Chicago's coldest Valentine's Day in 77 years|date=2020-02-14|website=WGN-TV|language=en|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref> Temperatures in Minnesota were also record breaking; an overnight low of -35&nbsp;\u00b0F was reported at Preston. New Hampton, Iowa broke a near-century old record when they fell to -18&nbsp;\u00b0F.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.accuweather.com/en/winter-weather/deep-freeze-brings-accuweather-realfeel-temps-as-low-as-minus-46-f/681571|title=Deep freeze brings AccuWeather RealFeel Temps as low as minus 46 F|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> North of the International border, temperatures fell into the -20&nbsp;\u00b0C range as far south as Toronto, where several frostquakes occurred.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theweathernetwork.com/ca/news/article/frost-quakes-reported-in-southern-ontario-frigid-winter-conditions|title=Did you hear it? Frost quakes rumble through southern Ontario|last=Inc|first=Pelmorex Weather Networks|website=theweathernetwork.com|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref>\n\n=== Early February storm complex ===\n\n[[File:Winter storm over Eastern US February 6, 2020.jpg|thumb|Large storm complex over Eastern North America February 6]]\n\nFebruary 4 and 5, snow fell in the deep south, primarily in Texas and Oklahoma, where several highways were closed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.keyc.com/2020/02/05/snowfall-blankets-texas-oklahoma-deep-south-see-storms/|title=Snowfall blankets Texas, Oklahoma; Deep South to see storms|website=https://www.keyc.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-05}}</ref> Snow fell as far south as Austin, 14 inches of snow fell in Jayton, Texas, and thundersnow occurred in Big Spring. I-70 in central Missouri was temporarily shut down as road crews cleaned debris in the aftermath of a collision. Schools closed in portions of Texas, Oklahoma and Missouri. 9,000 were left without power in the Oklahoma city metro. The following day, severe thunderstorms produced flash flooding and tornadoes in the Southeastern United States. In Simpson County, Mississippi, a possible-tornado destroyed several mobile homes. A PDS-tornado warning was issued for Charlotte, where those at the airport were relocated to the building's interior.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.accuweather.com/en/severe-weather/sleepless-night-in-southeast-after-deadly-severe-outbreak-rocks-the-area-with-tornado-reports/675726|title='Particularly dangerous situation' tornado warnings prompted by severe storms marching across Southeast|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://weather.com/news/news/2020-02-05-winter-storm-impacts-oklahoma-kansas-missouri-texas|title=Portion of Interstate 70 Shut Down in Missouri as Winter Storm Marches East|website=The Weather Channel|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-05}}</ref> Severe thunderstorms and tornado warnings occurred as far North as Maryland and Delaware.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NWStornado/status/1225791217662746630?s=19|title=NWS Tornado twitter|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Winter weather advisories were issued from Tennessee to Maine, with warnings concentrated over North-central Pennsylvania, Western New York, Northern portions of Vermont, New Hampshire and Maine. With a precipitation shield of 2500&nbsp;km, the storm impacted 16 million across 6 provinces in Canada.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theweathernetwork.com/ca/news/article/nearly-half-the-population-of-canada-riding-out-this-next-storm-heavy-snow-ice-ontario-quebec-nova-scotia-pei-new-brunswick-newfoundland|title=Nearly HALF the population of Canada is riding out this big storm|last=Inc|first=Pelmorex Weather Networks|website=theweathernetwork.com|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref> The storm was dubbed \"Winter Storm Kade\" by The Weather Channel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://weather.com/storms/winter/news/2020-02-02-winter-storm-west-rockies-plains-midwest-northeast-early-february|title=Winter Storm to Intensify With Heavy Snow, Some Ice In Northeast, But Will Leave New York, Philly, Washington All Wet|website=The Weather Channel|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref>\n\n=== Mid February Southeast U.S snowstorm ===\nA broad area of low pressure brought snow to parts of the Southeast beginning on February 19, when snow began to fall in the mountains of Tennessee. 4.2 and 4 inches of snow accumulated in Waynesville and Mount LeConte respectively. Similar but slightly lesser amounts occurred in surrounding areas of Eastern Tennessee and Western North Carolina. Another swath of snow occurred in Eastern North Carolina and Southeastern Virginia on February 20\u201321, ending a 400+ day snow-free streak in the region.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.accuweather.com/en/winter-weather/north-carolina-prepares-for-wintry-blast-as-437-day-snow-drought-ends/685691|title=North Carolina feels wintry blast as 437-day snow drought ends|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In preparation for the storm, most school boards closed or had delayed openings, hundreds of flights were cancelled and all of North Carolina was put under a Winter weather advisory.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://weather.com/news/news/2020-02-20-winter-storm-impacts-north-carolina-virginia-snow|title=Winter Storm Closes Schools, Cancels Flights in North Carolina, Virginia; Officials Warn of Hazardous Road Conditions|website=The Weather Channel|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref>\n\n=== Late February Great Lakes winter storm ===\n\nOn February 25, heavy snowfall and winds caused travel disruption in South Dakota and Wyoming, where portions of Interstates 80 and 25 were closed. 31 inches of snow fell in South Dakota's Black hills.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://weather.com/safety/winter/news/2020-02-22-more-rain-south-snow-west-midwest-northeast-forecast|title=Snowstorm to Track From Plains to Midwest and Interior Northeast Through Midweek|website=The Weather Channel|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-26}}</ref> The following day, the storm impacted the Midwest, with accumulations peaking at 8.7 inches in Salem Center, Indiana. Major cities in the Midwest, such as Chicago or Indianapolis, avoided the heaviest snow as they received fewer than 3 inches of it. However, strong winds caused minor lakeshore flooding and delayed 900 flights in the former. 1 fatality was reported in Missouri as the result of a car crash.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://weather.com/safety/winter/news/2020-02-22-more-rain-south-snow-west-midwest-northeast-forecast|title=Winter Storm Odell Blankets West, Plains, Midwest With Snow|website=The Weather Channel|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.accuweather.com/en/weather-news/two-winter-storms-joined-forces-sending-deadly-blow-to-midwest/690583|title=2 winter storms joined forces sending deadly blow to Midwest|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The entire 401 corridor from Windsor through Southern Quebec was impacted by heavy snow, high winds and/or freezing rain. The inclement weather resulted in 250 collision in the Greater Toronto area alone. 19.6&nbsp;cm of snow fell in Ottawa,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://climate.weather.gc.ca/climate_data/daily_data_e.html?StationID=49568|title=Daily Data Report for February 2020 - Climate - Environment and Climate Change Canada|last=Canada|first=Environment and Climate Change|date=2011-10-31|website=climate.weather.gc.ca|language=en|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref> however, the storm may have produced over a foot of snow in nearby, sparsely populated Cottage country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theweathernetwork.com/ca/news/article/ontario-dangerous-winter-driving-amid-heavy-blowing-snow-intense-squalls-with-reduced-visibility|title=Ontario: Slick Thursday commute, blizzard conditions with intense squalls next|last=Inc|first=Pelmorex Weather Networks|website=theweathernetwork.com|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref> Due to the Great Lakes being relatively ice free and warmer than normal, unusually heavy lake-effect snow squalls followed along their leeward shores, prompting Blizzard warnings in some localities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.accuweather.com/en/winter-weather/blizzard-warnings-in-upstate-new-york-as-60-inches-of-snow-possible/690025|title=Blizzard warnings in effect as parts of upstate NY brace for as much as 60 inches of snow|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (As of 11 PM February 28) 48 inches of snow fell in Carthage, New York, downwind of Lake Ontario. The heaviest snowfall downwind of Lake Erie was 25 inches at Springville, New York. 33.8 inches of snow fell at Watertown.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NWSBUFFALO/status/1233600953066172419?s=19|title=Check out some of the preliminary snowfall amounts that have been reported so far! Expect some of these totals to climb even higher as lake snow continues downwind of Lakes Erie and Ontario through Saturday morning across some areas.pic.twitter.com/oXmGd7d7tb|last=Buffalo|first=N. W. S.|date=2020-02-28|website=@NWSBUFFALO|language=en|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref>\n\n=== March nor'easters ===\n\n[[File:GOES-16 satellite image of March 6\u2014 2020 nor'easter.jpg|thumb|Bomb cyclone Nor'easter at peak intensity March 7, 2020]]\n\n==== 1st nor'easter (March 6\u20138) ====\n\nAn area of low pressure off the US East Coast began intensifying when it merged with a weaker area of low pressure over the Great Lakes. Between the morning of March 6 and the morning of March 7, the storm's central pressure dropped 40 mb, qualifying for the 24 mb drop in 24 hours to classify a bomb cyclone. Due to the sharp pressure gradient, very strong winds were reported on the islands off Massachusetts' coast, with a peak gust of 66&nbsp;mph reported on Nantucket, where 2.4 - 2.5 inches of snow was recorded.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/WX1BOX/status/1236262306029461504?s=19|title=700 AM: Nantucket, MA: basement window blown out of a home on siasconset - W1AWB-Andrew's residence. He also report 2.5\" of snow on the island. #mawx|last=Skywarn|first=NWS Boston/Norton|date=2020-03-07|website=@WX1BOX|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://weather.com/safety/winter/news/2020-03-05-potential-bomb-cyclone-east-coast-new-england-high-winds-snow|title=Bomb Cyclone Is Scraping Southeastern New England With High Winds, Snow, Coastal Flooding|website=The Weather Channel|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref> A 62&nbsp;mph wind gust was reported on Cape Cod while nearby coastlines of Connecticut, Rhode Island and New Hampshire were affected by winds in the 30 - 45&nbsp;mph range. Light snow fell in Southeastern Massachusetts, peaking at 2.6 inches in Dighton.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NWSBoston/status/1236325833922379776?s=19|title=Here's the latest map of observed snowfall (note due to smoothing many places show 0.1\" that didn't receive any). Overall accumulating snow was confined to SE MA, incl Cape Cod & Islands. \"Jackpot\" was 2.6\" in Dighton! Complete list: https://nwschat.weather.gov/p.php?pid=202003071426-KBOX-NOUS41-PNSBOX\u00a0\u2026pic.twitter.com/sM41B1vht7|last=Boston|first=N. W. S.|date=2020-03-07|website=@NWSBoston|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> The storm achieved a peak intensity of 965 mb early on March 7, as it was pulling away from New England.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NWSBoston/status/1236234206713274368?s=19|title=[5 am] latest weather map shows #BombCyclone well southeast of #Nantucket & continuing to generate strong to damaging winds with gusts up to 60 mph across Cape Cod & Nantucket. Latest radar indicates accumulating #snow continuing as well here with a band of heavier snow (green)pic.twitter.com/SXGEGf3m33|last=Boston|first=N. W. S.|date=2020-03-07|website=@NWSBoston|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref>\n\n==== 2nd nor'easter (March 22\u201325) ====\nAn area of low pressure moved offshore of the Mid-Atlantic and began organizing and stregnthening slightly. Remaining offshore, enough cold air was in place for it to deliver moderate, locally heavy snow to the interior northeast. Syracuse received their 2nd heaviest seasonal snowfall with 6.8 inches. The Albany metro area also saw >6 inches of snow. Higher elevation locales received much heftier totals; 9 inches of snow accumulated at Lake Desolate and 8.8 inches in Savoy, Massachusetts, for example. The most snowfall accumulated for this storm in the United States was 11 inches and occurred in 3 different locations; Mildford, New Hampshire, Quechee, Vermont and Norridgewock, Maine. Beforehand, light snowfall was experienced over a swath of the Midwest and 2 inches of snow accumulated at Chicago O'Hare International Airport.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://weather.com/storms/winter/news/2020-03-21-spring-snow-northeast-coastal-lows|title=Coastal Low Brought Snow and Rain to the Northeast as First Full Week of Spring Began|website=The Weather Channel|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Atlantic Canada also experienced impacts from the storm. In the Maritimes, wet snow fell ahead of moderate rainfall and mixed precipitation lessened snowfall totals. However, the island of Newfoundland experienced much heavier snow and stronger winds, producing near-blizzard conditions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theweathernetwork.com/ca/news/article/atlantic-maritimes-will-see-heavy-rain-blizzard-like-conditions-and-heavy-snow-for-newfoundland|title=Atlantic: Spring storm brings 20-40 cm of snow, blizzard-like conditions|last=Inc|first=Pelmorex Weather Networks|website=theweathernetwork.com|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> At Stanfield International Airport, 27.1&nbsp;cm of snow fell on March 24.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://climate.weather.gc.ca/climate_data/daily_data_e.html?StationID=50620|title=Daily Data Report for March 2020 - Climate - Environment and Climate Change Canada|last=Canada|first=Environment and Climate Change|date=2011-10-31|website=climate.weather.gc.ca|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> St. John's, Newfoundland saw 18.4&nbsp;cm of snow March 24\u201325 and winds there gusted to 91&nbsp;km/h.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://climate.weather.gc.ca/climate_data/daily_data_e.html?StationID=50089|title=Daily Data Report for March 2020 - Climate - Environment and Climate Change Canada|last=Canada|first=Environment and Climate Change|date=2011-10-31|website=climate.weather.gc.ca|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n=== Mid March High Plains blizzard ===\n\n[[File:Satellite image of water vapor over Northern rockies March 19, 2020.jpg|thumb|GOES 16 water vapor image of the Northern Rockies as the late season blizzard moves over.]]\n\nAn area of low pressure incoming from the Pacific drifted down the California coastline the week of March 16, bringing scattered thunderstorms with hail to Southern California.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NWSLosAngeles/status/1240028664340701184?s=19|title=Convective showers observed moving through LA County this afternoon. Have had reports of hail in some areas, including Woodland Hills. #SoCal #LArain #LAweatherpic.twitter.com/3DpBE1ipOH|last=Angeles|first=NWS Los|date=2020-03-17|website=@NWSLosAngeles|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> Continuous flow of moisture into California's mountains produced extreme snowfall totals during an otherwise unipressive winter there. 114 inches of snow fell at Homewood, 92\" at Sierra-at-Tahoe and 77\" at Kingvale, for example.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Brittany_Boyer/status/1240046206430183425?s=19|title=Incredible snow totals coming in from the multi-day event in California. They definitely needed it after the lack of snow prior to this #cawxpic.twitter.com/Jekzw2cn7L|last=Boyer|first=Brittany|date=2020-03-17|website=@Brittany_Boyer|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> Several rounds of severe thunderstorms occurred in Texas during this time period with the Dallas Metro being especially hit hard. Following >4 inches of rain, street flooding was reported.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/StormOfCorn/status/1240387696197074944?s=19|title=Twitter|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/BillWadell/status/1240282044300738561?s=19|title=Twitter|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The responsible low pressure area was observed to finally move ashore mid-day on the 18,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NWSSanDiego/status/1240346154853732352?s=19|title=Twitter NWS San Diego|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and the Colorado low began forming shortly afterward. In the Rocky Mountains and Great Plains, blizzard warnings were issued March 17 in anticipation of a very heavy snowfall to be accompanied by strong winds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://weather.com/storms/winter/news/2020-03-14-snow-wind-west-plains-upper-midwest-strong-system|title=Blizzard Warnings Issued in Wyoming and Nebraska as a Winter Storm Will Blast the Rockies, Plains|website=The Weather Channel|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> Snowfall totals in NWS Boulder's forecast region peak at 23 inches 4 miles NE of Nederland.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NWSBoulder/status/1240948876108062720?s=19|title=Snowfall totals from 8\"-18\" in the mountains and foothills with local amounts over 20\" in a few spots.  Along the I-25 Corridor 5\" to 10\" around Denver with up to 12\" over the Palmer Divide.  #cowxpic.twitter.com/XeKDuN7Ler|last=Boulder|first=N. W. S.|date=2020-03-20|website=@NWSBoulder|language=en|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> Combined with winds gusting >62&nbsp;mph,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NWSBoulder/status/1240777533832007680?s=19|title=List of peak wind reports: Akron airport checks in w/the strongest gust of 62 mph . Snow combined w/snow has created widespread blizzard conditions. Numerous locations across the northeast plains have been reporting whiteout or near whiteout conditions. #COwxpic.twitter.com/nMm74ud1jH|last=Boulder|first=N. W. S.|date=2020-03-19|website=@NWSBoulder|language=en|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> widespread blizzard conditions occurred.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NWSBoulder/status/1240776985011519489?s=19|title=Blizzard conditions exist over a large chunk of northeast Colorado (east of I-25 and over the Palmer Divide). More technical discussion attached in this tweet.  #COwxhttps://twitter.com/NWSSPC/status/1240771590301736960\u00a0\u2026|last=Boulder|first=N. W. S.|date=2020-03-19|website=@NWSBoulder|language=en|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> At Denver's airport over 1,000 flights or ~80% of air traffic that day, were cancelled.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://weather.com/storms/winter/news/2020-03-14-snow-wind-west-plains-upper-midwest-strong-system|title=Winter Storm Takes Aim on the Plains, Upper Midwest with Snow and Gusty Winds|website=The Weather Channel|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Include-NOAA}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.wpc.ncep.noaa.gov/storm_summaries/storm_summaries.shtml 2019 Storm Summaries] from the Weather Prediction Center\n\n{{portal|Weather}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{Succession box|before=[[2018\u201319 North American winter|2018\u201319]]|title=North American winters|years=2019\u201320|after=2020\u201321}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{United States winter storms}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2019-20 North American winter}}\n[[Category:2019 meteorology]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 North American winter| ]]\n[[Category:North American winters]]\n[[Category:2019 in North America|Winter]]\n", "name_user": "Orenburg1", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(ce)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2019%E2%80%9320_North_American_winter"}
{"title_page": "Atrioventricular block", "text_new": "{{Infobox medical condition|name=|image=|alt=|caption=}}\n\n'''Atrioventricular block''' ('''AV block''') is a type of [[heart block]] that occurs when the electrical signal traveling from the [[Atrium (heart)|atria]], or the upper chambers of the heart, to [[Ventricle (heart)|ventricles]], or the lower chambers of the heart, is impaired. Normally, the [[sinoatrial node]] (SA node) produces an electrical signal to control the heart rate. The signal travels from the SA node to the ventricles through the [[atrioventricular node]] (AV node). In an AV block, this electrical signal is either delayed or completely blocked. When the signal is completely blocked, the ventricles produce their own electrical signal to control the heart rate. The heart rate produced by the ventricles is much slower than that produced by the SA node.<ref name=\":3\">{{Citation|last=Kashou|first=Anthony H.|title=Atrioventricular Block|date=2019|url=http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK459147/|work=StatPearls|publisher=StatPearls Publishing|pmid=29083636|access-date=2019-11-12|last2=Goyal|first2=Amandeep|last3=Nguyen|first3=Tran|last4=Chhabra|first4=Lovely}}</ref>  \n\nSome AV blocks are benign, or normal, in certain people, such as in athletes or children. Other blocks are pathologic, or abnormal, and have several causes, including ischemia, infarction, fibrosis, and drugs.\n\n__TOC__\n== Anatomy ==\n[[File:Electrical conduction system of the heart cs.svg|thumb|Electrical conduction pathway of the heart.]]\n[[File:ECG Intervals.svg|thumb|Normal ECG tracing for a single contraction of the heart. ]]\nThe synchronized contraction of the heart occurs through a well coordinated [[Electrical conduction system of the heart|electrical signal pathway]]. The initial electrical signal originates from the SA node located in the upper portion of the right [[Atrium (heart)|atrium]]. The electrical signal then travels through both the right and left atrium, and causes the two atria to contract at the same time. This simultaneous contraction results in the [[P wave (electrocardiography)|P wave]] seen in an [[Electrocardiography|ECG]] tracing.\n\nThe electrical signal then travels to the [[atrioventricular node|AV node]] located on the lower portion of the [[interatrial septum]]. At the AV node there is a delay in the electrical signal, which allows the atria to contract and blood to flow from the atria to the ventricles. This delay accounts for the ECG period between the P wave and the [[QRS complex]], and creates the [[PR interval]].\n\nFrom the AV nodes, the electrical signal travels through [[Bundle of His]] and divides into the right bundle and left bundle, which are located within the [[interventricular septum]]. Finally, the electrical signal travels into the [[Purkinje fibers]]. The division of the signal into a right and left bundle and then into the Purkinje fibers allows for a simultaneous depolarization and contraction of the right and left ventricles. The contraction of the ventricles results in the QRS complex seen on an ECG tracing.[[File:ECG Principle fast.gif|thumb|ECG tracing in relation to normal depolarization and contraction of the heart. Red tracing indicates pathway of electrical depolarization. Blue tracing indicates resulting ECG tracing.]]After contraction, the ventricles must repolarize, or reset themselves, in order to allow for a second depolarization and contraction. The repolarization creates the [[T wave]] in the ECG tracing.<ref name=\"Lilly\">{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/pathophysiologyo00leon_1|title=Pathophysiology of Heart Disease|last=Lilly|first=Leonard|publisher=Lippincott Williams & Wilkins|year=2006|isbn=978-0-7817-6321-9|url-access=registration}}{{page needed|date=June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Cardiovascular physiology concepts|last=Klabunde, Richard E.|date=2012|publisher=Lippincott Williams & Wilkins/Wolters Kluwer|isbn=9781451113846|edition=2nd|location=Philadelphia, PA|oclc=712765593}}</ref>\n\n== Diagnosis ==\nAn [[Electrocardiography|electrocardiogram]], or ECG, is used to differentiate between the different types of AV block. In AV block, there is a disruption between the signal traveling from the atria to the ventricles. This results in abnormalities in the [[PR interval]], as well as the relationship between [[P wave (electrocardiography)|P waves]] and [[QRS complex|QRS complexes]] on the ECG tracing.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|title=Rapid interpretation of EKG's : an interactive course|last=Dubin, Dale, 1940-|date=2000|publisher=Cover Pub. Co|isbn=9780912912066|edition=6th|location=Tampa, Fla.|oclc=45498043}}</ref> If the patient is symptomatic from their suspected AV block, it is important that an ECG is also obtained while having symptoms. Physicians may also order a continuous ECG (i.e. [[Holter monitor]] or [[Implantable loop recorder|implanted cardiac monitor]]) to monitor the patient for symptoms and conduction abnormalities over a longer period of time, as AV blocks can be intermittent.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Kusumoto|first=Fred M.|last2=Schoenfeld|first2=Mark H.|last3=Barrett|first3=Coletta|last4=Edgerton|first4=James R.|last5=Ellenbogen|first5=Kenneth A.|last6=Gold|first6=Michael R.|last7=Goldschlager|first7=Nora F.|last8=Hamilton|first8=Robert M.|last9=Joglar|first9=Jos\u00e9 A.|last10=Kim|first10=Robert J.|last11=Lee|first11=Richard|date=2019-08-20|title=2018 ACC/AHA/HRS Guideline on the Evaluation and Management of Patients With Bradycardia and Cardiac Conduction Delay: A Report of the American College of Cardiology/American Heart Association Task Force on Clinical Practice Guidelines and the Heart Rhythm Society|journal=Circulation|volume=140|issue=8|pages=e382\u2013e482|doi=10.1161/CIR.0000000000000628|issn=1524-4539|pmid=30586772}}</ref> \n\nBecause some types of AV block can be associated with underlying [[structural heart disease]], patients may also undergo [[Echocardiography|echocardiogram]] to look at the heart and assess the function.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nLaboratory diagnosis for AV blocks include electrolyte, drug level and [[Cardiac marker|cardiac enzyme]] level tests.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|date=2017-01-06|title=Atrioventricular Block: Practice Essentials, Background, Pathophysiology|url=http://emedicine.medscape.com/article/151597-overview}}</ref> Based upon clinical suspicion, the physician may do lab tests to assess for reversible causes of AV block, such as [[hypothyroidism]], [[Rheumatology|rheumatologic disorders]], and infections (such as [[Lyme disease]]).<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== Classification ==\nThere are three types, or degrees, of AV block: (1) first-degree, (2) second-degree, and (3) third-degree, with third-degree being the most severe. An ECG is used to differentiate between the different types of AV block.\n[[File:Heart block.png|thumb|Representative electrocardiogram recordings of the different degrees of heart block.]]\n\n=== First-degree Atrioventricular Block ===\n[[First-degree atrioventricular block|First-degree AV block]] occurs when there is a delay, but but not disruption, as the electrical signal moves between the atrium and the ventricles through the AV node.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nhlbi.nih.gov/health/health-topics/topics/hb/types|title=Types of Heart Block - NHLBI, NIH|website=www.nhlbi.nih.gov|language=en|access-date=2017-03-22}}</ref>  On ECG, this is defined by a [[PR interval]] greater than 200 msec. Additionally, there are no dropped, or skipped, beats.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" />\n\n=== Second-degree Atrioventricular Block ===\n__TOC__\n\n[[Second-degree atrioventricular block|Second-degree AV block]] occurs when the electrical signal between the atria and ventricles is even more impaired than in a first-degree AV block. In a second-degree AV block, the impairment results in a failure to conduct an impulse, which causes a skipped beat. <ref name=\":2\">{{Citation|last=Mangi|first=Muhammad Asif|title=Atrioventricular Block Second-Degree|date=2019|url=http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482359/|work=StatPearls|publisher=StatPearls Publishing|pmid=29493981|access-date=2019-11-12|last2=Jones|first2=Wesley M.|last3=Napier|first3=Laura}}</ref>\n\n==== Mobitz I ====\nMobitz I is characterized by a progressive, yet, reversible block of the AV node. On ECG, this is defined by a progressive prolongation of the PR interval, with a resulting dropped beat (the PR interval gets longer and longer until a beat is finally dropped, or skipped).<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\nSome patients are asymptomatic; those who have symptoms respond to treatment effectively. There is low risk of a Mobitz I AV block leading to heart attack and complete heart block.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==== Mobitz II ====\nMobitz II is caused by a sudden, unexpected failure of the His-Purkinje cells to conduct the electrical impulse. On ECG, the PR interval is unchanged from beat to beat, but there is a sudden failure to conduct the signal to the ventricles, and a resulting random skipped beat.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nThe risks and possible effects of Mobitz II are much more severe than Mobitz I in that it can lead to severe heart attack.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wogan|first=J. M.|last2=Lowenstein|first2=S. R.|last3=Gordon|first3=G. S.|date=1993-01-01|title=Second-degree atrioventricular block: Mobitz type II|journal=The Journal of Emergency Medicine|volume=11|issue=1|pages=47\u201354|issn=0736-4679|pmid=8445186|doi=10.1016/0736-4679(93)90009-v}}</ref>\n\n=== Third-degree Atrioventricular Block ===\n[[Third-degree atrioventricular block|Third-degree AV block]] occurs when the signal between the atria and ventricles is completely blocked, and there is no communication between the two. None of the signals from the upper chambers make it to the lower chambers. On ECG, there is no relationship between P waves and QRS complexes, meaning the P waves and QRS complexes are not in a 1:1 ratio.\n\nThird-degree AV block is the most severe of the AV blocks. Persons suffering third-degree AV block need emergency treatment including but not limited to a [[Artificial cardiac pacemaker|pacemaker]].<ref name=\":6\">{{Citation|last=Knabben|first=Vinicius|title=Third-Degree Atrioventricular Block|date=2019|url=http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK545199/|work=StatPearls|publisher=StatPearls Publishing|pmid=31424783|access-date=2019-11-12|last2=Chhabra|first2=Lovely|last3=Slane|first3=Matthew}}</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n== Etiology ==\nThere are many causes of AV block, ranging from a [[Human variability|normal variant]] among people to the result of a [[Myocardial infarction|heart attack]].\n\nFirst-degree AV block and Mobitz I second-degree block are often thought to be just normal, benign, conditions in patients, and do not often result from a severe underlying condition.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nMobitz II second-degree block and third-degree AV block are not normal variants, and are associated with an underlying condition. Common causes include [[ischemia]] (lack of blood flow and oxygen to the heart muscle) or progressive [[fibrosis]] (excessive scaring) of the heart. It is also possible that high degree block can result after cardiac surgery during which the surgeon was in close proximity to the electrical conduction system and accidentally injured it. Reversible causes of Mobitz II and third-degree heart block include untreated [[Lyme disease]], [[hypothyroidism]], [[hyperkalemia]] (high levels of potassium), and drug toxicity. Drugs that slow the conduction of the electrical signal through AV node, such as [[Beta blocker|beta-blockers]], [[digoxin]], [[Calcium channel blocker|calcium channel blockers]], and [[amiodarone]], can cause heart block if they are taken in excessive amounts, or the levels in the blood get too high.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":6\" />\n\n== Management ==\nManagement is dependent upon the severity, or degree, of the blockage, the consistency of symptoms, as well as the cause of the AV block.\n\nPatients with [[First-degree atrioventricular block|first-degree AV block]] do not have any resulting severe or life-threatening symptoms, such as symptomatic [[bradycardia]] or [[hypotension]], and, thus, do not require treatment.<ref name=\":3\" /> \n\nSimilarly, patients with [[Second-degree atrioventricular block|second-degree Mobitz I AV block]] rarely develop life-threatening symptoms, and patients who are asymptomatic do not require treatment. However, in some cases, patients with Mobtz I block can develop life-threatening symptoms that requires intervention. These patients often respond well to [[atropine]], but make require temporary [[transcutaneous pacing]] or [[transvenous pacing]] until they are not longer symptomatic.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nPatients with [[Second-degree atrioventricular block|second-degree Mobitz II]] and [[Third-degree atrioventricular block|third-degree heart block]] are much more likely to have symptomatic [[bradycardia]] and hemodynamic instability, such as [[hypotension]]. Additionally, there is an increased risk of patients with Mobitz II heart block developing third-degree heart block. Therefore, these patients often require temporary pacing with [[Transcutaneous pacing|transcutaneous]] or [[transvenous pacing]] wires, and many will ultimately require a permanent implanted [[Artificial cardiac pacemaker|pacemaker]].<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":6\" /> \n\nIf the heart block is found to be caused by a reversible condition, such as Lyme disease, the underlying condition should first be treated. Often times, this will lead to resolution of the heart block and the associated symptoms.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n| DiseasesDB      = \n| ICD10           = {{ICD10|I|44|0|i|30}}-{{ICD10|I|44|3|i|30}}\n| ICD9            = {{ICD9|426.0}}-{{ICD9|426.1}}\n| ICDO            = \n| OMIM            = \n| MedlinePlus     = \n| eMedicineSubj   = med\n| eMedicineTopic  = 189\n| MeshID          = D054537\n| SNOMED CT       = 233917008\n}}\n\n*{{EMedicine|article|161919|Second-Degree Atrioventricular Block}}\n\n{{Circulatory system pathology}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Atrioventricular Block}}\n[[Category:Cardiac arrhythmia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox medical condition|name=|image=|alt=|caption=}}\n\n'''Atrioventricular block''' ('''AV block''') is a type of [[heart block]] that occurs when the electrical signal traveling from the [[Atrium (heart)|atria]], or the upper chambers of the heart, to [[Ventricle (heart)|ventricles]], or the lower chambers of the heart, is impaired. Normally, the [[sinoatrial node]] (SA node) produces an electrical signal to control the heart rate. The signal travels from the SA node to the ventricles through the [[atrioventricular node]] (AV node). In an AV block, this electrical signal is either delayed or completely blocked. When the signal is completely blocked, the ventricles produce their own electrical signal to control the heart rate. The heart rate produced by the ventricles is much slower than that produced by the SA node.<ref name=\":3\">{{Citation|last=Kashou|first=Anthony H.|title=Atrioventricular Block|date=2019|url=http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK459147/|work=StatPearls|publisher=StatPearls Publishing|pmid=29083636|access-date=2019-11-12|last2=Goyal|first2=Amandeep|last3=Nguyen|first3=Tran|last4=Chhabra|first4=Lovely}}</ref>  \n\nSome AV blocks are benign, or normal, in certain people, such as in athletes or children. Other blocks are pathologic, or abnormal, and have several causes, including ischemia, infarction, fibrosis, and drugs.\n\n__TOC__\n== Anatomy ==\n[[File:Electrical conduction system of the heart cs.svg|thumb|Electrical conduction pathway of the heart.]]\n[[File:ECG Intervals.svg|thumb|Normal ECG tracing for a single contraction of the heart. ]]\nThe synchronized contraction of the heart occurs through a well coordinated [[Electrical conduction system of the heart|electrical signal pathway]]. The initial electrical signal originates from the SA node located in the upper portion of the right [[Atrium (heart)|atrium]]. The electrical signal then travels through both the right and left atrium, and causes the two atria to contract at the same time. This simultaneous contraction results in the [[P wave (electrocardiography)|P wave]] seen in an [[Electrocardiography|ECG]] tracing.\n\nThe electrical signal then travels to the [[atrioventricular node|AV node]] located on the lower portion of the [[interatrial septum]]. At the AV node there is a delay in the electrical signal, which allows the atria to contract and blood to flow from the atria to the ventricles. This delay accounts for the ECG period between the P wave and the [[QRS complex]], and creates the [[PR interval]].\n\nFrom the AV nodes, the electrical signal travels through [[Bundle of His]] and divides into the right bundle and left bundle, which are located within the [[interventricular septum]]. Finally, the electrical signal travels into the [[Purkinje fibers]]. The division of the signal into a right and left bundle and then into the Purkinje fibers allows for a simultaneous depolarization and contraction of the right and left ventricles. The contraction of the ventricles results in the QRS complex seen on an ECG tracing.[[File:ECG Principle fast.gif|thumb|ECG tracing in relation to normal depolarization and contraction of the heart. Red tracing indicates pathway of electrical depolarization. Blue tracing indicates resulting ECG tracing.]]After contraction, the ventricles must repolarize, or reset themselves, in order to allow for a second depolarization and contraction. The repolarization creates the [[T wave]] in the ECG tracing.<ref name=\"Lilly\">{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/pathophysiologyo00leon_1|title=Pathophysiology of Heart Disease|last=Lilly|first=Leonard|publisher=Lippincott Williams & Wilkins|year=2006|isbn=978-0-7817-6321-9|url-access=registration}}{{page needed|date=June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Cardiovascular physiology concepts|last=Klabunde, Richard E.|date=2012|publisher=Lippincott Williams & Wilkins/Wolters Kluwer|isbn=9781451113846|edition=2nd|location=Philadelphia, PA|oclc=712765593}}</ref>\n\n== Diagnosis ==\nAn [[Electrocardiography|electrocardiogram]], or ECG, is used to differentiate between the different types of AV block. In AV block, there is a disruption between the signal traveling from the atria to the ventricles. This results in abnormalities in the [[PR interval]], as well as the relationship between [[P wave (electrocardiography)|P waves]] and [[QRS complex|QRS complexes]] on the ECG tracing.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|title=Rapid interpretation of EKG's : an interactive course|last=Dubin, Dale, 1940-|date=2000|publisher=Cover Pub. Co|isbn=9780912912066|edition=6th|location=Tampa, Fla.|oclc=45498043}}</ref> If the patient is symptomatic from their suspected AV block, it is important that an ECG is also obtained while having symptoms. Physicians may also order a continuous ECG (i.e. [[Holter monitor]] or [[Implantable loop recorder|implanted cardiac monitor]]) to monitor the patient for symptoms and conduction abnormalities over a longer period of time, as AV blocks can be intermittent.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Kusumoto|first=Fred M.|last2=Schoenfeld|first2=Mark H.|last3=Barrett|first3=Coletta|last4=Edgerton|first4=James R.|last5=Ellenbogen|first5=Kenneth A.|last6=Gold|first6=Michael R.|last7=Goldschlager|first7=Nora F.|last8=Hamilton|first8=Robert M.|last9=Joglar|first9=Jos\u00e9 A.|last10=Kim|first10=Robert J.|last11=Lee|first11=Richard|date=2019-08-20|title=2018 ACC/AHA/HRS Guideline on the Evaluation and Management of Patients With Bradycardia and Cardiac Conduction Delay: A Report of the American College of Cardiology/American Heart Association Task Force on Clinical Practice Guidelines and the Heart Rhythm Society|journal=Circulation|volume=140|issue=8|pages=e382\u2013e482|doi=10.1161/CIR.0000000000000628|issn=1524-4539|pmid=30586772}}</ref> \n\nBecause some types of AV block can be associated with underlying [[structural heart disease]], patients may also undergo [[Echocardiography|echocardiogram]] to look at the heart and assess the function.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nLaboratory diagnosis for AV blocks include electrolyte, drug level and [[Cardiac marker|cardiac enzyme]] level tests.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|date=2017-01-06|title=Atrioventricular Block: Practice Essentials, Background, Pathophysiology|url=http://emedicine.medscape.com/article/151597-overview}}</ref> Based upon clinical suspicion, the physician may do lab tests to assess for reversible causes of AV block, such as [[hypothyroidism]], [[Rheumatology|rheumatologic disorders]], and infections (such as [[Lyme disease]]).<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== Classification ==\nThere are three types, or degrees, of AV block: (1) first-degree, (2) second-degree, and (3) third-degree, with third-degree being the most severe. An ECG is used to differentiate between the different types of AV block.\n[[File:Heart block.png|thumb|Representative electrocardiogram recordings of the different degrees of heart block.]]\n\n=== First-degree Atrioventricular Block ===\n[[First-degree atrioventricular block|First-degree AV block]] occurs when there is a delay, but not disruption, as the electrical signal moves between the atrium and the ventricles through the AV node.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nhlbi.nih.gov/health/health-topics/topics/hb/types|title=Types of Heart Block - NHLBI, NIH|website=www.nhlbi.nih.gov|language=en|access-date=2017-03-22}}</ref>  On ECG, this is defined by a [[PR interval]] greater than 200 msec. Additionally, there are no dropped, or skipped, beats.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" />\n\n=== Second-degree Atrioventricular Block ===\n__TOC__\n\n[[Second-degree atrioventricular block|Second-degree AV block]] occurs when the electrical signal between the atria and ventricles is even more impaired than in a first-degree AV block. In a second-degree AV block, the impairment results in a failure to conduct an impulse, which causes a skipped beat. <ref name=\":2\">{{Citation|last=Mangi|first=Muhammad Asif|title=Atrioventricular Block Second-Degree|date=2019|url=http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482359/|work=StatPearls|publisher=StatPearls Publishing|pmid=29493981|access-date=2019-11-12|last2=Jones|first2=Wesley M.|last3=Napier|first3=Laura}}</ref>\n\n==== Mobitz I ====\nMobitz I is characterized by a progressive, yet, reversible block of the AV node. On ECG, this is defined by a progressive prolongation of the PR interval, with a resulting dropped beat (the PR interval gets longer and longer until a beat is finally dropped, or skipped).<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\nSome patients are asymptomatic; those who have symptoms respond to treatment effectively. There is low risk of a Mobitz I AV block leading to heart attack and complete heart block.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==== Mobitz II ====\nMobitz II is caused by a sudden, unexpected failure of the His-Purkinje cells to conduct the electrical impulse. On ECG, the PR interval is unchanged from beat to beat, but there is a sudden failure to conduct the signal to the ventricles, and a resulting random skipped beat.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nThe risks and possible effects of Mobitz II are much more severe than Mobitz I in that it can lead to severe heart attack.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wogan|first=J. M.|last2=Lowenstein|first2=S. R.|last3=Gordon|first3=G. S.|date=1993-01-01|title=Second-degree atrioventricular block: Mobitz type II|journal=The Journal of Emergency Medicine|volume=11|issue=1|pages=47\u201354|issn=0736-4679|pmid=8445186|doi=10.1016/0736-4679(93)90009-v}}</ref>\n\n=== Third-degree Atrioventricular Block ===\n[[Third-degree atrioventricular block|Third-degree AV block]] occurs when the signal between the atria and ventricles is completely blocked, and there is no communication between the two. None of the signals from the upper chambers make it to the lower chambers. On ECG, there is no relationship between P waves and QRS complexes, meaning the P waves and QRS complexes are not in a 1:1 ratio.\n\nThird-degree AV block is the most severe of the AV blocks. Persons suffering third-degree AV block need emergency treatment including but not limited to a [[Artificial cardiac pacemaker|pacemaker]].<ref name=\":6\">{{Citation|last=Knabben|first=Vinicius|title=Third-Degree Atrioventricular Block|date=2019|url=http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK545199/|work=StatPearls|publisher=StatPearls Publishing|pmid=31424783|access-date=2019-11-12|last2=Chhabra|first2=Lovely|last3=Slane|first3=Matthew}}</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n== Etiology ==\nThere are many causes of AV block, ranging from a [[Human variability|normal variant]] among people to the result of a [[Myocardial infarction|heart attack]].\n\nFirst-degree AV block and Mobitz I second-degree block are often thought to be just normal, benign, conditions in patients, and do not often result from a severe underlying condition.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nMobitz II second-degree block and third-degree AV block are not normal variants, and are associated with an underlying condition. Common causes include [[ischemia]] (lack of blood flow and oxygen to the heart muscle) or progressive [[fibrosis]] (excessive scaring) of the heart. It is also possible that high degree block can result after cardiac surgery during which the surgeon was in close proximity to the electrical conduction system and accidentally injured it. Reversible causes of Mobitz II and third-degree heart block include untreated [[Lyme disease]], [[hypothyroidism]], [[hyperkalemia]] (high levels of potassium), and drug toxicity. Drugs that slow the conduction of the electrical signal through AV node, such as [[Beta blocker|beta-blockers]], [[digoxin]], [[Calcium channel blocker|calcium channel blockers]], and [[amiodarone]], can cause heart block if they are taken in excessive amounts, or the levels in the blood get too high.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":6\" />\n\n== Management ==\nManagement is dependent upon the severity, or degree, of the blockage, the consistency of symptoms, as well as the cause of the AV block.\n\nPatients with [[First-degree atrioventricular block|first-degree AV block]] do not have any resulting severe or life-threatening symptoms, such as symptomatic [[bradycardia]] or [[hypotension]], and, thus, do not require treatment.<ref name=\":3\" /> \n\nSimilarly, patients with [[Second-degree atrioventricular block|second-degree Mobitz I AV block]] rarely develop life-threatening symptoms, and patients who are asymptomatic do not require treatment. However, in some cases, patients with Mobtz I block can develop life-threatening symptoms that requires intervention. These patients often respond well to [[atropine]], but make require temporary [[transcutaneous pacing]] or [[transvenous pacing]] until they are not longer symptomatic.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nPatients with [[Second-degree atrioventricular block|second-degree Mobitz II]] and [[Third-degree atrioventricular block|third-degree heart block]] are much more likely to have symptomatic [[bradycardia]] and hemodynamic instability, such as [[hypotension]]. Additionally, there is an increased risk of patients with Mobitz II heart block developing third-degree heart block. Therefore, these patients often require temporary pacing with [[Transcutaneous pacing|transcutaneous]] or [[transvenous pacing]] wires, and many will ultimately require a permanent implanted [[Artificial cardiac pacemaker|pacemaker]].<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":6\" /> \n\nIf the heart block is found to be caused by a reversible condition, such as Lyme disease, the underlying condition should first be treated. Often times, this will lead to resolution of the heart block and the associated symptoms.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n| DiseasesDB      = \n| ICD10           = {{ICD10|I|44|0|i|30}}-{{ICD10|I|44|3|i|30}}\n| ICD9            = {{ICD9|426.0}}-{{ICD9|426.1}}\n| ICDO            = \n| OMIM            = \n| MedlinePlus     = \n| eMedicineSubj   = med\n| eMedicineTopic  = 189\n| MeshID          = D054537\n| SNOMED CT       = 233917008\n}}\n\n*{{EMedicine|article|161919|Second-Degree Atrioventricular Block}}\n\n{{Circulatory system pathology}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Atrioventricular Block}}\n[[Category:Cardiac arrhythmia]]\n", "name_user": "2409:4061:210f:baf3::e4e:b0", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eFirst-degree Atrioventricular Block)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atrioventricular_block"}
